<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 10:26:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Jan. 18, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Daschle: Witnesses May Be Inevitable  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Conceding witnesses ``may be inevitable,''  
Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle signaled today that if Senate 
Republicans choose to have live testimony at President Clinton's 
impeachment trial Democrats might object to placing limits on who 
can be summoned. Daschle, D-S.D., said he continues to believe 
witnesses are unnecessary but acknowledged the political momentum 
was moving toward having some witnesses. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Marks King Holiday  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is spending the Martin  
Luther King holiday doing volunteer work and practicing his State 
of the Union speech. Clinton and Vice President Gore are visiting a 
Washington retirement home, joining volunteers from the AmeriCorps 
program in a service project. The president wants all Americans to 
volunteer in the spirit of the late civil rights leader. Later, 
Clinton will head back to the White House to practice his State of 
the Union speech, which he will deliver tomorrow night. 

</P>
<P>
	Heavy Fighting Reported in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serb forces today resumed attacks  
against ethnic Albanian rebels despite worldwide calls for an end 
to the violence. Serb and ethnic Albanian sources in Kosovo 
reported heavy fighting in the village of Racak, where the bodies 
of 45 ethnic Albanians were found over the weekend. NATO sent its 
two top generals to Belgrade to demand that Yugoslavia's president 
honor last October's cease-fire. Meanwhile, Yugoslav border guards 
refused to allow chief U.N. war crimes prosecutor Louise Arbour to 
enter the country to investigate the massacre. 

</P>
<P>
	Eight Die in Tennessee Tornadoes  
</P>
<P>
	JACKSON, Tenn. (AP) -- At least eight people died and scores of  
others were injured when a fierce storm system raced across 
Tennessee, destroying homes, uprooting trees and snapping power 
lines. A tornado touched down last night in Madison County, where 
six people were killed, official said. At least 71 people were 
hospitalized and 11 are in critical condition, a hospital 
spokeswoman said. Mobile homes, cars and trucks have been 
overturned, and power lines are down. 

</P>
<P>
	Pinochet Case Reopens in Britain  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The legal battle over the fate of Augusto Pinochet  
re-opened today, with a second House of Lords panel considering 
whether to clear the way for the former Chilean dictator's 
extradition to Spain to face criminal charges. Gen. Pinochet is 
fighting extradition on a warrant alleging crimes against humanity 
committed by his secret police during his 1973-to-1990 rule. 
Lawyers for Spain and Britain declared that immunity shouldn't 
protect any leader who commits torture. 

</P>
<P>
	Report Targets Flight Hazards  
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Federal officials have failed to keep a 1996  
promise to better control hazardous materials shipped by air on 
cargo and passenger planes, The Plain Dealer reported. The Federal 
Aviation Administration has issued fewer and smaller fines for 
violating rules, opting instead for more warning letters, the 
newspaper reported, citing agency records. The FAA said 1,133 
problems were reported in 1997. As of the end of August 1998, there 
were more than 1,600. An FAA spokeswoman said the number of 
reported violations has increased because of there are more staff 
members. 

</P>
<P>
	18th Century Bookcase Bags $8M  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A 18th-century combination bookcase-writing desk  
fetched $8.25 million at a Sotheby's sale, one of the highest 
prices ever paid for a piece of American furniture at auction. The 
bookcase, which dates to around 1745, was discovered last year in 
France, where it had been for nearly two centuries. It appears to 
be the most elaborate piece built by the famous Rhode Island 
cabinetmaker Christopher Townsend. 

</P>
<P>
	Cookes May Keep Role With Redskins  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The NFL would like the Washington Redskins to  
remain in John Kent Cooke's hand despite a firm deal to sell the 
team to a higher bidder, The Washington Post reported today. ``The 
continuity of this ownership would be a plus for the league,'' said 
Joe Browne, NFL senior vice president for communications and 
government affairs. The trustees of the late Jack Kent Cooke's 
estate have agreed to sell the team to a group headed by Howard 
Milstein for $800 million. However, the deal needs the approval of 
three-fourths of the NFL owners. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
