<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gibson, Sawyer Return to Morning TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- How will viewers receive Charlie, back from  
retirement as ``Good Morning America'' host? 
</P>
<P>
	Will morning become Diane?  
</P>
<P>
	Such were the questions facing these SWAT team co-anchors Monday  
morning, their first ``GMA'' appearance since being summoned to 
keep ABC's wakeup show afloat. 
</P>
<P>
	They signed on with all due camaraderie:  
</P>
<P>
	``Hi, I'm Diane Sawyer from Louisville, Ky. -- the new kid on the  
block.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``And I'm Charles Gibson, originally from Evanston, Ill. I hope  
you remember the old kid on the block.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, Sawyer isn't really a new kid on this turf: She had  
the same job at CBS in the early 1980s. Now, after rising to 
prime-time stardom, she, like Gibson, is playing the good soldier 
by returning to the morning-show trenches. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC's battle plan, such as it is: to recapture the warm, family  
feeling that once vaulted ``GMA'' to the top of the ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	One new family member was officially named on Monday's  
broadcast: ABC correspondent and former ``Good Morning 
America/Sunday'' co-host Antonio Mora as news anchor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to in effect take this program back to the future,''  
said Gibson, who ended an 11-year ``GMA'' stretch last May. He also 
spoke of his surprise at this unexpected assignment: ``A few weeks 
ago, you'd have knocked me over with a feather if you'd told me we 
were going to be here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What wasn't unexpected: emergency measures for the failing  
``GMA,'' especially after one recent week when CBS' ``This 
Morning'' slipped past it to claim second place for the only time 
... since Sawyer was an anchor. 
</P>
<P>
	``So how was it, old kid, getting up in the morning?'' Sawyer  
asked Gibson shortly after 7 a.m. EST. 
</P>
<P>
	``That alarm clock was a familiar sound this morning,'' he  
replied. ``I didn't actually throw a pillow at it, but I strongly 
considered it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Same at my house,'' Sawyer said. ``I got up all right, but it  
was not pretty, let me tell you that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just how long they'll be getting up at 4 a.m. remains unclear  
(especially since Sawyer will continue as a correspondent on the 
newsmagazine ``20/20''). But their stewardship in ``GMA's'' 
make-believe living room is meant to send a message that ABC is 
serious about getting the broadcast back on track. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, it might more aptly have been titled, ``Good  
Morning ... Anybody?'' Its glory days ended in 1995 as NBC's 
``Today'' caught fire and became the apparently unstoppable 
front-runner. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, ``GMA'' grew increasingly anemic. Longtime co-anchor  
Joan Lunden left in 1997, and replacement Lisa McRee and Gibson 
successor Kevin Newman could do nothing to boost the show's appeal. 
Now those co-anchors have been reassigned to other ABC News duties. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Gibson took a moment to thank the ousted pair.  
``Nobody has been more helpful to us as we begin the transition ... 
than they have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then, at the end of the broadcast, Sawyer faced Gibson.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have a comment to you before we go,'' she said, whereupon  
she pretended to collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	After much laughter, Gibson gently reminded her: ``We have  
another show tomorrow.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
