<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Furniture Sets Auction Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A rare 18th century bookcase sold for a record  
$8,250,500 Sunday at a Sotheby's sale, making it the second highest 
price ever paid for a piece of American furniture at an auction. 
</P>
<P>
	The bookcase, which dates to around 1745, was discovered in  
France last year. It had been there for nearly two centuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``The discovery of this piece has forced us to redefine the way  
we look at American furniture,'' said Leslie Keno, senior vice 
president and director of the American Furniture Department at 
Sotheby's. 
</P>
<P>
	The bookcase appears to be the most elaborate piece built by  
famous Newport cabinet maker Christopher Townsend. It is also the 
only known piece of American furniture with solid silver hardware 
on it signed by celebrated silversmith Samuel Casey, Keno said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bookcase was originally expected to fetch $500,000 to  
$800,000. But when the bidding began, at least five buyers drew the 
price into the millions. The final bid went to an anonymous buyer 
on the telephone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
