<CATEGORY> regional </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Momday's Canada News Briefs / Canada Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Part of the snow-covered roof of Olympic Stadium  
caved in Monday, injuring one person. 
</P>
<P>
	About 200 workers were setting up an auto show in the stadium at  
the time of the cave-in, which sent water and snow cascading over 
several display booths. 
</P>
<P>
	The stadium, home to the Montreal Expos baseball team, has been  
plagued with problems since it was built for the 1976 Summer 
Olympics. The original roof was designed to be retractable but 
didn't work. It had to replaced by synthetic material. 

</P>
<P>
                              *------	 

</P>
<P>
 *Newfoundlanders To Vote Feb. 9    	
</P>
<P>
	ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland (AP) -- Brian Tobin cut short his first  
term as Newfoundland premier Monday, calling an election for Feb. 
9. 
</P>
<P>
	Tobin said he needed a renewed mandate after just three years to  
continue brokering two major deals on the province's natural 
resources: a hydroelectric pact with Quebec to develop the Lower 
Churchill Falls and ongoing negotiations with Inco over development 
of the Voisey's Bay nickel play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whomever the people of the province select to complete these  
negotiations must be able to do so from a position of confidence 
and a position of strength,'' said Tobin, flanked by his caucus and 
cabinet. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics suggest Tobin is only hoping to squeeze in a second term  
before making a bid to seize the federal Liberal leadership. 
Heading for a second term now would certainly help clear a path to 
Prime Minister Jean Chretien's job whenever it becomes vacant. 
</P>
<P>
                            	  *------	 

</P>
<P>
 *British Columbia To Appeal Ruling Quashing Child Porn Law    	
</P>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- The provincial government  
said Monday it will appeal a judge's controversial ruling that 
possession of child pornography should not be a crime. 
</P>
<P>
	In a decision that angered many Canadians, Justice Duncan Shaw  
of British Columbia's Supreme Court ruled Friday that the federal 
law against possessing child pornography violated the 
freedom-of-expression clause of Canada's Charter of Rights. 
</P>
<P>
	British Columbia's attorney general, Ujjal Dosanjh, said Monday  
the province believed the law was valid and would seek expedited 
hearings in a bid to overturn Shaw's ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The case involved John Sharpe, 65, of Vancouver, who was charged  
with possessing child pornography after police raided his home in 
1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaw said there was no proof that possessing child pornography  
made people more inclined to sexually molest children. 
</P>
<P>
	His ruling, which is binding in British Columbia but not other  
provinces, upheld the existing laws against producing and 
distributing child pornography. 
</P>
<P>
	The British Columbia Civil Liberties Association said it agreed  
with Shaw that the law governing child pornography was too broad 
and needed to be changed. 
</P>
<P>
	But John Westwood, executive director of the association, said  
the changes should focus on whether real children are used in the 
pornography. Possession of writings and drawings involving 
fictional children should be legal, while possession of pornography 
involving real children should be illegal, Westwood said. 

</P>
<P>
                              *------	 

</P>
<P>
 *Heritage Department Looks for International Allies    	
</P>
<P>
	OTTAWA (AP) -- Canada will be looking overseas for allies in its  
dispute with the United States over safeguarding the domestic 
magazine industry, say sources within the Canadian Heritage 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The French government, during an official visit last month,  
expressed its support of Canada's measures to prevent U.S. 
magazines from overwhelming domestic publications. Buoyed by that 
vote of confidence, Heritage officials are looking for more moral 
support abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government has been embroiled in a trade feud with  
the United States over Canadian legislation that would make it 
illegal for foreign publishers to run advertising directed at the 
Canadian market. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials have threatened to retaliate with trade sanctions  
targeting such areas as textiles, forest products and steel if Bill 
C-55 isn't withdrawn or changed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
