<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 05:18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Lawmakers Join Lobbying Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Rep. Vic Fazio will continue to track  
legislation. He will still meet with friends on Capitol Hill. He 
will still be able to walk onto the House floor or enter the 
cloakroom, both off-limits to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	But Fazio will be doing all these things on behalf of corporate  
clients rather than his former constituents in California. 
</P>
<P>
	Fazio, a former member of the House Democratic leadership, is  
among several recently retired lawmakers who have gone straight 
from the Capitol to the influence business, as lobbyists or 
corporate advisers. Others include former Sens. Dan Coats, R-Ind.; 
Wendell Ford, D-Ky.; and Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.; and former Reps. 
Scott Klug, R-Wis.; Bill Paxon, R-N.Y.; and David Skaggs, D-Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have that most precious commodity -- instant access,''  
said Rogan Kersh, a Syracuse University political science 
professor. ``They don't have to spend a lot of time building 
relationships on the Hill. They have longstanding relationships.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though legally prohibited from formally lobbying Congress for a  
year, the ex-lawmakers bring high value to their clients. They can 
lobby the White House and federal agencies immediately. They can 
guide their clients through the congressional maze that all 
legislation must pass. And they can tell their clients what is 
going on in Congress, and about issues on the horizon they need to 
be concerned about. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're valued for is our ability to help people strategize  
on what they ought to do,'' said Fazio, one of two partners running 
the Washington office of Clark &AMP; Weinstock. The other is former 
Rep. Vin Weber, R-Minn., who began the D.C. operation after he 
retired in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a continuation of what I've been doing to a large  
degree. Instead of doing it for constituents, I'm now doing it for 
people who want to retain my services,'' Fazio said. 
</P>
<P>
	These lawmakers are following the well-worn path of their  
predecessors, entering the lobbying business where they can trade 
on their legislative contacts and knowledge of the government. 
</P>
<P>
	The nameplates on the doors of the capital's top firms are  
filled with ex-lawmakers. Former Senate Majority Leader Howard 
Baker, R-Tenn., heads a company whose clients include American 
Airlines, Federal Express and RJR Nabisco. Former Rep. Robert 
Walker, R-Pa., is president of the Wexler Group, whose clients 
include Anheuser-Busch, Burger King and Visa. 
</P>
<P>
	Paxon joined one of Washington's top law and lobbying firms --  
Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP; Feld -- which represents such blue-chip 
clients as Johnson &AMP; Johnson, the National Basketball Association, 
and Philip Morris. 
</P>
<P>
	``This firm represents some of the strongest and most enduring  
corporations in America,'' Paxon said. ``One of the things we can 
do is provide them counsel on how the system works.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Rep. Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y., set up his own company, and  
is sharing clients, employees and space with former Sen. Paul 
Laxalt, R-Nev., whose successful lobbying firm's clients include 
Lockheed Martin and the Nevada Resort Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any of these people coming into a firm bring Rolodexes,'' said  
Bill Hogan, director of investigative projects for the Center for 
Public Integrity, a watchdog group. ``With ex-members, they have a 
lot of people left on the Hill whose livelihoods they're 
responsible for. They brought them to Washington, they employed 
them, and those people owe them something.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 16:25:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Mayor Calls Garbage a Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani on Monday softened his  
assertion that other states should take New York City's garbage 
because their residents enjoy the city's cultural and business 
worlds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never said they were obligated to do it. We pay them for it,  
this is a business. This isn't a question of obligation,'' Giuliani 
told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	His remarks were a retreat from controversial statements last  
week, when he said since out-of-towners benefit from spending time 
in New York, there is a ``reciprocal relationship'' under which 
their home states should accept New York trash. 
</P>
<P>
	His remarks inflamed lawmakers in states like Virginia, where  
New York ships thousands of tons of waste for disposal. 
</P>
<P>
	A top aide said the mayor was not shifting his position.  
Cristyne Lategano, Giuliani's communications director, said the 
mayor's earlier statements had been misconstrued in the media and 
by Virginia politicians, and she emphasized Giuliani never used the 
word ``obligation'' in characterizing New York's relationship with 
other states. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't say, `You should take it,''' the mayor said Monday.  
``I said, `If you want to do business with us, we're willing to do 
business with you.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Virginia Gov. Jim Gilmore said he wanted to curb the  
dumping of out-of-state trash in Virginia, and ban barges from 
moving trash on state waterways. 
</P>
<P>
	He was reacting to word that Waste Management Inc., a  
trash-disposal company, wants to dump an additional 4,000 tons of 
New York City trash in Virginia every day. 
</P>
<P>
	The company already ships out 2,400 tons of New York City trash  
daily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 16:14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Flooded With Mail on Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The letter begins with praise from a supporter  
of Republican Sen. John Chafee of Rhode Island. What a fine 
governor he used to be! His record in the Senate -- ``splendid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far so good.  
</P>
<P>
	``Please be advised, however, that in the event that you should  
cast a vote in favor of removing William Jefferson Clinton ... I 
shall devote every breath in my body and every nickel in my pocket 
to the noble cause of ensuring your defeat the next time you run 
for re-election. Have a nice Christmas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate mailbags are bulging with everything except tepid  
indecision. The debate over President Clinton's fate may be 
engaging the nation only fitfully, but in the mail to senators it 
beats with a hearty pulse. 
</P>
<P>
	A self-described elderly Episcopalian woman from Port Angeles,  
Wash., writes crisply that Clinton has done a good job in office 
and should only be censured -- ``with a firm smack on those hands 
that fondled that filthy (expletive).'' 
</P>
<P>
	And then there is this Dear Senator letter: ``You, sir, are in  
the position to begin to repair the long-term damage to our way of 
life that the Clinton Presidency has caused.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They are coming in by the thousands, by regular mail, electronic  
mail and fax. True to the Senate's way of doing things -- a 
dignified step behind the times -- even the e-mail tends to get 
answered by old-fashioned paper, just as phone calls are usually 
answered by human beings. 
</P>
<P>
	The letters make liberal use of that fine democratic flourish,  
the exclamation mark. Whole words come capitalized or underlined. 
</P>
<P>
	They are brief and biting, appealing for an end to this  
``gruesome episode.'' Or, heartfelt musings on morality: ``It is 
true most people have made youthful indiscretions, but most of us 
have mended our ways by the time we became responsible adults.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They even offer advice on strategy: ``Why do you let Senator  
Byrd stand in front of the cameras and look like the only statesman 
in all of the Senate, when in reality he is OBVIOUSLY trying to 
pull Bill Clinton's fat out of the fire?'' Sen. Robert Byrd, 
D-W.Va., is widely recognized by his colleagues as keeper of the 
Senate's traditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Democratic Sen. John Edwards of North Carolina, a noted  
trial lawyer, is hearing from fellow attorneys who are parsing the 
legal implications of it all. ``Regular people kind of distill it 
to more basic things,'' said Josh Stein, chief of staff. ``Either, 
'We elected this man, this is a witch hunt,' or 'This man did 
something immoral''' and begone with him. 
</P>
<P>
	In many offices the flow rivals that seen before the Persian  
Gulf War or when groups have organized mass mailings for abortion 
votes -- war and abortion being sure-fire magnets for a Dear Senator 
missive. 
</P>
<P>
	Maine Republican Sen. Olympia Snowe may not have heard so much  
on any issue since she battled federal lobster restrictions, 
spokesman Dave Lackey said. Some 200 faxes alone await the staff 
each morning; more than 10,000 letters, e-mails and phone calls 
have come in since August. 
</P>
<P>
	In the office of Democratic Sen. John D. Rockefeller of West  
Virginia, aides find that when things are going sour for Clinton, 
the mail turns a bit in his favor. When he bounds back, more 
critics emerge. 
</P>
<P>
	That rings true for other senators, too. ``In the same way that  
ire drives mail, so does sympathy,'' said Chafee aide Nicholas 
Graham. 
</P>
<P>
	Many senators in both parties report a rough 50-50 split for and  
against Clinton's removal, making the mail more hostile to the 
president than the nation overall. 
</P>
<P>
	Few aides would allow a peek into the mail. But Republican  
moderates Chafee and Gorton offered a cross-section with names 
blocked out. 
</P>
<P>
	Senators naturally concentrate on mail from their states and  
make sure it all gets answered. On this issue, however, some 
senators say they are avoiding the mail count until the trial ends. 
</P>
<P>
	While people now can send the same e-mail to all 100 senators  
with a few clicks on a computer, that sort of correspondence 
doesn't land with much impact. 
</P>
<P>
	In Chafee's office, the stack of constituent mail that is  
solidly pro-Clinton is 2 inches thick. Same as the anti-Clinton 
mail. Mail wanting him censured but not removed, or something like 
that, is an inch thick. 
</P>
<P>
	``And here is our open-minded pile,'' said an aide, showing off  
the thinnest pickings of all. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, a few write merely to ask senators to do their best.  
</P>
<P>
	But even these letters can be tough. A constituent tells Sen.  
Slade Gorton, R-Wash.: ``A vote based on anything but your honest 
belief in his guilt or innocence would be a travesty and, assuming 
you have a conscience, would haunt you the rest of your life.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
