<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High-Scoring Bure Likes Fla. Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUNRISE, Fla. (AP) -- He has lost a half-season waiting for  
Vancouver to trade him. Still, Pavel Bure has no regrets about the 
holdout that encouraged the Canucks to send him to the Florida 
Panthers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an important thing in my life,'' the high-scoring  
``Russian Rocket'' said Monday from his home in Moscow. ``I put the 
goal in front of myself and I was always trying to reach that goal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes you have to make sacrifices, but you have to go all  
the way and never change your mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bure's perseverance paid off Sunday when the Canucks shipped him  
to Florida as part of a seven-player deal, giving the Panthers 
their first true offensive star. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know it's a young team,'' Bure said. ``I hope we can do  
something good for the franchise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 27-year-old Bure is a three-time 50-goal scorer and  
four-time all-star who has averaged slightly better than a point 
per game over his seven NHL seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	But a history of confrontations with former general manager Pat  
Quinn apparently soured Bure on the Canucks, leading him to demand 
a trade last summer and vow he would not return to Vancouver. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Bure threatened to sit out the Stanley Cup finals if  
the team didn't move to finalize a five-year contract that had been 
negotiated. When that was done, he said management didn't back him 
strongly enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years later, he made similar complaints after major knee  
surgery and back spasms limited him to just 23 goals in 63 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Bure would not discuss his relationship with the Canucks when  
asked Monday. But he disputed a statement by Canucks president 
Brian Burke that he had wearied of living in a fishbowl atmosphere 
in Vancouver. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's so funny. I never said that,'' Bure said. ``People were  
really nice to me there. I have a lot of friends there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since returning to Russia, Bure has been working out twice a day  
with CSKA Moscow, the former Red Army team where he spent his first 
four years as a professional. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the workouts have left him in good shape, but not  
playing in games became a grind. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was really frustrating for me,'' he said. ``I was missing  
hockey a lot and was missing the fans. It's really hard -- day after 
day going to practice and no games, not knowing when I'd start to 
play. I'm really happy it's over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bure was scheduled to fly Tuesday to New York, where he would  
join the Panthers for games Wednesday against the Islanders and 
Thursday against the Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	He was unsure about playing Wednesday, saying he wanted to meet  
with Panthers officials before reaching a decision. General manager 
Bryan Murray was guardedly optimistic. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to play this guy if he's flown 12 hours and  
says he's not ready to play,'' Murray said. ``But we're going to 
see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bure's new teammates greeted the news with enthusiasm. No  
Panther has scored more than 32 goals in a season during the team's 
six years, and Florida's 103 goals this year ranks 18th in the 
27-team league. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a go-to guy now,'' said Ray Whitney, whose 14 goals  
leads the team. ``None of us has to pretend to be a go-go-guy. Now 
we can go to the `Rocket.' This helps all of the guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rob Niedermayer called Bure's acquisition ``a dream come true.''  
</P>
<P>
	``To get a chance to play with a guy like that -- any centerman  
in the league would relish that,'' Niedermayer said. ``It certainly 
gets me excited.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
