<DOCNO> APW19990118.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 03:14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Shlomo Baum    	
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Shlomo Baum, a founder of a feared Israeli  
commando unit which carried out bloody reprisal raids in 
Jordanian-held territory in the 1950s, died Sunday. He was 70. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of death was not disclosed.  
</P>
<P>
	Baum, a noted right-wing activist, was one of the founders of  
the 101 unit, which was led by Ariel Sharon, now Israel's foreign 
minister. 

</P>
<P>
                           *David W. Belin    	
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- David W. Belin, a prominent Des Moines  
attorney who served as a top investigator to the Warren Commission, 
died Sunday from head injuries suffered in a fall in a Minnesota 
hotel room. He was 70. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1978, he and other lawyers founded the firm that would  
eventually become Belin Lamson McCormick Zumbach Flynn, where he 
served as a senior partner until his death. 
</P>
<P>
	Belin's public service included an appointment to serve as  
counsel to the Warren Commission, which investigated President John 
F. Kennedy's assassination. He wrote two books on the subject, 
including ``Final Disclosure'' in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Belin also served as executive director to the Rockefeller  
Commission, which investigated CIA activities within the United 
States. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Betty Evelyn Box    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Betty Evelyn Box, one of the most successful  
producers of British films in the post-World War II era, died 
Friday, according to news reports in London. She was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Box produced such hits as ``Doctor in the House,''  
``Miranda,'' ``Conspiracy of Hearts,'' and the Huggett family 
films. Most of her films were directed by Ralph Thomas, with whom 
she had a successful partnership for 24 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Box was part of a film dynasty. Her older brother Sydney Box  
and his wife, Muriel, were a noted screenwriter-director-producer 
team. In 1949, Betty Box married one of her brother's writers, 
Peter Rogers, who went on to be a producer in his own right. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in England, she started her career in 1942 by joining the  
company formed by her brother to produce training and propaganda 
films for the British government during World War II. 

</P>
<P>
                          *John Leon Collis    	
</P>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- Retired Rear Adm. John Leon Collis, a former  
commander of the Pearl Harbor Naval Shipyard, died Tuesday at 92. 
</P>
<P>
	Collis was an aide to Rear Adm. William Furlong on the admiral's  
flagship, USS Oglala, when it was sunk during the Japanese attack 
on Dec. 7, 1941. 
</P>
<P>
	He was commander of the Pearl Harbor shipyard from 1957 to 1958.  
</P>
<P>
	After his retirement, he worked for several years with the Bank  
of Hawaii, eventually becoming vice president of business services. 
</P>
<P>
	Collis also was the composer of Hawaiian songs, including ``On  
an Island With You,'' ``Hula Lullaby,'' and ``Flowered Isle.'' 

</P>
<P>
                            *Jack David    	
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Jack David, who founded the Blue Moon Tavern,  
Seattle's famous watering hole, died Jan. 10. He was 90. 
</P>
<P>
	David bought the University District tavern with his brother,  
Jim, in 1956. He took over his brother's interest three years 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he sold the place in 1966, David was credited for  
fostering the ambiance of the bar, which attracted beatniks, 
hippies, artists, victims of the 1950s Communist-baiting, and 
anti-Vietnam War activists -- along with countless college students 
and the occasional patron who just wanted a beer. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Arthur C. Fatt    	
</P>
<P>
	DELRAY BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Arthur C. Fatt, one of the founders of  
Grey Advertising and a former chief executive of the company, died 
Tuesday at his winter home here. He was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	With Lawrence Valenstein, Fatt started Grey in 1925 with a  
handful of employees in New York. By the time they retired, Grey 
had become one of the nation's leading advertising agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the accounts that Fatt brought to the company were Ford  
Motor Company, Proctor &AMP; Gamble and Chock Full O' Nuts. He wrote 
the well-known line for the Greyhound Lines bus company, ``Leave 
the driving to us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fatt became president and chief executive in 1956, succeeding  
his partner, who died in 1982. Fatt retired in 1976 after serving 
six years as founder-chairman. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Mario D. Grossi    	
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Mario D. Grossi, a radio physicist who helped  
develop the concept of the tethered satellite, died of vascular 
disease Monday. He was 74. 
</P>
<P>
	Grossi was born in Giuncarico, Italy, and moved to the United  
States in 1958. He was affiliated with the Harvard-Smithsonian 
Center for Astrophysics for many years. He also was a consulting 
scientist at defense contractor Raytheon Co. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1970s Grossi and his colleague, Giuseppe Colombo,  
developed the concept of the tethered satellite, a technique that 
connects satellites to spacecrafts and allows them to drag through 
the lower atmosphere. Tethered satellites have several 
applications, including the generation of electrical power in 
space. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Robert E. Hagan    	
</P>
<P>
	MADISON, Ohio (AP) -- Robert E. Hagan, a vice presidential  
campaign speechwriter and former state representative, died 
Saturday. He was 77 and had been diagnosed with cancer of the 
liver. 
</P>
<P>
	His political legacy includes two sons who also made their mark  
in politics -- former Cuyahoga County Commissioner Timothy F. Hagan 
of Olmsted Township and state Sen. Robert F. Hagan of Youngstown. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1981 Robert E. Hagan was elected to the Ohio House from the  
new 61st District and served until 1988. In an Ohio first, Hagan 
got to serve in the legislature with his son, Robert F., who was 
elected in 1986 from a district in Youngstown. 
</P>
<P>
	Hagan had a varied career: steelwork designer, television show  
host, county commissioner and speechwriter for Sargent Shriver who 
was the running mate for 1972 presidential candidate George 
McGovern. 
</P>
<P>
	Before going into politics, Hagan hosted his own TV variety show  
in Youngstown, appeared five times on the Mike Douglas show and 
wrote comedy material for entertainer Danny Thomas and other 
comics. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Monroe Karmin    	
</P>
<P>
	BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Monroe ``Bud'' Karmin, winner of a 1967  
Pulitzer Prize in journalism for stories investigating the 
influence on gambling of organized crime, died Friday after 
battling cancer. He was 69. 
</P>
<P>
	After college, service in the Air Force and studying at the  
Columbia University School of Journalism, Karmin joined The Wall 
Street Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	Karmin and colleague Stanley Penn won their Pulitzer Prize for  
an expose of Mafia dominance of gambling in the Bahamas. Karmin 
left the Journal in 1974 and worked for the Chicago Daily News, 
Knight Ridder and U.S. News and World Report before joining 
Bloomberg News as editor at large. 
</P>
<P>
	He was named to the Hall of Fame of the Washington chapter of  
the Society of Professional Journalists, was president of the 
National Press Club in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, a son, a daughter and five  
grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Doan Khue    	
</P>
<P>
	HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- Former Defense Minister Gen. Doan Khue, a  
candidate for president during a government reshuffle in late 1997, 
died Saturday after a lengthy battle with cancer. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	Khue was considered a conservative in the Communist Party  
Politburo and was given the Ho Chi Minh Medal, Vietnam's highest 
honor, this past week. 
</P>
<P>
	His death takes the number of Politburo members down to 17 from  
19 at the last party Central Committee plenum. 
</P>
<P>
	Khue began his career as an army officer in 1967. He worked his  
way up the ranks and became vice defense minister in 1980, the same 
year he joined the Politburo. He was named chief of staff in 1987 
and was promoted to four-star general in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	He became defense minister in 1991 and resigned in 1996 amid  
reports of ill health. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Frank Munk    	
</P>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- World Affairs Council of Oregon co-founder  
Frank Munk, a Czech immigrant who fled the Nazis and later taught 
at Reed College and Portland State, died Saturday. He was 97. 
</P>
<P>
	Munk also commented on global issues for KOIN-TV in the 1960s  
and frequently wrote about politics for The Oregonian and the 
former Oregon Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	Munk arrived in the Northwest in 1939, after learning his name  
was among those to be arrested after the Nazi occupation of his 
native Czechoslovakia. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1950s and '60s, Munk was an adviser on the Intellectual  
Cooperation for Radio-Free Europe in Munich, a senior research 
fellow at the Atlantic Institute in Paris and a visiting professor 
at the University of Zagreb, Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	He also taught in Belgium, California and Washington. He wrote  
several books, including the ``Legacy of Nazism,'' and a memoir, 
``My Century and My Many Lives.'' 

</P>
<P>
                           *Fredric Myrow    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Fredric Myrow, a director and composer of  
music for plays, films, orchestras but best known for his work with 
the Los Angeles Theater Center, died Thursday of a heart attack. He 
was 59. 
</P>
<P>
	The son of film composer and lyricist Josef Myrow, who wrote  
``You Make Me Feel So Young,'' the young Myrow began his career 
when Russian composer Dmitri Shostakovich heard his work at the 
University of Southern California during a tour in 1958. 
</P>
<P>
	This brought Myrow a commission from the Young Musicians  
Federation. His ``Symphonic Variations'' was played by the Debut 
Orchestra at the Hollywood Bowl when he was 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Myrow served for a year as composer in residence under Leonard  
Bernstein at the New York Philharmonic and taught at the State 
University of New York in Buffalo before returning to Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Myrow also composed scores for films such as ``Leo the Last,''  
``Soylent Green,'' ``Scarecrow,'' and the cult horror trilogy 
``Phantasm.'' 

</P>
<P>
                            *Walter Page    	
</P>
<P>
	COLD SPRING HARBOR, N.Y. (AP) -- Walter Page, a former J.P.  
Morgan and Company chairman, died Jan. 8. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	Page joined J.P. Morgan as a trainee in 1937, when the company  
was still a privately held bank. He retired in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Page was instrumental in establishing the company's  
international strategy, especially in the 1960s and 1970s. In the 
1970s he helped shape the plan that led to the creation of the 
Saudi International Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Page remained on the J.P. Morgan board. In 1985 he was named a  
member of a group advising top company managers. 

</P>
