<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Optimistic About Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- Highly dependent on foreign capital,  
Singapore's economy should lure an acceptable amount of overseas 
investment this year despite the lingering economic crisis and 
sobering figures for last year, a government official said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The investment climate in 1999 will continue to be  
challenging,'' said Economic Development Board chairman Philip Yeo 
in a statement. ``But I am confident that EDB will be able to 
attract investment commitments comparable to what we have achieved 
in 1998.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The government is ``cautiously optimistic about the overall  
outlook for the manufacturing and service sectors in 1999,'' he 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time in five years, foreign investment commitments  
in the country's key economic engine -- manufacturing -- shrank in 
1998, said the board, a division of the Ministry of Trade and 
Industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Amid a worsening regional economic crisis and the city-state's  
first recession in 13 years, new foreign manufacturing investment 
dropped 8.1 percent to 7.8 billion Singapore dollars ($4.7 billion) 
last year, compared to the record-high 8.5 billion Singapore 
dollars ($5.1 billion) in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining investment in Singapore's electronics sector, arguably  
the single most important industry in this small economy, was the 
main culprit, plunging 20 percent to 3.1 billion Singapore dollars 
($1.8 billion) because of a global slump and the regional crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	But the island state's manufacturing base as a whole did ``OK''  
in 1998, considering the economic disruptions last year, argued 
Yeo. The investment data ``are very respectable numbers compared to 
everyone around,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeo conceded that one notable failure was Singapore's inability  
to lure more new money into the electronics sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
