<DOCNO> APW19990118.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 22:25:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> President Will Address Americans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With a dissonant prelude, President Clinton is  
claiming the stage tonight for a State of the Union report he will 
address past his impeachment judges, to tell Americans he is 
performing their work, and well. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the on-the-job side of his case for acquittal in the  
Senate impeachment trial, which is convening to hear his defense 
lawyers, then adjourning to cross the Capitol to the House chamber 
to hear him. 
</P>
<P>
	Not without some complaints that he was going ahead with the  
ritual State of the Union report to a joint session of Congress, 
instead of waiting out the trial or sending his proposals in 
writing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quite frankly, I'd rather go to the dentist,'' Republican Sen.  
Phil Gramm of Texas said on ABC. But he'll go to the speech, as 
will other Republicans from the House prosecution team and Senate 
jury, to stand in applause, they said, for the office, not the man 
on trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois said in a letter to House  
members that the Republican Congress is receiving Clinton ``out of 
respect for the office of the presidency and for a desire to hear 
about the state of our nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That is the custom and precedent, now followed in unprecedented  
circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	Never has an impeached president gone before the House that  
accused him and the Senate trying him for his job to deliver his 
major annual message on the nation's affairs and his agenda for the 
future. Andrew Johnson, the only other president impeached, sent 
his messages in writing, as was the custom of his time. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's nationally televised address fits his strategy of  
fending off impeachment so that he will have a future in the White 
House for the balance of his term, ending two years from Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawyers argue the case. He argues that he's attending to the  
business of the American people, the job he was elected to do. 
</P>
<P>
	Both are on display, with an opening statement for the defense  
in the Senate in the afternoon, Clinton's address at night. He 
won't be brief, taking at least the 73 minutes of his 1998 State of 
the Union address, according to the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	How uncomfortable will he be standing in the chamber where he  
was impeached, talking to an audience that impeached him and is 
judging him? 
</P>
<P>
	``The president is always comfortable when he's dealing with the  
issues, dealing with issues that impact real people's lives, and 
dealing with how the government can help provide the tools that 
people need,'' spokesman Joe Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	All part of a White House buildup that included a reminder that  
Clinton has a higher job approval rating than Ronald Reagan or 
Dwight D. Eisenhower did at this point in their second terms. 
</P>
<P>
	It is in the 60 percent-plus range, at two-thirds approval in  
some polls. Clinton's ratings went up to those levels after his 
last State of the Union performance, delivered in the stress of the 
Monica Lewinsky investigation, which had just been disclosed. At 
that point he was denying the affair, dishonestly, as he finally 
had to confess. He didn't mention it that night. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the situation is even more strained. Gramm said it is like  
suspending a trial to have the accused hold a pep really in front 
of the jury. ``I think he believes that it will help him,'' Gramm 
said. ``Every time he gives a State of the Union address, it 
does.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As it does every president including, briefly, Richard Nixon  
during Watergate. It is a ritual occasion of state, convening 
Congress, the Cabinet, robed Supreme Court justices, diplomats, all 
come to hear the president. 
</P>
<P>
	Although not necessarily to heed him. Clinton made 30 proposals  
for congressional action a year ago; a program to begin hiring 
100,000 new schoolteachers was the only major one enacted on his 
terms. 
</P>
<P>
	He told Congress that night that it must save Social Security  
first, before spending the budget surplus on anything else, and he 
succeeded in holding that line against Republican tax cuts. Both 
his admonition and the GOP push for sharp tax reductions will be 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's congressional success rate in the year of scandal and  
ultimately impeachment was relatively weak. He is dealing with an 
opposition Congress, but other presidents did better in the same 
situation. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Congressional Quarterly, the administration won in  
51 percent of 154 votes on which it took a position, the sixth 
lowest in the 46 years since the publication began keeping track. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist  
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
