<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Cambodia Discuss Garment Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- A United States trade delegation  
began talks Monday with Cambodia's government about a surge of 
garment exports to the U.S. and working conditions in Cambodian 
textile factories that labor organizations describe as appalling. 
</P>
<P>
	A quota on Cambodia-made garments is expected to be set by the  
Office of the U.S. Trade Representative after the negotiations, a 
move that Cambodian Commerce Minister Cham Prasidh argued will 
depress his country's fastest-growing industry and cost local 
workers their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``More jobs are at stake, and the existing jobs as well. That's  
the problem,'' Cham Prasidh said during a break in the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry insiders say a quota is likely to be imposed by the  
U.S. to discourage the practice of garment manufacturers exporting 
clothes labeled ``Made in Cambodia'' which were actually 
manufactured in other Asian countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The garment industry has boomed in Cambodia in recent years  
after the U.S. granted the Southeast Asian nation trade privileges 
that lower or eliminate tariffs on many American-bound exports. 
</P>
<P>
	But international labor organizations say the industry has been  
built on the backs of underpaid and overworked workers exploited by 
factory owners who ignore Cambodia's new labor law with the help of 
corrupt government officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``Labor conditions in the garment factories in Cambodia are  
appalling,'' said Philip Robertson of the American Center for 
International Labor Solidarity, a branch of America's largest labor 
confederation, the AFL-CIO. 
</P>
<P>
	The AFL-CIO asked Washington last year to withdraw trade  
privileges from Cambodia because of severe labor rights abuses that 
Robertson said include substandard factory conditions, forced 
overtime, failure to pay overtime wages and sexual abuse of the 
predominantly female workers. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. trade privileges are linked by law to a country having  
adequate labor protection. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the U.S. delegation -- led by Donald Johnson, chief  
textile negotiator for the U.S. Trade Representative -- are 
scheduled to meet with local labor unions and visit factories 
during their visit. 
</P>
<P>
	Garment exports from Cambodia in 1998 have been estimated at  
$360 million, with two-thirds of the total going to the U.S. 
</P>
</TEXT>
