<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Said To Oppose Redskins Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The trustees of the Jack Kent Cooke estate  
have a record-setting deal to sell the Washington Redskins, but the 
National Football League isn't so sure that's a good idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Browne, NFL senior vice president for communications and  
government affairs, said the current ownership headed by Cooke's 
son, John, ``has a proven track record,'' The Washington Post 
reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The continuity of this ownership would be a plus for the  
league, if it can be accomplished to the satisfaction of the 
trustees,'' Browne said. 
</P>
<P>
	Trustees of the senior Cooke's estate have agreed to sell the  
team to a group headed by Howard Milstein for $800 million. 
However, the deal needs the approval of three-fourths of the NFL 
owners. 
</P>
<P>
	A sticking point is that NFL rules require that the lead owner  
of a team be capable of putting up at least 30 percent of the cost 
of its purchase out of personal funds -- possibly relying on 
partners or loans for the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Under those guidelines, John Kent Cooke was able to put together  
an offer of about $680 million, placing him third in the bidding. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the committee really wants to see what John Cooke's  
bid was,'' said Pat Bowlen, owner of the Denver Broncos and a 
member of the NFL's finance committee. ``He has been an owner in 
the National Football League for a long time, and I think there's 
some amount of sympathy for his position. 
</P>
<P>
	``But you know I don't think we could take it where we are  
saying that the foundation should take substantially less money 
from John Cooke. I think we want to have a closer look at the whole 
financial transaction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even though Jack Kent Cooke, who died in April 1997, was the  
actual owner of the team, Bowlen was referring to John Cooke's 
involvement in day-to-day operations of the team for 20 years. He 
represented the team at league meetings during that period. 
</P>
<P>
	Trustees of the elder Cooke's estate have taken the position  
that they are legally bound to obtain the highest possible price 
for the team and use most of the proceeds to set up a foundation as 
decreed by Cooke's will. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
