<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Social Security Accounts Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Proposals to replace Social Security's  
guaranteed benefits with new private retirement accounts are 
unacceptable, a group of congressional Democrats warned President 
Clinton in a letter. 
</P>
<P>
	But the lawmakers left an opening for an alternative: using the  
budget surplus to subsidize new 401(k)-style accounts that 
consumers could manage themselves as an addition to, but not a 
replacement for, Social Security benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	That is something being considered by administration officials  
advising Clinton on what to say in his State of the Union address 
Tuesday. Clinton wants to use the address to jump-start action in 
Congress to reform the nation's retirement program, but aides 
wouldn't say Monday just how explicit he would be. 
</P>
<P>
	Many congressional Democrats say they would prefer that Clinton  
avoid any explicit policy endorsements in his speech Tuesday, and 
pursue bipartisan talks instead. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a recent letter to Clinton, 44 House Democrats and  
independent Rep. Bernard Sanders of Vermont took one stand: ``We 
are firmly united on one principle -- any Social Security 
privatization plan must be rejected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letter was silent, however, on the possibility of  
supplemental accounts using government surpluses, rather than 
Social Security taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is something I would certainly consider,'' said Sanders,  
who composed the missive to Clinton along with Reps. Jerrold 
Nadler, D-N.Y., and Dennis Kucinich, D-Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Supplemental accounts wouldn't directly address the cash  
shortfall expected to face Social Security as the huge baby boom 
generation retires. But they could help Americans better prepare 
for retirement and soften the blow of any changes in Social 
Security that might be necessary, such as raising the eligibility 
age for benefits or limiting retirees' yearly cost-of-living 
raises. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials consider it one option that Clinton could broach  
without upsetting lawmakers of either political party. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have long advocated diverting some of the Social  
Security taxes now deducted from workers' paychecks into individual 
accounts Americans could invest in the stock market. Private 
investments would give most people a better return than Social 
Security does, they say. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Democrats, however, strongly oppose moving money out of  
Social Security into such accounts, warning of increasing financial 
risks to individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Retirement benefits should be guaranteed, not subjected to the  
whims of the stock market,'' the House Democrats said in their 
letter. 
</P>
<P>
	House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri has said he  
could support supplemental accounts, however, as long as taxes 
earmarked for Social Security's guaranteed benefits aren't touched. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders, meanwhile, have already introduced  
legislation to use surpluses to start new retirement accounts, 
holding open the possibility that some Social Security taxes could 
be transferred into them later. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am hopeful that this idea can be the basis for a bipartisan  
consensus solution to building a secure retirement for all 
Americans,'' said Senate Finance Committee Chairman William Roth, 
R-Del., in a separate letter to colleagues last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Roth's proposal would use budget surpluses to guarantee every  
worker a minimum of $250 a year for his account, with additional 
government payments to parallel what each person contributes in 
taxes to Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	Alternatively, some Democrats suggest Americans with the lowest  
incomes could get the largest government subsidies for their 
accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	In either case, the accounts would be similar to the 401(k)  
retirement savings plans many companies offer. Workers would 
probably be able to add their own money and choose from several 
government-supervised investment plans, such as stock and bond 
mutual funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
