<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices fell slightly in early trading  
Tuesday amid pessimism about Japan's prospects for an economic 
recovery. The dollar retreated against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average dipped 26.31 points, or 0.19 percent,  
to 13,778.75 points in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Monday, 
the average gained 66.20 points, or 0.48 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was trading at 113.83 yen, down 114.14 yen from late  
Monday in Tokyo and also below its level of 114.35 yen in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors continued to stay away from the stock market as few  
signs emerged that Japan was poised for an economic comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. markets were closed Monday for the Martin Luther King Jr.  
holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 0.49 points, negligible in percentage terms, 
to 1,075.30. The TOPIX closed up 5.85 points, or 0.55 percent, 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The foreign exchange market was quiet as investors took to the  
sidelines to see if finance officials would comment on currency 
movements at the opening of Japan's regular session of Parliament 
on Tuesday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the euro was quoted at 132.41 yen in Tokyo, up from  
132.34 yen late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.780  
percent from 1.725 percent Monday, driving its price down to 100.16 
yen from 100.60 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
