<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A Family Tale From Ireland to U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``A Couple of Blaguards'' is engaging  
autobiography, a family journey that travels from Ireland to 
America on equal amounts of blarney, sentiment and charm. 
</P>
<P>
	It helps that the storytellers are the McCourt brothers, Frank  
and Malachy, whose literary endeavors have become something of a 
cottage industry. Frank's award-winning ``Angela's Ashes'' and 
Malachy's ``A Monk Swimming'' are the foundations on which this 
genial stage memoir is built. 
</P>
<P>
	The informal evening, on view at off-Broadway's Triad features  
two ingratiating actors: the tall, lanky Mickey Kelly and the 
short, stout Shay Duffin. They play Frank and Malachy respectively, 
as well as other McCourt family members, scolding clerics, amorous 
girlfriends and assorted citizens of the two countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly's Frank is a quiet, unassuming man, yet possessed of a sly  
humor that gently works its way into the tale, particularly in the 
play's second half. 
</P>
<P>
	Act 1 is devoted to the lads' early years, their grim growing up  
in the town of Limerick where several siblings died young and their 
father retreated into an alcoholic haze. 
</P>
<P>
	Duffin offers a particularly affecting recollection of one  
little brother's funeral. The death and burial are described 
matter-of-factly, without placing any blame except on the poverty 
that trapped the entire family. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet most of the evening remains firmly on the side of a good  
laugh, even when the boys are dealing with the biggest influence of 
their early oppressed lives -- the Catholic Church. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank's remembrances of his First Communion are touching and  
funny, done by Kelly with an affectionate exasperation. They make a 
nice counterpoint to Duffin's impersonation of the young boy's 
grandmother. She is a zealous woman who raises the importance of 
her grandson's communion to the level of the Second Coming. 
</P>
<P>
	In Act 2, we get the McCourt migration to the United States, a  
story that doesn't resonate with as much emotion as the childhood 
experiences in Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the second half has its pleasures, much of it derived  
from Malachy's attempt to get a job, any job. 
</P>
<P>
	Duffin is a physical comedian as well as a verbal one. His  
Malachy captures the boisterous manner of a man who would never 
turn down the offer of a drink or the opportunity to tell a joke. 
The actor has a craggy face and a ruddy complexion that instantly 
define his heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	One other thing. Duffin and Kelly can sing -- blending their  
voices at the drop of a hat or a drop of whisky. 
</P>
<P>
	If the humor in ``A Couple of Blaguards'' occasionally gets a  
bit too broad for the small Triad stage, the pleasing personalities 
of its two stars put everything back in the proper perspective. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
