<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed sharply higher  
Monday, buoyed by last week's rally on Wall Street following 
Brazil's decision to float its currency. 
</P>
<P>
	In Singapore, the key index surged 3.2 percent as foreign  
investors pushed up large-capitalization stocks. The Straits Times 
Index rose 47.29 to 1,547.10. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealers said that institutional investors were returning to the  
Singapore market because they were confident the Brazilian 
financial crisis won't have a significant impact on the Asian 
region. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index in Hong Kong rose 255.14 points,  
or 2.5 percent, closing at 10,402.54. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said share prices climbed amid receding fears about the  
impact of the financial turmoil in Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil triggered a worldwide market rout on Wednesday after its  
central bank chief resigned and his successor devalued the 
country's currency. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the Brazilian government decided to allow its  
currency, the real, to float freely against the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision sent share prices soaring in New York on Friday,  
with the Dow Jones Industrial Average rising by 219.62 points to 
close at 9,340.55. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippine shares rebounded strongly from their sharp losses  
last week as worries over the situation in Brazil eased. 
</P>
<P>
	The Philippine Stock Exchange Index of 30 selected companies  
soared 89.35 points, or 4.4 percent, to 2,130.90. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose  
66.20 points, or 0.48 percent, closing at 13,805.06. On Thursday, 
the average gained 335.26 points, or 2.50 percent. Financial 
markets in Japan were closed Friday for a national holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said investors were heartened by a recovery in U.S. and  
other world stock exchanges on Friday following moves by the 
Brazilian government to stabilize its economy, Latin America's 
largest. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the dollar was quoted at 114.14 yen in late afternoon  
trading, up 0.68 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo and little changed 
from its level late Friday in New York of 114.13 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The markets were closed in Malaysia and Indonesia for holidays.  
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed sharply higher as  
stronger global financial markets buoyed the local market. The 
benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 46.75 points, or 2.2 percent, 
to 2,159.86. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian stock market closed moderately higher,  
helped by a strong performance in the banking and finance sector. 
The All Ordinaries Index rose 21.1 points, or 0.75 percent, to 
2,830.4. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed lower as investors took profits  
following recent gains. The market's key Weighted Stock Price Index 
fell 106.05 points, or 1.6 percent, to 6,377.25. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed higher amid an easing of concerns  
over Brazil's financial turmoil. The Korea Composite Stock Price 
Index rose 7.95 points, or 1.2 percent, to 622.52. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed higher. The Thailand SET Index  
rose 5.79 points, or 1.5 percent, to 387.61 (381.82) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
