<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report Targets Flight Hazards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Federal officials have failed to keep a 1996  
promise to better control hazardous materials shipped by air on 
cargo and passenger planes, The Plain Dealer reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration has issued fewer and smaller  
fines for violating rules, opting instead for more warning letters, 
the newspaper reported Sunday, citing agency records. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA said 1,133 problems were reported in 1997. As of the end  
of August 1998, there were more than 1,600. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of reported violations has increased because of  
agency improvements, including increasing the number of staff 
members, said FAA spokeswoman Diane Spitaliere on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fines, warning letters and news releases help deter more  
problems, she said. ``The airlines are much more conscious of this 
now because they know we're out there,'' Spitaliere said. 
</P>
<P>
	Airlines have different rules about what is allowed on board.  
Materials that could be hazardous include paints, flammable 
liquids, adhesives and perfumes. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper reported that passengers and baggage handlers  
found pesticides, engine cleaner, kerosene lamp fuel and a chain 
saw in overhead compartments. Compressed gas cylinders, fireworks 
and leaking contact cement have been found in cargo holds. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA promised to improve oversight of hazardous material  
after a ValuJet plane crashed in the Everglades in 1996, killing 
110 people. The National Transportation Safety Board ruled that the 
FAA, ValuJet and a contractor shared blame for the crash, caused by 
a fire in a cargo hold triggered by improperly packaged oxygen 
generators. 
</P>
<P>
	After the accident, Congress approved spending $10.5 million to  
hire 130 new employees to improve training and aircraft 
inspections. 
</P>
<P>
	An audit in March by the Office of Inspector General said the  
FAA and Transportation Department had fallen up to 18 months behind 
schedule to implement many changes promised in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA still has not required that airlines train employees to  
detect and prevent hazardous materials from making it aboard 
airplanes, even though 60 percent of the cargo shipped by air is 
aboard passenger airlines, the newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA does not know how many of the violations are serious  
because the agency has no method for ranking them, said Gerald 
Dillingham, associate director of transportation issues for the 
General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Spitaliere said most inspectors report problems they find.  
</P>
<P>
	She also disputed the newspaper's contention that FAA  
enforcement is inconsistent. Spitaliere said reports from different 
parts of the country vary because some areas handle more cargo than 
others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
