<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain To Focus on Calif. in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- As he prepares a run for the  
presidency, Sen. John McCain of Arizona is pinning his hopes on 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican war hero, who filed candidacy papers Dec. 30,  
believes that Californians will respond to his Ronald Reagan 
conservatism, maverick image and largely scandal-free past. 
</P>
<P>
	The state has more delegates in the nominating process than any  
other, and last year moved its primary up to the earliest possible 
date, March 7 -- which could give it extra clout. 
</P>
<P>
	``For someone like me who is Western, then obviously that adds  
importance to it,'' he said, citing his understanding of issues 
that loom large in both Arizona and California -- including water, 
land use and the environment. 
</P>
<P>
	``People in the West are much more appreciative of those who act  
independently, according to their own judgments,'' he said Friday 
in a phone interview from Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, 62, has a reputation for such independence. In recent  
years, he has heightened his visibility by taking on big tobacco 
and the national campaign-finance system, both of which had 
defenders in his own party. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the GOP-controlled Senate killed his campaign-finance  
bill and his proposal to raise cigarette prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Californians have passed ballot initiatives in the last  
two elections that were meant to revamp campaign finance and 
increase the cost of cigarettes. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain also has been a fierce defender of American Indian  
self-governance and gambling. Indians emerged last year as a group 
with enormous political clout in California, pouring some $68 
million into their campaign for a ballot measure that expanded 
tribal gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, who spoke during a recess from President Clinton's  
impeachment trial, said he would not use the Clinton-Monica 
Lewinsky affair as a campaign issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't intend to discuss the Clinton scandal,'' McCain said.  
``I've always believed the scandal in Washington was not Monica. It 
was the abuse of the institutions of government by Clinton and 
Gore. The scandals are absolutely disgraceful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain has had his own brush with scandal. He and four other  
senators were rebuked by the Senate Ethics Committee for 
intervening with regulators on behalf of Charles H. Keating during 
the collapse of the Arizona financier's Southern California-based 
Lincoln Savings &AMP; Loan. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain would rather remind California voters of his links to  
Reagan, a two-time California governor who carried the state in the 
1980 and 1984 presidential contests. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain was a Navy pilot who was shot down in Vietnam, captured  
and tortured for more than five years before returning to the 
United States in 1973. He won a House seat representing Arizona 
nine years later as a Reagan Republican. In 1986, during Reagan's 
second term, he won his Senate race. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's one of my great heroes,'' McCain said.  
</P>
<P>
	Already McCain is surrounding himself with advisers who are  
Reagan associates: Ken Duberstein, who was Reagan's chief of staff, 
is ``on the team''; advisers include Mike Deaver, the master 
image-maker at the Reagan White House, and Stu Spencer, who managed 
Reagan's first campaign for governor and later advised the 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, who plans to be among the aspiring candidates addressing  
next month's California Republican Party convention, says he 
already has a deep well of support in the state party. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was adopted several years ago by the CRP as their senator,''  
he joked, referring to the lock that Democratic Sens. Barbara Boxer 
and Dianne Feinstein have had on California for the past few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
