<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 01:53:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll on King Assassination Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Only about one in eight Americans believe James  
Earl Ray was solely responsible for the assassination of the Rev. 
Martin Luther King Jr., according to a poll published today. 
</P>
<P>
	A telephone survey by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution found  
that while 12 percent believe Ray alone was to blame for the civil 
rights leader's death, 46 percent suspect that Ray was aided by 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	Roughly one-quarter of the respondents believe that people other  
than Ray were responsible for the 1968 murder. About one-fifth of 
the respondents said they didn't know who was responsible. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray pleaded guilty in 1969 to killing King, but recanted within  
days. He maintained his innocence until his death last year at age 
70 while serving a 99-year sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll of 818 Southern residents and 394 non-Southerners was  
conducted from Sept. 23 to Nov. 15, and has a margin of error of 
plus or minus 5 percentage points. Generally, there was little 
difference in the responses given by Southerners and 
non-Southerners. 
</P>
<P>
	Family members of the slain civil rights leader believe Ray is  
innocent and supported his efforts in recent years to obtain the 
trial that he circumvented with his plea. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very happy that other people share our conclusions that  
there were others involved,'' said Dexter Scott King, son of the 
slain civil rights leader. ``It's encouraging because... there was 
never a full-blown trial to get to the bottom of everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the Kings' instigation, the Justice Department opened a  
limited probe last year to investigate some aspects of the killing. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll found that a majority of respondents -- 55 percent --  
believe no further investigation is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time to stop dredging all this stuff up,'' said poll  
respondent Amy Cecil, 49, a nursing home employee from Lexington, 
N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, 35 percent of poll respondents and 50 percent of black  
respondents said they would like to see more federal investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are too many questions,'' said Beverly Niemzak, 40, a  
homemaker in Gadsden, Ala. ``I don't know that the investigation 
was ever taken far enough. ...There are too many things that just 
shout that it wasn't done the right way. 
</P>
<P>
	Blacks in particular are likely to believe people other than Ray  
were involved. 
</P>
<P>
	In the South, 42 percent of blacks said they believed Ray was  
not involved in the slaying. Outside the South, 46 percent of 
blacks believed Ray was innocent of the crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 18:12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Says Economy Mired in Slump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Despite mild improvements Japan's economy remains  
mired in a prolonged slump, the government said Tuesday in a 
closely watched monthly report. 
</P>
<P>
	While items such as consumer spending for certain items and the  
number of bankruptcies have shown improvement, employment and 
corporate capital investment deteriorated, leaving the overall 
state of the economy ``very severe,'' the Economic Planning Agency 
said in its December report. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency's assessment was unchanged from the previous month.  
</P>
<P>
	Japan is stuck in its worst recession since World War II, as  
debt-ridden financial institutions scale back on lending, starving 
companies of cash. Unemployment is at a record high. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said the yen's recent sharp rise against the dollar  
and the surge in long-term Japanese interest rates last month 
contributed to uncertainties about the outlook for the overall 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are starting to see several scattered signs of improvement,  
but we still can't say they are starting a bigger trend,'' said 
Takashi Omori, director of the national economic division at the 
agency's research bureau. 
</P>
<P>
	The assessment for employment was downgraded, with the agency  
saying the employment situation is ``getting even more severe.'' 
The jobless rate hit an all-time high of 4.4 percent in November, 
the latest month for which statistics were available. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency's overall assessment for personal consumption as  
``sluggish overall'' was unchanged from last month. It said that 
category was weighed down by falling wages, adding that 
``consumers' purse strings remain tightened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But it said demand for certain ``reasonably priced'' items, such  
as home appliances and mini-vehicles, has stopped declining. 
Bankruptcies, which had been at record highs, also declined in 
November, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 09:46:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Prepares Annual Address </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Conceding that families with only one  
breadwinner need tax relief too, President Clinton is proposing a 
credit to offset costs borne by parents who choose to stay home and 
care for their children. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's budget proposal for fiscal 2000 will include a tax  
credit of up to $500 per child age 1 or younger, according to a 
White House official who spoke Sunday on condition of anonymity. It 
is expected to cost $1.3 billion over five years, allowing for an 
average tax credit of $178, the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is expected to outline the proposal in his State of the  
Union address Tuesday night before a joint session of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal is part of a larger child care package that seeks a  
total of $18 billion over five years to aid working poor and 
middle-class families. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the president put forth a $22 billion child care  
package that was tied to revenue from the proposed tobacco 
settlement. But the proposal went nowhere because Republicans said 
it failed to address parents who do not work outside the home. 
</P>
<P>
	With this plan, the White House hopes to deflate that argument  
and give GOP leaders what amounts to a political dare. 
</P>
<P>
	The child care package is the latest policy item to be previewed  
from Clinton's speech. Others have included plans to reduce 
violence against children, improve military readiness and food 
safety and meet Americans' long-term health care needs. But the 
White House has revealed little about how the president would 
ensure that Social Security remains solvent as the huge baby boom 
generation retires. 
</P>
<P>
	In yet another proposal expected to be in the speech, Health and  
Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala told The Washington Post in 
an interview in today's editions that Clinton will call for $1 
billion over five years to improve health care for many of the 
nation's 32 million uninsured adults. The money would be used to 
encourage community clinics and hospitals to work together to keep 
track of patients and make sure they get needed treatment. The 
administration has now made health proposals that would cost about 
$10 billion over five years. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials said today the president also plans to  
propose restructuring $20 billion in federal education money to 
require school districts to meet standards such as ending social 
promotions, better informing parents of school performance, 
enhancing teacher training and improving classroom discipline. If 
they do not, they could risk losing some or all their federal 
assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton spent much of Sunday practicing his delivery of the  
State of the Union address. He rehearsed into the night, testing 
and retesting themes that are likely to resonate with members of 
Congress and the 70 million to 80 million Americans expected to 
watch on television. 
</P>
<P>
	The president donned a suit jacket and tie and rehearsed before  
about 20 aides, who tried to listen with the ears of lawmakers who 
voted to impeach him so the White House can try to anticipate 
reactions that can either help or hurt the president. ``The dynamic 
in the room matters,'' one senior official said privately. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton stood at a podium, his remarks queued on prompting  
devices; nearby were two computer terminals for making revisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're beyond drafts now,'' said White House spokesman Joe  
Lockhart. ``There were three or four real drafts, and there were 
considerable changes from draft to draft. They're in the stage now 
that they're just throwing out pages and writing in the margins.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the Sunday television talk shows, some lawmakers renewed a  
plea for Clinton to skip the speech, noting they won't find it easy 
to segue from trying his impeachment case in the Senate chamber a 
few hours earlier. Still, they said they planned to be on hand to 
hear it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quite frankly, I'd rather go to the dentist. But I intend to  
go,'' Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said on ABC's ``This Week.'' ``I'm 
going to applaud. I'm going to be respectful. Despite all the 
political rhetoric, I don't hate Bill Clinton.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter Sunday, Republican leaders told the president they  
will be listening closely to what he says about tax cuts, defense 
spending, expanding local control over education dollars and 
overhauling Social Security ``without tax increases or benefit 
cuts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and House Speaker  
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., invited Clinton to submit a Social Security 
proposal before March 1, the date they said they have scheduled a 
joint House-Senate committee meeting to receive it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although your presentation of the traditional State of the  
Union address will occur this year under extraordinary 
circumstances, we should not permit those circumstances to distract 
us from the nation's legislative agenda,'' Lott and Hastert wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed child care credit would benefit an estimated 1.7  
million families. That would mean a family earning $30,000 per year 
with one working parent would be able to claim $500 in child care 
expenses, rather than the $250 they are allowed under current law. 
The amount of the credit declines as family income increases. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration official declined to reveal how the tax  
credit would be funded, other than to say it would be financed 
through ``a host of options'' being exercised in Clinton's budget 
and would not be tied to a tobacco tax increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's tax credit for stay-at-home parents is patterned after  
one offered last year by Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., the 
official said. The rest of the $18 billion package incorporates 
elements of a proposal by Sens. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and John 
Chafee, R-R.I. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chafee-Hatch bill called for $15 billion to $16 billion over  
five years, and would have expanded the dependent-care tax credit 
for stay-at-home parents up to $900 per year per family. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
