<HEADLINE> Children's Bureau Physician Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Katherine Bain, a pediatrician who served with  
the U.S. Children's Bureau for 32 years before retiring in 1972, 
died of cancer Jan. 10 at the Washington Home Hospice. 
</P>
<P>
	She was 101.  
</P>
<P>
	A 1925 graduate of Washington University medical school in her  
native St. Louis, she led a number of government programs 
addressing such issues as dangerous household chemicals, the need 
for child-proof medicine caps and the need to promote 
breast-feeding of newborns in hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	She received a Surgeon General's Medallion in 1986 for her  
pioneering advocacy of intensive-care units for infants and also 
was honored by the American academy of Pediatrics. 
</P>
<P>
	She is survived by a number of nieces and nephews.  
</P>
</TEXT>
