<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Knicks To Acquire Latrell Sprewell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- One of the NBA's baddest boys may be heading to  
the New York Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Latrell Sprewell, whose attack on his coach last season led to  
one of the harshest penalties in league history, is expected to be 
traded to the Knicks as soon as the lockout ends, two league 
sources told The Associated Press on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks apparently emerged the winning bidder after Golden  
State Warriors general manager Garry St. Jean told all interested 
teams to make their best offers by 4 p.m. EST Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately clear who the Knicks would send to the  
Warriors. New York was believed to be offering forward Chris Mills 
and guard Chris Childs, with Golden State general manager Garry St. 
Jean asking for John Starks. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal would work under salary cap guidelines if any two of  
the three Knicks were packaged together. Sprewell was to make $8.3 
million this season, while Childs makes $3.64 million, Mills makes 
$3.6 million and Starks makes $4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Two NBA sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the  
Knicks beat out the Indiana Pacers and Miami Heat in the bidding 
for the three-time All-Star, one of the most talented shooting 
guards in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Knicks, Sprewell would play alongside the Knicks' other  
shooting guard, Allan Houston, in a three-guard formation much like 
New York used for most of last season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks, Heat and Pacers had been known to be the leading  
bidders in the Sprewell sweepstakes, and the AP learned that a 
complicated four-team trade involving Golden State, Miami, 
Cleveland and Boston also was discussed. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell would have gone to the Heat along with Bimbo Coles and  
Clarence Weatherspoon, with Golden State getting Brent Barry, Dan 
Majerle and Bobby Sura. Boston would have received Jamal Mashburn 
and Vitaly Potapenko, and Cleveland would have received Paul Pierce 
and Andrew Declercq. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the league's most notorious choke artist -- as Sprewell  
has come to be known for obvious reasons -- will be playing in the 
harsh spotlight of the nation's media capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell has averaged 20.1 points in his six-year career,  
including a career-high 24.2 points in 1996-97. 
</P>
<P>
	He was suspended for one year and had his contract terminated by  
the Warriors for his attack on coach P.J. Carlesimo in December 
1997, although an arbitrator reduced the suspension to 68 games and 
reinstated the final two years of his contract after a hearing last 
February. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell has not played since the incident, and spent most of  
the summer under house arrest after pleading no contest to a 
reckless driving charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell will make $9 million in the 1999-2000 season, but more  
importantly will elevate the Knicks to the status of top Eastern 
Conference contender for the upcoming season. 
</P>
<P>
	No deals can be finalized until the lockout settlement is put  
into writing, which won't happen until Tuesday night at the 
earliest. If the deal is finalized Tuesday night, trades and free 
agent signings will begin Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
