<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Format Aims To Give Track Leg Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In an attempt to lift track and field from the  
doldrums in the United States, the head of the sport's national 
body has devised a program aimed at giving American athletes more 
money and television exposure. 
</P>
<P>
	Craig Masback, chief executive officer of USA Track &AMP; Field  
since July 1997, said Monday his organization has signed several 
prominent athletes to compete in domestic meets that would provide 
them with ``meaningful appearances for competition and 
opportunities to make money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Masback, speaking before the New York Track Writers, said there  
would be four indoor meets next month, including the USA 
Championships, and six outdoor meets during May and June, including 
the championships, for American athletes to showcase their talents 
in televised events. 
</P>
<P>
	``Six (outdoor) meets within an eight- or nine-week period is  
critical for our development,'' Masback said, without disclosing 
which meets would be in the series. 
</P>
<P>
	Masback said USATF was working with meet directors to ensure  
that top athletes compete. The athletes will make promotional 
appearances before meets. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a matter of the athletes being willing to run in this  
country,'' Masback said. ``And it's a matter of being given the 
opportunity to run here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The national TV series will begin with the Feb. 5 Millrose Games  
at Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the nation's premier runners, 1996 Olympic 400-meter  
hurdles champion Derrick Adkins and 1998 U.S. indoor and outdoor 
800-meter champion Mark Everett, spoke Monday of the plight of U.S. 
athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	Both said they did not have shoe contracts, Adkins having lost  
his at the end of 1997 and Everett without one since 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Masback pointed out that USATF recently signed two new sponsors,  
one to support its elite programs and one to aid its youth 
development. He said there would be more sponsor announcements the 
next few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are attracted to us because we are the sport (the most  
highly watched during the Summer Olympics) and because of the 
personalities in the sport,'' Masback said. 
</P>
<P>
	While the sport's top two personalities -- Michael Johnson and  
Marion Jones -- are skipping the indoor season, Masback noted many 
other stars will compete against each other. 
</P>
<P>
	They include Maurice Greene and Jon Drummond at 60 meters, Suzy  
Hamilton and Regina Jacobs in the women's mile, Joetta Clark and 
Meredith Valmon in the women's 800 and Mark Crear and Reggie Torian 
in the 60 hurdles. 
</P>
<P>
	``The athletes are not hesitating to match up, which has long  
been a complaint of the sport,'' Masback said. ``Someone competing 
in a vacuum doesn't help us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that Adkins, Everett and 400-meter specialists Tyree  
Washington and Milton Campbell would run the 500 meters at the 
Millrose Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an odd distance, but it doesn't matter,'' Masback said.  
``There's no form chart for 500 meters, so anyone can win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Americans still are among the best teams in the world,  
the absence of greats like Carl Lewis, who retired in 1997, and 
Jackie Joyner-Kersee, who completed her career last year, has posed 
a big problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had some incredible superstars,'' Masback said, ``but  
time is an enemy. We have to replace them. We need stars to 
emerge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Masback said that will happen with more meets and TV exposure.  
He was dismayed track and field did not capitalize on its success 
after the 1996 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no organized follow-up to Atlanta,'' he said.  
``Gymnastics, they had a tour. So the response (to track) was 
nothing but a negative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Masback wants to draw on his sport's ``outstanding  
personalities, outstanding athletes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact we've made some small progress is encouraging,'' he  
said. ``The support we've gotten from sponsors makes me believe 
we'll make more progress in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to give the kids the opportunities to realize their  
dreams.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
