<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Elway Got His Groove Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- This is the story of how John Elway got his groove  
back. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver was behind 10-0 to the New York Jets in what was almost  
certainly his last game at Mile High Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Elway brought the Broncos to the line of scrimmage with 12  
minutes left in the third quarter. He saw the receiver who was 
supposed to be on his right lined up on his left. And vice versa. 
</P>
<P>
	Being John Elway, naturally, he turned it into the game-breaking  
play. 
</P>
<P>
	Elway made eye contact with Rod Smith and somehow got this  
message across: Run a crossing pattern instead of a post. Then, he 
yelled ``post'' at Ed McCaffrey, loud enough so that the Jets 
linemen, if not the defensive backs, had some idea of what was in 
store. 
</P>
<P>
	Fat lot of good that did. After getting the safeties to bite on  
a play-action fake, Elway hooked up with McCaffrey racing down the 
middle for 47 yards, setting up the first of four straight, 
lightning-fast scoring drives that sent the Broncos to a 23-10 win 
in the AFC Championship and on to the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're bright guys,'' Elway said of his receiving tandem,  
``even though they came out of the huddle the wrong way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Somehow you knew it would all work out. Somehow you knew he was  
not going to leave this place a loser. Not for the last time. Not 
without a fight. 
</P>
<P>
	Not Elway.  
</P>
<P>
	After wrestling with his emotions and questions about retirement  
all week, then being buffeted by swirling winds and the Jets' 
defense for a half, he turned as tough as the weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the comeback nor the stats were vintage Elway -- the  
first came way too early, the second were not worthy of a passer 
who has established himself as perhaps the NFL's best during the 
last 16 seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	But by the end, retirement was still a question and not a  
demand. 
</P>
<P>
	``My main focus is to finish this year,'' Elway said, ``before l  
figure out the next one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Judged by deed instead of word, he has most likely played his  
last game in Denver. He took a victory lap at the end of this one, 
rare for a player who treats praise the same way he does defensive 
lineman -- by scrambling. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was kind of unusual for him,'' Broncos coach Mike Shanahan  
said. ``I had to encourage him to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elway's next victory lap -- if there is one -- will take place in  
Miami, with the Atlanta Falcons as unwilling celebrants. And none 
of them will be as unwilling as their coach Dan Reeves. The same 
Dan Reeves who used to coach in Denver and fired Shanahan as his 
offensive coordinator because, Reeves said, Shanahan and Elway were 
usurping his authority behind his back. 
</P>
<P>
	If so, neither said anything even mildly critical that would  
find its way back to Reeves -- particularly on this day. 
</P>
<P>
	``At times,'' Shanahan said, ``we were best friends.''  
</P>
<P>
	``He's a great football coach,'' Elway said.  
</P>
<P>
	A moment later, s x1/2dne asked Elway whether he hoped this would  
be the last time the Reeves-revenge angle is mentioned. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't wish for things that are not going to happen,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	All things considered, though, the questions could have been  
worse N 
</P>
<P>
	Much worse.  
</P>
<P>
	As in last ye!r's Super Bowl, Elway had sentiment going for him  
at the start and not much else. He was 0-for-his-first five throws. 
His receivers were dropping balls and the Jets defenders were 
</P>
</TEXT>
