<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Jan. 18, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Condemns Kosovo Massacre  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. Security Council today strongly  
condemned the massacre of 45 ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and urged 
the Yugoslav government to rescind its decision to expel the head 
of the peace mission in the embattled Serb province. The council 
called for an immediate and full investigation of the massacre 
uncovered Saturday and urged all parties to cooperate with the 
international war crimes tribunal. The press statement pointedly 
did not pin the blame for the massacre on any party, and it made no 
mention of Yugoslavia's refusal today to allow the chief U.N. war 
crimes prosecutor to enter the country to investigate the atrocity. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Team Prepares Defense  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- White House lawyers today prepared the defense  
presentation for President Clinton's impeachment trial that they 
will begin tomorrow. It will focus on conflicts in testimony, a 
strategy that aims at undercutting House charges of perjury and 
obstruction of justice but that also could open the way to 
Republican demands for witnesses to help resolve the disputes. The 
White House has been fighting that demand, but now expects 
witnesses, officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Practices Annual Address  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today prepared for  
tomorrow's State of the Union address. The speech will touch on 
education, health care and other initiatives. Clinton will deliver 
his State of the Union address at 9 p.m. EST tomorrow in the House 
chamber. It was in that same chamber one month ago Tuesday that the 
House voted for only the second time in history to impeach the 
president. House Speaker Dennis Hastert sent House members a letter 
telling them to be on good behavior despite ``the discomfort'' 
surrounding the Senate trial. 

</P>
<P>
	Pippen To Be Traded to Rockets  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Chicago Bulls will trade Scottie Pippen to  
the Houston Rockets when the NBA lockout ends, The Associated Press 
has learned. The Bulls, who will sign Pippen to a deal worth more 
than $70 million for five years before trading him, will get 
forward Roy Rogers and a second-round draft pick in return. The 
acquisition of Pippen, a six-time champion with the Bulls, won't be 
finalized until the lockout is lifted Wednesday or Thursday. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Marks Martin Luther King Day  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- From the pulpit where Martin Luther King Jr. once  
preached, South African Archbishop Desmond Tutu today gave thanks 
to King and all American civil rights leaders he credited with 
paving the way for the end of apartheid in his country. People 
across the country celebrated Martin Luther King Day with speeches, 
sermons and volunteerism. Last Friday would have been King's 70th 
birthday. He died April 4, 1968, from an assassin's bullet. 

</P>
<P>
	Test Performed on King Probe Papers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A scientific test has failed to discredit two  
documents a former FBI agent said he took from James Earl Ray's car 
in 1968 after the assassination of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., 
a federal official said today. A former agent came forward last 
March with the two documents, which he said he had kept hidden for 
30 years after the assassination. The documents both have the name 
``Raul'' written on them. James Earl Ray pleaded guilty in 1969 to 
the King assassination but recanted within days. Ray, who died in 
prison in April, claimed after he was sentenced that he was set up 
by a smuggler he only knew as Raul. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S., IMF Back Brazil Currency Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration and the  
International Monetary Fund cautiously endorsed Brazil's move today 
to allow its currency to float freely. Both the IMF and the White 
House were caught by surprise by Brazil's abrupt decision to 
devalue its currency last week. A senior U.S. official said it was 
a shared judgment that the most important thing in Brazil was the 
pursuit of strong policies, especially carrying through on deficit 
reduction measures, strong anti-inflationary monetary measures and 
continuing structural reforms. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices fell slightly in early trading  
Tuesday amid pessimism about Japan's prospects for an economic 
recovery. The Nikkei dipped 26.31 points to 13,778.75 in the first 
30 minutes of trading. U.S. markets were closed today for the 
Martin Luther King Jr. holiday. 

</P>
<P>
	Joe Dimaggio Goes Home  
</P>
<P>
	HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) -- After 99 days in intensive care, lung  
cancer surgery, pneumonia, and an infection that nearly killed him 
and left him in a coma, Joe DiMaggio went home today. DiMaggio 
entered the hospital Oct. 12 and had surgery two days later to 
remove a cancerous lung tumor. He had a series of setbacks after a 
serious infection set in. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
</P>
</TEXT>
