<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe, Asia Markets Gain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Receding worries about Brazil's economic problems  
touched off a global rally in stock markets Monday as the country's 
central bank announced it would continue to float Brazil's 
currency, the real. 
</P>
<P>
	The steepest gains took place in Europe, with London's blue-chip  
Financial Times Stock Exchange index up 3.1 percent, or 182.9 
points, to 6,123.9. However, other world markets were still 
volatile. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is still a lot of uncertainty out there and I would not  
advise people to be investing in shares right now. These gains are 
simply not sustainable,'' said Michael Derks, senior market 
strategist for Nomura Securities in London. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil caused a panic in world financial markets Wednesday when  
it devalued its currency by 8 percent, sparking fears that if the 
country could succumb to an Asian-style currency crisis. A crisis 
in its economy, the largest in Latin America, could drag down other 
countries in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks made strong gains across Europe. Frankfurt's DAX index  
rose 1.8 percent, the Paris CAC 40 index ended 2.4 percent higher, 
Milan's MIBtel index rose 4.6 percent, and Madrid's IBEX-35 index 
was up 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Market-watchers credited the gains to a recovery last week on  
Wall Street and other world stock exchanges following moves by the 
Brazilian government to stabilize its economy. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. financial markets were closed Monday for the Martin Luther  
King Jr. Day holiday. On Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average 
gained 2.4 percent when it became apparent Brazil's government 
would stop spending its dwindling foreign reserves defending its 
faltering currency. 
</P>
<P>
	Asian bourses had opened sharply Monday, although many fell back  
by the close of trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average opened up but  
lost much of its steam, finishing up 0.48 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index opened sharply higher in Hong Kong. By the  
end of trading, the blue-chip index had soared to a gain of 2.5 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Korea Composite Stock Price Index in Seoul closed up by  
1.27 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Markets gained a hefty 4.4 percent in Manila, Singapore's  
Straits Times Index was up 2.7 percent, and New Zealand's NZSE-40 
capital index finished up 2.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	One weak spot was China, where the two stock markets opened  
largely unchanged Monday. Traders said prices could fall because of 
growing numbers of Chinese companies warning of low profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in Taiwan also ended lower on profit-taking following two  
sessions of government-led stock fund purchases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
