<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Currency Plan Is Backed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration and the  
International Monetary Fund cautiously endorsed Brazil's move on 
Monday to allow its currency to float freely while stressing the 
critical need for the country to quickly get its budget deficit 
under control. 
</P>
<P>
	The endorsements were sought by a team of Brazilian finance  
officials led by Finance Minister Pedro Malan who have engaged in a 
nonstop round of talks that started Saturday in an effort to 
explain Brazil's decision to stop trying to keep the value of the 
country's currency, the real, linked to the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to meeting with top staff at the IMF and World Bank,  
Malan held a series of talks with Deputy Treasury Secretary 
Lawrence Summers, the administration's point man on the global 
currency crisis, and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. 
</P>
<P>
	While both the IMF and the Clinton administration were caught by  
surprise by Brazil's abrupt decision to devalue the real last week, 
officials insisted after the talks with Malan that they better 
understood the pressures that forced the change. 
</P>
<P>
	``The discussions were comprehensive and constructive and  
provided useful clarification of the policy stance of the Brazilian 
authorities,'' IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior U.S. official said it was a shared judgment that the  
most important thing in Brazil was the pursuit of strong policies, 
especially carrying through on deficit reduction measures, strong 
anti-inflationary monetary measures and continuing structural 
reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration official, who spoke on condition of  
anonymity, said Malan had stressed the determination of President 
Fernando Henrique Cardoso to win approval for promised deficit 
reduction measures in a very complex political environment. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF and the United States combined forces last fall to  
assemble a $41.5 billion support package for Brazil in hopes of 
preventing that country from falling victim to the same currency 
troubles that have leveled a number of Asian nations and Russia 
beginning in mid-1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil is the largest economy in Latin America, a region that  
accounts for 20 percent of U.S. exports. With American 
manufacturers and farmers already reeling from a loss of Asian 
markets, the administration hoped to keep the currency upheavals 
that have pushed 40 percent of the globe into recession from 
striking Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	For a time it appeared that the pre-emptive credit line for  
Brazil would work as global markets stabilized and U.S. stocks, 
which had lost 20 percent of their value after Russia's summer 
collapse, recouped those losses and climbed to new highs. 
</P>
<P>
	But fears of further turbulence resumed last week when foreign  
investors began to dump their Brazilian holdings after Cardoso was 
defeated in a series of efforts to gain political support for his 
deficit reduction efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil has already received $9 billion from the IMF package  
announced in November, with another $9 billion scheduled for the 
end of February. 
</P>
<P>
	While Malan told reporters on Saturday it was possible he could  
ask for early release of the second loan installment, he insisted 
at a news conference Monday that Brazil had not sought that. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Bank said Monday in a statement that it was  
considering accelerating some of its support in the areas of 
assistance to the poor, banking and government reform. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the $41.5 billion, $18 billion is coming from the IMF, $9  
billion from the World Bank and the Inter-American Development Bank 
and the rest from 20 wealthy nations, including $5 billion from the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Both IMF and U.S. officials expressed unhappiness last week  
about the abrupt nature of Brazil's decision to devalue the 
currency. Asked about that criticism, Malan told reporters, ``I can 
assure you that what happened last week is water under the bridge. 
... We are looking ahead instead of looking back.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
