<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dozens Hospitalized in Bus Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRINCETON, Ill. (AP) -- Forty-six people on their way to a  
riverboat casino were rushed to the hospital after the charter bus 
they were riding in lost control and flipped onto its side. 
</P>
<P>
	The bus was headed from Chicago to the President's Riverboat  
Casino in Davenport, Iowa, when it apparently lost control on an 
icy patch of Interstate 80 near Princeton, police said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were all talking and the next thing you know the bus  
swerved and everybody was on one side of the bus,'' passenger Tara 
Lockett, 24, an optician from Chicago, said. ``It was kind of 
awful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police were still investigating the accident and have not  
decided whether driver Isiah Golden, 52 of Chicago, would be 
ticketed, said Master Sgt. David Spahm of the Illinois State 
Police. Golden was not injured. 
</P>
<P>
	No other vehicles were involved in the accident, police said.  
</P>
<P>
	A woman answering the phone at Neal's Bus Company, the  
Chicago-based company that operates the bus, declined to comment on 
the accident Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerald Boyd, 56, of Chicago, was transferred to OSF Saint  
Francis Medical Center in Peoria in critical condition, suffering 
from several broken bones, according to hospital spokeswoman 
Michele Sheppard. Ella Abram, 50, also of Chicago, was transferred 
to Saint Francis in serious condition with head injuries, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven passengers were treated and released at Perry Memorial,  
nursing supervisor Carol Howes said. Four were admitted in good 
condition, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten passengers were treated and released at Illinois Valley  
Hospital in Peru, according to the nursing supervisor. One person 
was admitted, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighteen other people were treated and released at St.  
Margaret's Hospital in Spring Valley. 
</P>
</TEXT>
