<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 16:14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Few Following Clinton Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans are not engaged by the impeachment  
process, and the trial so far has not changed their minds about 
turning President Clinton out of office, a poll released Monday 
indicated. 
</P>
<P>
	Fewer than a third of Americans are paying very close attention  
to the trial in the Senate, the survey by the Pew Research Center 
for the People and the Press indicated. 
</P>
<P>
	Of 1,200 adults polled by telephone Jan. 14-18, 69 percent said  
the trial has not changed their opinions about whether the 
president should be removed from office or resign. 
</P>
<P>
	A steady two-thirds of the public wanted Clinton to remain in  
office. 
</P>
<P>
	Of those polled, 76 percent said Republicans and Democrats are  
mostly bickering instead of working together as only the nation's 
second presidential impeachment trial gets under way. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional Republicans won approval from 32 percent of those  
polled for their handling of the investigation, and Democrats 
scored a 44 percent approval rating. Clinton himself scored a 45 
percent approval rating, and 35 percent said they approve of the 
way the media are handling their task. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Justice William Rehnquist did better than other trial  
participants, with a 50 percent approval rating, although he has 
been little visible in the trial so far. 
</P>
<P>
	Study authors suggested those polled may have reacted more to  
Rehnquist's stature than his performance in the impeachment 
proceedings. Only 19 percent could name Rehnquist as presiding over 
the trial, although 48 percent could name Larry Flynt as the 
publisher who offered money for proof that members of Congress 
committed adultery. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the public continues to give Clinton good grades on  
the job. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pew poll indicated 63 percent of Americans approve of  
Clinton's performance in office. That's down some from late 
December, when 71 percent gave Clinton a favorable rating, but 
about the same as his 61 percent approval rating in the same survey 
when the Monica Lewinsky scandal broke a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey indicated 53 percent of Americans are satisfied with  
the way things are going in the country -- up from 46 percent a year 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	And 45 percent of those polled said they are very satisfied with  
their standard of living, up substantially from 35 percent in late 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans are even happier about their family lives -- 71 percent  
rate themselves as very satisfied. Asked about their housing 
situations, 61 percent said they are very satisfied. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey has a margin or error of plus or minus 3.5 percentage  
points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
