<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Varsity Blues' Tops Box Office / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``Varsity Blues,'' starring James Van Der  
Beek as a high school football star coming of age in a Texas town, 
rumbled past ``A Civil Action'' into the No. 1 box office spot over 
the weekend, estimates showed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Varsity Blues,'' a collaboration between Paramount and MTV,  
debuted at No. 1 with $14.3 million. It was the strongest opener 
ever during a Martin Luther King Jr. holiday weekend, moving ahead 
of the previous record of $14 million held by 1994's ``Legends of 
the Fall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This movie appeals to the young male audience,'' said Wayne  
Lewellen, president of distribution at Paramount. ``There really 
hasn't been a lot of product out for that audience. They were pent 
up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``A Civil Action,'' about a real-life legal battle against  
tainted drinking water, dropped to second place with $10.9 million 
after taking the top spot last weekend in its expanded release, 
estimates showed Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	In its first weekend of wide release, the World War II epic  
``The Thin Red Line'' jumped to a respectable No. 3 with $10.5 
million in ticket sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Robin Williams' heartwarmer ``Patch Adams'' fell to the No. 4  
spot with $10.2 million in its fourth week. 
</P>
<P>
	``At First Sight'' opened in the No. 5 spot this weekend with  
$7.7 million in ticket sales. Val Kilmer stars in this story of a 
blind masseur who falls in love with Mira Sorvino and regains his 
vision -- but stumbles when thrown into the world of sight. 
</P>
<P>
	Dropping again this weekend were ``Stepmom'' to sixth place with  
$6.3 million; ``You've Got Mail'' at seventh with $5.9 million; and 
``The Prince of Egypt'' in a tie for eighth place with $5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Virus,'' the science-fiction adventure starring Jamie Lee  
Curtis and William Baldwin, also took eighth place in its opening 
weekend, selling $5 million in tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	Another movie opening this weekend, the thriller ``In Dreams,''  
starring Annette Bening and Robert Downey Jr. tied with 
``Shakespeare in Love'' for the No. 10 spot with $4 million in 
ticket sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Here are estimated grosses at North American theaters for Friday  
through Sunday. Final figures were to be released today: 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``Varsity Blues,'' $14.3 million.  
</P>
<P>
	2. ``A Civil Action,'' $10.9 million.  
</P>
<P>
	3. ``The Thin Red Line,'' $10.5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	4. ``Patch Adams,'' $10.2 million.  
</P>
<P>
	5. ``At First Sight,'' $7.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``Stepmom,'' $6.3 million.  
</P>
<P>
	7. ``You've Got Mail,'' $5.9 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. (tie) ``The Prince of Egypt,'' $5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. (tie) ``Virus,'' $5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	10. (tie) ``Shakespeare in Love,'' $4 million.  
</P>
<P>
	10. (tie) ``In Dreams,'' $4 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
