<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vikes QB Wants To Start, or Leave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- One day after a disappointing end to  
his own disappointing season, Brad Johnson said he hopes the 
Minnesota Vikings trade him if he won't be their starting 
quarterback in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's something available and it's a good situation for  
the Vikings first -- because that's the way it'll be decided, the 
Vikings first and me second -- then I'm open to that,'' Johnson said 
Monday. ``If it's a situation where I can hopefully have that 
chance as a starter, then I'm all for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, a career backup who earned the starting job late in the  
1996 season, began this season as Minnesota's starter. He had come 
back from a neck injury that cost him the last five games of the 
1997 season, but he broke a bone in his leg in the second game. 
</P>
<P>
	Randall Cunningham replaced him and flourished, earning Pro Bowl  
and All-Pro recognition. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson returned Nov. 8 when Cunningham injured his knee against  
New Orleans, but Johnson broke the thumb on his throwing hand in 
the second half that day. Even though he finished the game he also 
was finished playing for six more weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Then the Vikings gave Cunningham a $28 million contract  
extension late in the regular season, and Johnson's future became 
uncertain. He discussed it for the first time following Sunday's 
painful 30-27 overtime loss to Atlanta in the NFC championship 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Vikings have said repeatedly they want to keep both  
players and believe they can afford starter's salaries for two 
quarterbacks -- Johnson has three years left on a $15.5 million 
contract -- Johnson seems unlikely to accept a role as Cunningham's 
permanent backup. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love it here in Minnesota, but I feel like I want to play, I  
want to be a starter,'' he said. ``I deserve that opportunity. I 
don't know if it will happen here. It might, but I'm just going to 
wait things out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Vikings publicly say they are committed to keeping  
Johnson, the possibility of getting a top-5 draft pick as part of a 
deal for him might be too good to pass up. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Diamond, Minnesota's senior vice president of football  
operations, maintained the company line Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to take a look at the whole situation, and our  
intent is to try to keep them both,'' Diamond said. ``Brad is a 
class guy, a terrific guy. We'd like to see him stay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson made it clear that would be his preference, but only as  
a starter. He paused when asked if he would consider staying if 
coach Dennis Green guaranteed him a chance to compete with 
Cunningham in training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to play, but whatever they decide, I trust Denny,''  
Johnson said. ``Randall had a great year this year. Whatever they 
decide to do, that's what we go with regardless.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Green suggested last month that Cunningham might return to the  
backup role the Vikings brought him in to fill in 1997. Cunningham 
said Monday he hopes Johnson returns. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we'll win with either one of us, and that's the  
decision they have to make,'' Johnson said. ``No matter who plays 
or if I'm here or not.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
