<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Varsity Blues' Tops Box Office / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Teen males who had the day off from school  
Monday helped the new football movie ``Varsity Blues'' with James 
Van Der Beek tighten its hold on No. 1 at the North American box 
office, estimates showed. 
</P>
<P>
	Three other new films opened to disappointing business, however.  
``At First Sight'' with Val Kilmer and Mira Sorvino had $8.7 
million for fifth, ``Virus'' with Jamie Lee Curtis had $6 million 
for ninth and ``In Dreams'' with Annette Bening had $4.7 million 
for 11th. 
</P>
<P>
	``Varsity Blues'' raked in $17.6 million to become the  
biggest-opening movie for Martin Luther King Day weekend, a dubious 
title since studios traditionally release weaker films this time of 
year. The previous record-holder was ``Higher Learning'' in 1995, 
which went on to gross a modest $38 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the four-day box office period, ``Varsity Blues,'' and its  
core audience of teen males knocked ``A Civil Action'' into second 
place with $11.8 million. ``Patch Adams'' was third with $11.7 
million and will top the $100 million mark this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The war film ``The Thin Red Line'' went into expanded release  
for the first time and brought in a respectable $11.4 million for 
fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stepmom'' was sixth with $7.8 million, ``You've Got Mail''  
seventh with $6.7 million and ``The Prince of Egypt'' eighth with 
$6.2 million. ``Shakespeare In Love'' rounded out the Top 10 with 
$4.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Here are estimated grosses at North American theaters for Friday  
through Monday. Final figures were to be released Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``Varsity Blues,'' $17.6 million.  
</P>
<P>
	2. ``A Civil Action,'' $11.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	3. ``Patch Adams,'' $11.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	4. ``The Thin Red Line,'' $11.4 million.  
</P>
<P>
	5. ``At First Sight,'' $8.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``Stepmom,'' $7.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	7. ``You've Got Mail,'' $6.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. ``The Prince of Egypt,'' $6.2 million.  
</P>
<P>
	9. ``Virus,'' $6 million.  
</P>
<P>
	10. ``Shakespeare in Love,'' $4.8 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
