<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Resuming Legislative Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Top Senate Republicans are unveiling an agenda  
focusing on Social Security, tax cuts and other issues as the new 
Congress begins burrowing into its legislative tasks. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and other Senate GOP  
leaders today planned to reveal their first five bills of the 106th 
Congress, which began its two-year life earlier this month. The 
announcement of each party's initial bills is a biennial ritual 
that each uses to publicize its top priorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislative work will begin slowly as usual, with little but  
committee work going on this month. But with polls showing most 
members of the public disenchanted with GOP efforts to remove 
President Clinton from office, Republicans are especially 
interested in demonstrating that they are eager to address issues 
of concern to voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``A good message is the work moves forward,'' said Rep. Jennifer  
Dunn, R-Wash., in an interview Monday. Dunn and Rep. Steve Largent, 
R-Okla., will be delivering the GOP response tonight to Clinton's 
State of the Union address. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Senate Republicans' first five bills will focus on  
Social Security, tax cuts, education, anti-crime and anti-drug 
initiatives, and defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats also plan to unveil their top five bills.  
</P>
<P>
	In the House, new Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said Monday he  
would reserve H.R.1, the House's first bill of the new Congress, 
for the president's legislation on strengthening the pension 
program for the elderly and disabled. Clinton has called for 
buttressing the program for the impending retirement of baby 
boomers, but has provided no details on how he would do it and is 
not expected to reveal any soon. 
</P>
<P>
	The flurry of activity comes as lawmakers return to the Capitol  
in full force, in time to hear Clinton's address tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	The House meets Tuesday, but mainly so members can be around for  
Clinton's address in the evening. It will then recess until Feb. 2, 
although many committees will remain at work. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate was meeting briefly this morning for speeches on  
legislation. After lunch, senators will resume their more familiar 
mode of late, hearing the Clinton impeachment trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Topping off what will unavoidably be a peculiar day, those same  
senators will then troop across the Capitol after dinner to hear 
the president's address. 
</P>
<P>
	The full Senate's legislative schedule is uncertain after that,  
mainly because of the unsure timing of the impeachment trial. It is 
possible that the Senate will meet for legislative business on 
Wednesday and Friday mornings, though little more than speeches are 
likely because no bills are ready for floor consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate Appropriations Committee was planning almost daily  
hearings in preparation for its work later this year on spending 
bills for 2000. GOP leaders want to get those bills finished as 
early as possible, in hopes of avoiding a replay of last fall's 
mammoth $520 billion spending measure, which handed Clinton several 
victories just before the elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Other panels planning early hearings include the Senate Budget  
Committee, with 11 hearings on budget topics; the House Ways and 
Means Committee, at which Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan 
will testify on economic issues; the House's renamed Armed Services 
Committee, which will hear from the Joint Chiefs of Staff; and the 
Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee, which will consider 
efforts to impose new controls on health-maintenance organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
