<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UConn Stays Atop Men's Hoops Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The last time the Miami Hurricanes were ranked in The Associated  
Press college basketball poll, Rick Barry was still in high school. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Monday, the Hurricanes were in the poll at No. 25, the  
school's first appearance since 1960. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's more exposure, so it's good for us,'' forward Johnny  
Hemsley said. ``We're an up-and-coming program, and people are 
starting to notice it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Things remained the same at the top, with Connecticut at No. 1  
for the eighth straight week and Duke a solid No. 2 for the sixth 
week in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	But there were changes at the bottom as Louisville also moved in  
for the first time this season at No. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut (15-0), an easy winner over Notre Dame and  
Pittsburgh last week, received 53 first-place votes and 1,755 
points from the national media panel. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke (17-1), which beat Wake Forest and Florida State last week,  
was No. 1 on 18 ballots and had 1,721 points, 134 more than 
Stanford, which moved up one spot to No. 3 following road wins over 
Southern California and UCLA. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland also moved up one place to fourth, while Cincinnati,  
which lost for the first time this season last week at North 
Carolina Charlotte, dropped two spots to No. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Auburn, along with Connecticut the only unbeaten teams in  
Division I, jumped from eighth to sixth, and was followed in the 
Top Ten by Kentucky, St. John's, Arizona and North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Auburn plays at Kentucky on Wednesday night, and this week's  
other Top Ten matchup will have Duke at St. John's on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan State was 11th followed by New Mexico and UCLA. Then  
came five straight Big Ten teams -- Iowa, Wisconsin, Purdue, 
Minnesota and Indiana. Kansas was 19th and Syracuse 20th. 
</P>
<P>
	The Top 25 was rounded out by Texas Christian, Arkansas,  
Oklahoma State, Louisville and Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hurricanes (11-3) were ranked for all but the first poll of  
the 1959-60 season, reaching as high as No. 8. Barry, who went on 
to a Hall of Fame NBA career, played at Miami from 1963-65, and six 
seasons later the school dropped the sport because of a lack of 
interest in South Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	The program was restarted for the 1985-86 season and the  
Hurricanes, under coach Leonard Hamilton, been close of the Top 25 
in recent seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a team that's trying to build a tradition,'' said  
Hamilton, 109-132 in his ninth season at Miami. ``Once we get 
there, I hope we'll stay there. But you have to earn that by being 
consistent over a period of time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Hurricanes entered the rankings having won nine of their  
past 10 games, the only loss to Notre Dame. Their other losses have 
been to North Carolina-Charlotte and Kentucky; wins have included 
Ohio State and St. John's. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a huge opportunity for us. I know it's the highest  
opportunity of my career,'' said forward Tim James, Miami's leading 
scorer with an 18.8 average. 
</P>
<P>
	The ranking will get a test right away, with No. 1 Connecticut  
visiting Miami Arena for a Big East game Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Winning Big East games are important. The fact this is the No.  
1 team in the country -- that's a bonus,'' Hamilton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Louisville (10-3) has won four straight games since a loss at  
Michigan State. The Cardinals are ranked for the first time since 
the second week of last season when they were 19th. Louisville is 
on a probation and will miss the Conference USA and NCAA 
tournaments this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State, which entered the poll last week for the first time  
this season, dropped out from No. 21 following losses to Iowa and 
Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemson, which came in with the first poll of the regular season  
and reached as high as No. 14 under first-year coach Larry Shyatt, 
fell out from No. 25 following losses to Florida State and 
Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State's departure ends the Big Ten's record run of seven  
teams at one week. It was the second time the conference had seven 
teams ranked and the last time, January 1993, also lasted one week. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami's entrance gives the Big East four teams, joining  
Connecticut, St. John's and Syracuse. Only the Big Ten, with six 
teams, has more. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
