<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 14:57:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Honors King, Volunteers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After knocking down a wall with  
``therapeutic'' zeal, President Clinton used Monday's holiday 
honoring Martin Luther King Jr. to announce a $6.5 billion fair 
housing settlement reached by enforcing a law passed days after 
King's death. 
</P>
<P>
	The president, dressed in blue jeans, cited King's philosophy as  
he joined Vice President Al Gore and a team of AmeriCorps 
volunteers in tearing down a wall to make way for a health clinic 
at the Regency House retirement home. 
</P>
<P>
	Their work was part of a national focus on volunteerism in the  
spirit of King, the nation's most celebrated human rights activist 
who was born Jan. 15, 1929, and died April 4, 1968, from an 
assassin's bullet. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton attacked the wall using a hammer with one hand and a  
crowbar with the other. Gore did, too. Tiny chunks of plaster 
pelted reporters standing nearby. They asked Clinton whether the 
work was therapeutic for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all highly therapeutic,'' said Clinton, who gave  
instructions to others and dragged away a set of metal bars. 
</P>
<P>
	``It did the vice president and me a lot of good to pick up  
those hammers and crowbars and tear something down,'' Clinton 
laughed. ``We do this desk work all the time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton noted the words to one of King's favorite hymns -- ``If I  
can help somebody ... Then my living will not be in vain'' -- and 
said all Americans should heed the call to serve others. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, Clinton bought three books at a local bookstore and  
returned to the White House to practice his State of the Union 
speech. 
</P>
<P>
	At Regency House, Clinton announced that the Department of  
Housing and Urban Development and Columbia National Mortgage Co. 
had settled a housing discrimination case worth $6.5 billion in 
loans and homeownership programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the settlement, the Columbia, Md.-based lender will make  
$6 billion in home mortgage loans available over five years to 
minorities and low- to moderate-income families in the District of 
Columbia and 26 states where they did business in 1997. The company 
also will spend $529 million on programs designed to increase 
homeownership among minority and poor families. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia National was accused of violating the Fair Housing Act  
-- which bars discrimination in home sales and rentals -- by making 
too few loans to minority or low- to moderate-income families. In 
1997, its loans to such borrowers totaled only $51.6 million, less 
than 5 percent of its volume; In 10 states, none of its loans went 
to minorities or the poor. 
</P>
<P>
	The case was the eighth settlement negotiated by HUD to resolve  
alleged unfair lending practices uncovered through testing by the 
Fort Worth Human Relations Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	``If companies know we're going to enforce the law, you'll see  
more compliance. And $6.5 billion says we're going to enforce the 
law,'' said Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo, who attended services 
in Atlanta commemorating King. 
</P>
<P>
	In the final months of his life, King had pressed for passage of  
the Fair Housing Act. Congress approved it April 10, 1968, six days 
after King's death. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had worked for years to outlaw discrimination in housing,  
and many who voted for the measure said they did it in tribute to 
him,'' Clinton said. ``So here, all these years later, ... we are 
proud that this happened on Dr. King's national holiday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the settlement is the largest of its kind. HUD  
negotiated the second-largest lending discrimination settlement, 
$2.1 billion, with AccuBanc Mortgage last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, meanwhile, announced that the administration will request  
a 15 percent increase in federal spending on civil rights 
enforcement. Last year, the administration asked for an $86 million 
increase and got $64 million from Congress. The administration is 
seeking an additional $84 million this year, to bring the total to 
$663 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 01:32:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up, Japanese Stocks Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The United States dollar edged higher against the  
yen today, buoyed by wary optimism about Brazil's financial 
situation. Tokyo stocks posted a slight gain. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 114.14 yen in late afternoon trading, up 0.68  
yen from late Thursday and little changed from its level late 
Friday in New York of 114.13 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 66.20 points,  
or 0.48 percent, closing at 13,805.06. On Thursday, the average 
gained 335.26 points, or 2.50 percent. Financial markets in Japan 
were closed Friday for a national holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar moved as high  
as 114.55 yen in intraday trading amid easing concern over 
financial turmoil in Brazil, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	But these early gains were eroded as Japanese exporters and  
overseas hedge funds took profits by selling dollars for yen, 
sending the greenback as low as 113.25 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Brazilian situation is still very murky and no one can  
predict its effects on the U.S. economy,'' said Takayuki Togawa, 
manager of the foreign exchange division at Tokai Bank Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were expected to closely watch testimony by U.S. Federal  
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan before Congress on Wednesday for 
any indication of monetary policy changes or comments on the 
problems in Brazil, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the euro was quoted at 132.34 yen in Tokyo, up from  
132.30 yen late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, traders said investors were  
heartened by a recovery in U.S. and other world stock exchanges on 
Friday following moves by the Brazilian government to stabilize its 
economy, Latin America's largest. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Tokyo market welcomed a temporary relief from worries over  
the Brazilian economy,'' said Masatoshi Sato, manager of the 
investor information group at Kankaku Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 219.62 points  
to 9,340.55. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil caused a panic in world financial markets on Wednesday  
when it devalued its currency, the real, by nearly 8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But the nation's decision Friday to stop spending heavily to  
support the real generated confidence the government was taking 
appropriate measures to nurse the economy back to health. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the Tokyo Stock Exchange's first section was estimated  
at 334 million shares, down from Thursday's turnover of 409 million 
shares. Advancers outnumbered decliners 671 to 439, with 166 issues 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 5.85 points, or 0.55 percent, to 1,075.79. The 
TOPIX had climbed 12.86 points, or 1.22 percent, Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.725 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.665 percent, 
driving its price down to 100.60 yen from 101.09 yen the previous 
day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
