<DOCNO> APW19990118.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 13:36:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises vs. Other Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar posted slight gains against the yen  
and was mixed against European currencies Monday as traders 
continued to take their cues from developments in Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	On a day of slender market activity due to the Martin Luther  
King Jr. Day holiday, the dollar rose to 114.35 yen in late New 
York trading, up from 114.13 late Friday. The euro was quoted at 
$1.1601, up from $1.1588 late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's Central Bank Monday confirmed its plan to allow the  
nation's currency, the real, to float freely against the dollar. 
But the bank reserved the right to intervene in markets from time 
to time in order to prevent extreme fluctuations of the real's 
value. The dollar strengthened against the real Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lingering caution prevented any major gains, as currency traders  
have already begun anticipating Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan's testimony before Congress Wednesday. If Greenspan 
appears nervous about Brazil's impact on the U.S. economy, U.S. 
stocks and the dollar are both likely to falter. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, the dollar was quoted at 1.3811 Swiss francs,  
down from 1.3833 Friday, and 1.5283 Canadian dollars, up from 
1.5243. The British pound rose to $1.6529 from $1.6518. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.6861 German 
marks, down from 1.6878; 5.6529 French francs, down from 5.6593; 
and 1,669.45 Italian lire, down from 1,672.24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
