<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nagano Bidders Gave IOC Painting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A painting worth thousands of dollars was among the  
apples, crafts and other gifts that Nagano bidders gave the IOC in 
an effort to win the 1998 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Nagano Mayor Tasuku Tsukada, a senior member of the bidding  
committee, said Monday that Eisetsu Shiratori, a Nagano artist, 
donated his work as a gift to the IOC and the bidders passed it on 
to an IOC official. 
</P>
<P>
	Tsukada, who has repeatedly denied any wrongdoing in his city's  
bid, commented by fax in reply to questions from The Associated 
Press. He refused to identify the IOC official and would not say 
whether he saw the gift as possible bribery. 
</P>
<P>
	``We relayed Mr. Shiratori's goodwill to the IOC,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The bribery scandal in Salt Lake City has rekindled doubts about  
long-rumored lavish gifts as well as wining and dining during 
Nagano's 1989-1991 bid. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC officials are banned from accepting gifts of more than $150.  
But IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch has said the rule does not 
apply to him because he does not vote in the selection of cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese-style paintings, including those by contemporary  
artists, are often valued at extremely high prices and used as 
investment vehicles by wealthy buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Tsukada said he did not have the painting assessed. Works by  
Shiratori, a respected painter in Japan, are rarely sold and 
difficult to value, but the painting presented to the IOC is 
believed to be worth at least $9,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Shiratori did not immediately return telephone messages asking  
for his comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The city of Nagano and the Japanese Olympic Committee said  
Monday they do not plan an investigation into the bid for last 
year's games. 
</P>
<P>
	The Asahi newspaper in a weekend editorial accused Nagano  
bidders of trying to cover up their expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nagano city and the Nagano prefectural government are bound by  
duty to offer the public the facts about the Olympic Games,'' Asahi 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sumikazu Yamaguchi, a senior official with the bidding  
committee, said last week that he had ordered the records of the 
bidding expenses burned in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bidding committee has already disbanded,'' Shigenobu  
Koyanagi, a Nagano city official in charge of the Olympics, said 
Monday. ``And the records have all been disposed of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Nagano bidders say they spent nearly $18 million -- more than  
half of that for entertainment, air and hotel fares for IOC 
officials and a contract with a foreign agent to gather information 
about the IOC and rival cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
