<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Will Allow Currency To Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil today announced it would continue  
to allow its currency to trade openly on foreign exchange markets 
on a long-term basis, a move seen as a step toward overcoming its 
financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting today, Brazil's central bank will let financial  
institutions determine the exchange rate by buying and selling the 
currency according to their own needs, bank official Demosthenes 
Madurerira de Pinho said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Central Bank may intervene in the market occasionally and  
in a limited form with the objective of preventing disorderly 
movements in the exchange rate,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after the announcement, Brazil's currency, the real,  
opened against the dollar at between 1.42 and 1.48. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement follows the market's positive reaction to  
action taken by the government on Friday, when Brazil announced it 
would temporarily abandon its defense of the real by not dipping 
into its cash reserves to prop up its beleaguered currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The real plunged as low as 1.60 to the dollar before  
strengthening slightly to 1.43 at the close of trading. That was 
down from 1.32 at the close of trading Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	That move came just two days after the Central Bank tried a  
smaller devaluation of 8 percent by extending the band in which the 
currency could trade to between 1.20 reals and 1.32 reals to the 
dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, the currency has fallen more than 15 percent since  
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Minister Pedro Malan and new Central Bank chief  
Francisco Lopes met in Washington on Sunday with U.S. officials and 
the International Monetary Fund, which in November put together a 
$41.5 billion aid package for Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	The global financial crisis hit Brazil full force in August,  
when investors pulled money out, fearing the government couldn't 
cover a $65 billion budget deficit and might default on loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, more than $40 billion has left the country, dropping  
reserves to around $35 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
