<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jets Give Nod To talk To Belichick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- The Kansas City Chiefs and Chicago Bears  
have been given permission to talk with New York Jets assistant 
head coach Bill Belichick about head coaching vacancies with those 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know whether he intends to interview with either or  
both, but I gave him permission to do so,'' said Jets coach Bill 
Parcells, who also serves as chief football operations officer. 
``Bill and I have talked about things so I think that will be a 
relatively short process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belichick is the heir-apparent to Parcells as Jets coach.  
Parcells announced Monday that he will return to coach the AFC East 
champions in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets also on Monday re-signed all their assistant coaches,  
Belichick, Maurice Carthon (running backs), Romeo Crennel 
(defensive line), Al Groh (linebackers), Dan Henning 
(quarterbacks), Todd Haley (offensive assistant), Pat Hodgson 
(tight ends), John Lott (strength and conditioning), Eric Mangini 
(defensive assistant), Bill Muir (offensive line), Mike Sweatman 
(special teams) and offensive coordinator Charlie Weis. 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells said 90 percent of the assistants got two-year  
contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	The status of veterans Pepper Johnson, Dave Meggett and Keith  
Byars remains uncertain next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells told Johnson he would be looking for a younger  
linebacker while Meggett was told by the coach that he would not be 
kept if it stifled the progress of a younger return man (Leon 
Johnson). Byars is considering retirement, and Parcells told the 
fullback to consider carefully whether he wants to return for a 
14th season. 
</P>
<P>
	New York, which lost the AFC championship game to Denver 23-10  
on Sunday, also signed seven free agents on Monday, including tight 
end Johnny Mitchell, their former 1992 first-round draft who has 
not played football in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell played for the Jets from 1992-95 and then briefly with  
Dallas in 1996 after signing as a free agent. He had 154 catches 
for 2,086 yards and 16 touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells said he is looking for a good pass receiving tight end  
who can get down the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's at the end of the line, he knows that,'' Parcells said.  
``So we'll see what an opportunity it is for him. He's not an old 
guy, he's only 27.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets also signed their practice squad players for next year,  
RB Robert Farmer, WRs Chris Brazzell and Brian Musso, TE Lawrence 
Hart and DT Geno Bell. Former Georgia RB Odell Collins was signed 
as a free agent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
