<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Urges Americans To Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Former President George Bush warned Monday that  
the nation needs to shore up the Social Security and Medicare 
programs before millions of baby boomers enter retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shouldn't be waiting for the big problems to fall into our  
laps,'' Bush told a crowd of about 700 during a daylong workshop 
sponsored by the Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget and 
American Express Financial Advisors. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a father of five, I know you don't prepare for the arrival  
of a new baby the week it's due. It just takes a little common 
sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The workshop, ``Building a Better Future: An Exercise in Hard  
Choices,'' is one of 10 being held across the country to solicit 
debate about keeping the nation's two largest entitlement programs 
afloat for future generations. 
</P>
<P>
	Without action by lawmakers, it's estimated that Medicare could  
go broke by 2008, with Social Security following suit about 24 
years later. 
</P>
<P>
	``The American symbol is an eagle, not an ostrich and now is not  
the time to go burying our heads in the sand,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	The former president, who admitted that he is not an expert on  
entitlement programs, said he didn't want to offer his opinion on 
what Congress should do because it might pressure his sons -- 
Florida Gov. Jeb Bush and Texas Gov. George W. Bush -- to follow his 
philosophy. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the problem of endangered federal entitlements rests  
with President Clinton, who has asked Congress to consider devoting 
the 1999 budget surplus -- $76 billion -- to fix Social Security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
