<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> States Push Fund for Tobacco Farms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) -- Faced with shrinking quotas, falling  
demand and several legal questions, tobacco state governors will go 
after money from cigarette manufacturers this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Six governors issued a joint statement Monday saying that a  
$5.15 billion trust fund to be financed by cigarette companies is 
``the only viable course of action to ensure the protection of our 
farmers and their future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The governors, attorneys general and agriculture commissioners  
of tobacco states are scheduled to meet with cigarette company 
officials Wednesday in Durham, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	``While there has been a strong sentiment for guaranteed  
purchases, the potential legal issues associated with this course 
of action may be considerable and would be time-consuming to 
resolve,'' the governors said in the statement. ``The dramatic 
reduction in the intent to purchase tobacco for the 1999 crop 
requires immediate and substantial action to avert financial 
disaster as the 1999 crop comes to market next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The statement was issued by Govs. Jim Hunt of North Carolina,  
Paul Patton of Kentucky, Jim Gilmore of Virginia, Jim Hodges of 
South Carolina, Roy Barnes of Georgia and Don Sundquist of 
Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	``We urge the companies to do the right thing by establishing  
this $5.15 billion trust fund to compensate them for part of their 
losses,'' the governors' statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The negotiations grow out of the $206 billion national tobacco  
settlement, in which the companies agreed to settle suits over 
smoking-related health care costs incurred by the states. The 
settlement stipulated that the companies meet with political 
leaders of tobacco states to talk about the concerns of the 
growers, who were not included in the deal. A first meeting was 
held a month ago. 
</P>
<P>
	But state and farm leaders acknowledge they have none of the  
legal leverage to get concessions for farmers that states did in 
seeking reimbursement for Medicaid and other health costs. 
</P>
<P>
	One company, Philip Morris, already has said it will contribute  
to the trust fund. But the company also said future payments would 
depend on what is done by the other major tobacco companies -- R.J. 
Reynolds, Brown &AMP; Williamson and Lorillard. 
</P>
<P>
	Reynolds initially opposed the trust fund, saying a better way  
to help farmers was to promise to buy more American-grown tobacco. 
Last week, the U.S. Department of Agriculture announced that 
cigarette makers plan to purchase 291 million pounds of burley 
tobacco in 1999, a 31 percent drop from a year ago. And flue-cured 
tobacco quotas are down about 30 percent from two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The national tobacco settlement has already produced huge  
increases in the price of cigarettes and is expected to further 
depress demand for farmers to continue their production. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 05:35:36 </DATE_TIME>
