<DOCNO> APW19990118.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 00:25:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Time Magazine Interviews Judi Dench </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- She appears on screen as a regal, commanding,  
even frightening presence-- the kind of character who ``if she just 
glanced at you, you'd be pretty dodgy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But watch how British actor Judi Dench -- who plays Queen  
Elizabeth I in ``Shakespeare in Love'' -- quivers on the other side 
of the screen. 
</P>
<P>
	Dench, 64, tells Time magazine in its Jan. 25 editions that she  
can barely stand watching her own performances. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very squeamish about it,'' she says. ``Once I see it, I  
regret what I've left undone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dench has another confession: After 41 years on the English  
stage, she still gets butterflies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's anxiety and fear that create adrenaline, which for me is  
petrol,'' she says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
