<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wilson's State of the Union Speech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- On an April afternoon in 1913, Woodrow Wilson  
stepped before an irritated Congress, shattered an ancient but 
unwritten rule and gave the modern presidency its voice. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson chose to deliver the annual message on the state of the  
union in person, not have it read by a faceless clerk as 24 other 
presidents had done. Some senators grumbled he was issuing a 
``speech from the throne'' and wrapping himself in the tarnished 
tinsel of royalty. Congress was ``nettled,'' the Washington Evening 
Star reported. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday night, nearly 86 years later, President Clinton will  
follow Wilson's example, using his seventh State of the Union 
address to reach beyond his antagonists in the Capitol to the 
nation at large. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is ignoring grumblers on Capitol Hill who contend an  
impeached president should cancel the speech and wait out his trial 
in the Senate. ``It's like adjourning a trial to have the accused 
give a pep rally before the jury,'' Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, 
complained Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Like most of the 14 presidents who have personally addressed  
Congress since Wilson on April 8, 1913, Clinton has used the State 
of the Union address to energize his administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, he called on Americans to resist siren calls to slash  
taxes and ``save Social Security first.'' Although Clinton was 
already under investigation for sexual misconduct, the speech 
raised his approval rating in the polls to 71 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Clinton, Wilson saw the president's annual message as an  
opportunity too large to be ignored. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a chance to supercharge his fledgling administration,  
then just a month old. And it was a chance to steal some of the 
still-echoing thunder of that Republican hurler of lightning bolts, 
Theodore Roosevelt. 
</P>
<P>
	Trumping TR was a point nearly everyone saw, including Wilson's  
wife, Ellen. 
</P>
<P>
	As the presidential car drew away from the Capitol, she leaned  
over and told her husband the speech was exactly what Roosevelt 
would have done ``if only he had thought of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' the new president chuckled. ``I think I put one over on  
Teddy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The wonder is that in seven years Theodore Roosevelt never  
thought of this way of stamping his personality upon his age,'' a 
New York Times editorial said on April 9, the day after the speech. 
</P>
<P>
	The Constitution requires presidents from time to time to give  
Congress ``information of the state of the union'' along with such 
proposals ``as he shall judge necessary and expedient.' 
</P>
<P>
	George Washington and John Adams had taken that literally,  
delivering their addresses in person, if not always in comfort. 
</P>
<P>
	The third president, Thomas Jefferson, had other ideas. The idea  
of the head of state addressing Congress was too much like the 
speech of a British monarch opening Parliament. Better to send a 
message in writing, avoid an unwanted royal trapping and thus 
``fortify republicanism,'' Jefferson believed. 
</P>
<P>
	Two dozen presidents did just that, the clerks of the House and  
the Senate droning their often-forgettable words over 112 years. 
Never has such a message produced a sensation, ``often it has 
produced sleep,'' the Evening Star editorialized. 
</P>
<P>
	But now Wilson was making a change, breaking a precedent.  
Congress was astonished. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am sorry to see revived the old Federalistic custom of  
speeches from the throne,'' said Sen. John Sharp Williams, D-Miss., 
said at the time. ``I regret this cheap and tawdry imitation of 
British royalty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his first words before an audience that filled the House  
floor and galleries, Wilson demolished that notion. 
</P>
<P>
	His purpose, he said, was to ``verify for myself the impression  
that the president of the United States is a person, not a mere 
department of the government hailing Congress from some isolated 
island of jealous power, sending messages, not speaking naturally 
and with his own voice -- that he is a human being trying to 
cooperate with other human beings in a common service.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``After this pleasant experience, I shall feel quite normal in  
all our dealings with one another,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Then to the issue at hand: He proposed legislation to cut the  
protective tariffs that for decades had sheltered American products 
from international competition. 
</P>
<P>
	When Wilson actually looked over the packed House chamber ``it  
was all so unusual that it seemed almost unreal,'' the Evening Star 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the state of the union address, revived so skillfully by  
Wilson, used masterfully by such presidents as Franklin D. 
Roosevelt, has become in the television age a platform that no 
chief executive would willingly surrender. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on the White  
House, Congress and Washington history for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 23:45:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Abortion Foe Kopp May Be in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The search for an abortion foe wanted for  
questioning in the sniper slaying of a Buffalo, N.Y., doctor is 
extending to Mexico, a Justice Department official says. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal investigators have some evidence that anti-abortion  
activist James Charles Kopp, 44, was driven to Mexico by a female 
friend after the Oct. 23 shooting of Dr. Barnett Slepian, a 
52-year-old obstetrician-gynecologist who performed abortions, this 
official said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	A Customs Service videotape from a border crossing point shows  
the woman's car returning from Mexico later, according to the 
official, who requested anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Newsweek magazine reported that credit card receipts reflect a  
trip to Mexico by the woman. In its Jan. 25 issue, Newsweek also 
said FBI Director Louis Freeh, in Mexico on an official visit last 
week, asked the Mexican government for help locating Kopp. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators have recovered fibers at the shooting scene that  
are being tested to see if they can be linked to Kopp, the Justice 
official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kopp is wanted as a material witness in the killing of Slepian,  
who was gunned down in the kitchen of his suburban Buffalo home by 
a rifle shot fired from outside. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities have said Kopp's car was spotted in Amherst, N.Y., a  
Buffalo suburb, in the weeks before Slepian was killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Kopp's 1987 Chevrolet Cavalier was discovered last month at  
Newark, N.J., International Airport, the FBI said. The car had been 
in the long-term lot for about two weeks, said Greg Trevor, a 
spokesman for the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	The car had a New Jersey license plate that didn't belong on it.  
FBI Agent Monica Patton in Newark said she couldn't say whether the 
plate had been stolen. 
</P>
<P>
	Kopp is believed to have been working on a construction job in  
the metropolitan New York area two days after the shooting, FBI 
Agent Bernard Tolbert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators believe the Slepian killing is linked to four  
earlier nonfatal shootings targeting doctors who provided abortion 
services in Canada and upstate New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 07:56:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minn. Considers a 'Ventura Highway' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLYN PARK, Minn. (AP) -- Jesse Ventura took a strange road to  
the governor's office. Now, two state lawmakers want to name a 
highway after him. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Linda Scheid and Rep. Darlene Luther have proposed naming  
U.S. Highway 610, which is under construction between Brooklyn Park 
and Maple Grove, ``Ventura Highway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They say the former professional wrestler deserves the  
recognition because he lobbied Congress for $36 million for the 
project when he was the mayor of Brooklyn Park, from 1991 to 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ventura Highway'' is the name of a 1972 song by the group  
America. The band played the song at Ventura's inaugural bash 
Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say Ventura shouldn't be singled out for praise.  
</P>
<P>
	``I would take it as sort of a personal affront if that would  
happen,'' said James Krautkremer, another former Brooklyn Park 
mayor. He was defeated by Ventura in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Krautkremer said Ventura was one of many officials who pushed  
for the $141 million highway and that his contribution came at the 
end of more than two decades of planning and lobbying by others. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after Ventura and other suburban mayors visited Congress  
in 1991, the highway project received $36 million in federal 
funding. Ventura later said that getting the money was perhaps his 
biggest accomplishment and suggested the name ``Ventura Highway'' -- 
saying it would be ``hilarious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's Darlene Luther's effort,'' Ventura spokeswoman Teresa  
McFarland said. ``I guess I would say it's flattering, (but) the 
governor's not going to be pursuing it necessarily.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Legislature would have to approve the designation.  
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, whose given name is James George Janos, chose his stage  
name after picking the California city on a map. The highway 
stretching between Ventura and Los Angeles is called the Ventura 
Freeway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 23:54:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blacks Have Stake in Clinton Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	With the impeachment trial of President Clinton entering its  
second week, many blacks spent Martin Luther King Day asking 
whether the proceedings prove that any man embraced by their 
community is doomed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody that I know that is black thinks that if he wouldn't  
have employed so many black folks and passed so many laws that 
benefited them, this wouldn't be much of an issue,'' Armon Henry, 
an Atlanta business owner, said Monday at the Martin Luther King 
Day parade in the neighborhood where the slain civil rights leader 
grew up. ``Clinton really is the first black president we've had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of miles away, Victoria Mares Hershey had a similar  
sentiment. 
</P>
<P>
	``My question is, are they really hounding him for his personal  
transgressions, or (to punish) him for making his administration 
the most diverse that the country's ever known?'' said Hershey, a 
vice president of the NAACP in Portland, Maine. ``That, to me, 
seems the undertone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many blacks have praised Clinton for his urban policy, focus on  
race relations and record number of black federal appointments -- 
and have rewarded him with their support. 
</P>
<P>
	A poll taken after the release of Independent Counsel Kenneth  
Starr's report last September showed that blacks were more 
supportive of the president than whites. 
</P>
<P>
	In Congress, black legislators have followed suit. All but six  
members of the Congressional Black Caucus opposed releasing Starr's 
report, and the entire caucus rose to his defense when the House 
considered impeaching him. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, blacks from all walks of life, at parades and prayer  
breakfasts, at work or at home, said it was particularly painful 
for them to watch the Senate trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think black Americans have a lot at stake if President  
Clinton is impeached,'' said Alicia Burbank, a 31-year-old 
homemaker and mother from New Orleans. ``It doesn't take a brain 
scientist to figure out that these are a bunch of right-wing 
conservatives trying to get a liberal Democrat out of the White 
House by any means necessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mikel Holt, editor of the Milwaukee Community Journal, a black  
newspaper, agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Clinton is removed from office, that's a slap in the face  
for black America,'' said Holt. ``That's in essence, derailing the 
civil rights freedom train.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has long enjoyed black support, both from the public and  
in Congress, because he socializes and prays with black people, 
appoints them to high positions and understands the struggle of 
racism, blacks said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some even summoned King's name and message in Clinton's defense  
-- saying the two men shared a common dream of equality. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dr. King would be suspect of the impeachment process because  
he would be suspect of the impeachers,'' the Rev. Jesse Jackson 
said after a breakfast honoring King in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson specifically mentioned Senate Majority leader Trent  
Lott, who was recently linked by his uncle to an ultraconservative 
group accused of promoting white supremacy. Lott denied last week 
that he was affiliated with the group and said he is opposed to 
racism and white supremacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Bailey, a historian and author from Montgomery, Ala.,  
said he too was suspect of some of Clinton's critics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think (blacks) are most uncomfortable with the way matters  
are being handled and with the key players,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A few blacks said the trial is an outrage -- no matter what color  
you are. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's about the same for everybody,'' said Millard Johnson, 58,  
a maintenance man at a downtown Cleveland. ``Congress just doesn't 
have any business fooling with the man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others said Clinton is getting exactly what he deserves, and  
that race is irrelevant. 
</P>
<P>
	``It appears the president lied and the Senate will do what it  
has to do,'' said Alex Mitchell, 20, a student in Lincoln, Neb. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
