<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 13:36:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two IOC Officials Deny Wrongdoing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Two of the IOC's most prominent members, including  
a contender for the top job, are among 13 of the agency's delegates 
under investigation in the Salt Lake City bribery case. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korea's Kim Un-Yong, a powerful member of the IOC  
executive board, and Russia's Vitaly Smirnov, a former vice 
president, denied any wrongdoing Monday. They said they were 
prepared to defend themselves when the IOC inquiry convenes in 
Lausanne, Switzerland, on Saturday. The six-member panel will make 
recommendations to the full executive board Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC is investigating allegations that members or their  
relatives received cash, scholarships, medical care, lavish gifts 
and other inducements from Salt Lake bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch said last week that nine  
members were accused of ``serious'' misconduct and could face 
expulsion. Four others, he said, were cited for lesser violations 
and could escape with a warning or no punishment at all. 
</P>
<P>
	Members found guilty of corruption will be suspended pending an  
expulsion vote by the full IOC assembly in March. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference in Lausanne, IOC director general Francois  
Carrard said most of the 13 members had replied to letters from IOC 
investigators. The deadline is Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The 67-year-old Kim is by far the biggest name on the list, a  
member of the IOC's inner circle and considered a candidate to 
succeed Samaranch. 
</P>
<P>
	SportIntern, a German-based newsletter specializing in Olympic  
news, said Kim was one of the four members implicated for a minor 
violation and has ``nothing to fear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kim said the allegations were an attempt to defame him.  
</P>
<P>
	``I did not do anything that I should be ashamed of,'' he said  
in Seoul. ``I don't even feel it necessary to comment on it, 
because I have absolutely nothing to do with the scandal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kim said he was asked for explanations for help he gave Smirnov  
in getting a 19-year-old Russian woman enrolled in a U.S. 
university. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was simply an effort to help a friend,'' Kim said.  
``Considering a difficult situation in Russia in 1991 after the 
former Soviet Union collapsed, I introduced the student to former 
Salt Lake Olympics chief Tom Welch. I did not receive any money or 
gift in return.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Details of the arrangement, including the name of the  
university, were not revealed. Welch, who resigned from the 
Olympics job after pleading no contest to spouse-abuse charges, has 
said Salt Lake bidders ran scholarship programs for 
``humanitarian'' reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander Ratner, a spokesman for Smirnov, said two cases cited  
by IOC investigators involved a trip Smirnov made to Salt Lake in 
late 1990 or early 1991, when Salt Lake was bidding for the 1998 
Winter Games eventually awarded to Nagano, Japan. In 1995, Salt 
Lake was awarded the 2002 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Ratner said Smirnov asked officials in Salt Lake to help with  
medical treatment for ice hockey star Alexander Ragulin. The Soviet 
Union, on the verge of collapse, had neither the funds nor medical 
facilities to help Ragulin, who faced possible amputation of both 
legs, Ratner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ratner said the medical bill was paid by the Salt Lake bid  
committee. He wouldn't say how much it cost. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nearly eight years after, (Ragulin) is fine, walking on his  
own legs and even stepping on ice occasionally,'' Ratner said. 
``Vitaly Smirnov feels proud he could help a prominent athlete, 
three-time Olympic champion. He considers that as a display of 
Olympic solidarity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the second case, Smirnov received a Browning hunting rifle.  
He said he couldn't accept it, but hosts packed the rifle in his 
luggage without his knowledge, Ratner said. 
</P>
<P>
	During a stopover in Atlanta on his way home, Smirnov was asked  
about the gun by customs and was completely bewildered, Ratner 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smirnov left the weapon behind, but two years later the gun was  
delivered to Moscow by Salt Lake City organizers. Smirnov turned it 
over to a sports facility in Krasnodar, Russia, the spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Smirnov is fully backing the IOC investigation, open to  
any questions and deeply convinced that the IOC will make a correct 
decision,'' Ratner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim, an IOC member since 1986, has been on the executive board  
since 1988, was a vice president from 1992 until 1996, and is 
chairman of the radio and television commission. 
</P>
<P>
	A key figure in the 1988 Seoul Olympics, Kim is president of the  
South Korean Olympic Committee, the World Taekwondo Federation and 
the General Assembly of International Sports Federations. 
</P>
<P>
	Smirnov, an IOC member since 1971, was one of the most  
influential figures in the Olympic movement in the 1980s and early 
'90s and a close adviser of Samaranch. 
</P>
<P>
	Smirnov was a first vice president of the organizing committee  
for the 1980 Moscow Olympics, vice president of the Soviet Olympic 
Committee from 1969-1991 and is president of the Russian Olympic 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Smirnov was a member of the IOC executive board from 1974-82 and  
1986-90 and a vice president from 1978-82 and 1991-95. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
