<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Part of Expos Stadium Collapses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- A part of the Olympic Stadium's problem-plagued  
roof caved in Monday as some 200 workers were setting up for an 
auto show. 
</P>
<P>
	An avalanche of snow tumbled down and five people were injured.  
</P>
<P>
	``If I had been at my booth, I would be dead.'' said 28-year-old  
Todd Joel, who was working inside at the stadium at the time. ``It 
was bloody scary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joel, who is from Toronto and works for a company that sets up  
display booths for Subaru, said the ``the roof has been raining on 
us'' for days. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the latest chapter in the difficult history of the  
stadium, built for the 1976 Summer Olympics and home to the 
Montreal Expos baseball team. The Expos insist they must have a new 
baseball-only stadium to survive. 
</P>
<P>
	About 200 people were inside the stadium when one of the 63  
panels on the latest edition of the roof -- made of fiberglass with 
Teflon coating -- gave way. 
</P>
<P>
	The workers were preparing the stadium for an auto show when the  
mid-afternoon collapse occurred, sparked apparently by recent heavy 
snowfall. 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Gilbert, a spokesman for the Montreal fire department,  
said two people were taken to a hospital and three others were 
treated on the scene for slight injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	In previous incidents, chunks of outer wall of the stadium  
crashed to the ground but no one was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	The original roof was built to be retractable but didn't work.  
It had to replaced by synthetic material at a cost of about $37 
million Canadian ($24 million U.S. at current rates). 
</P>
<P>
	An American firm, Birdair, has been installing the new roof,  
which is largely complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers setting up for the auto show said they had been told  
repeatedly by the agency that runs the Olympic Stadium not to 
worry. 
</P>
<P>
	They said the Regie des Installations Olympiques (RIO) told them  
there was a bit of a problem with leaks but everything was fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, water was falling on the Subaru booth. Other booths,  
including the Jaguar and Land Rover displays, also were affected. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we can say we are embarrassed by this,'' said Andre  
Huberdeau, vice president of marketing for the RIO. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be easy to condemn them (Birdair) but we have to wait  
to have their explanation,'' RIO president Andre Tetrault. 
</P>
<P>
	The RIO recently asked Birdair whether it needed to clear the  
roof because of all the heavy snow and rain. Tetrault said the 
company answered no. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
