<DOCNO> APW19990118.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 22:13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schools To Get Civil Rights Lesson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A handbook on civil rights for students and  
teachers and how they can be protected by school policies is slated 
for distribution this month to schools across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	In honor of Martin Luther King Day, the U.S. Department of  
Education on Monday announced the creation of the 60-plus page book 
called ``Protecting Students from Harassment and Hate Crimes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Massachusetts Attorney General's Office of Civil Rights came  
up with the idea after visiting schools across the state. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some schools only had policies because there had already been  
a lawsuit or a crisis,'' said Richard Cole, the office's chief of 
civil rights. ``We want schools to look at this handbook, look at 
the examples and set up policies before problems arise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The book defines potential violations such as name-calling,  
graffiti, harassment, unwanted touching and physical threats, and 
offers ways to address problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``We basically know about all the racial stuff but a lot of kids  
at school don't know what harassment is or what types of touching 
is cool, or when enough is enough,'' said Thomasina Disola, a 
17-year-old senior at John D. O'Bryant High School in Boston. ``I 
think this guidebook will help a lot.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
