<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ranking of NBA Free Agents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When the NBA lockout settlement is finally  
signed, it will unleash a flurry of free-agent signings throughout 
the league. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 200 players are waiting to see where they'll be playing,  
and only a handful have reached tentative agreements on new 
contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Here are some of the top free agents, ranked by position and  
listed with their former team, and the status of their 
negotiations: 
</P>
<P>
 *CENTERS:   	
</P>
<P>
	Rik Smits, Pacers: A lock to remain with Indiana with a healthy  
raise from his 1997-98 salary of $4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Theo Ratliff, 76ers: Also a lock to stay with his old team, with  
Philadelphia outbidding several suitors infatuated by the 
shot-blocking machine. 
</P>
<P>
	Vlade Divac, Hornets: Scheduled to arrive back in the U.S. on  
Tuesday to decide between offers from the Sacramento Kings, the Los 
Angeles Clippers and other teams. Charlotte has almost no chance of 
retaining him. 
</P>
<P>
	Isaac Austin, L.A. Clippers: Looks like he will end up in  
Orlando after being pursued by several teams, including the Suns 
and Hornets. 
</P>
<P>
	Arvydas Sabonis, Trail Blazers: Made about $1.7 million for  
Portland last season, and should get a decent bump when he re-signs 
with the Blazers. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Geiger, Hornets: Has reached an agreement to join the  
Philadelphia 76ers, getting a six-year, $54 million deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Luc Longley, Bulls: Was expected to sign with Phoenix, but a  
number of sign-and-trade scenarios have developed since then 
involving several teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Dudley, Knicks: One of the few big men still considered to  
be available. New York is in danger of losing him to a team willing 
to overpay for height. 
</P>
<P>
 *POWER FORWARDS:   	
</P>
<P>
	Antonio McDyess, Suns: Has narrowed his choices to staying with  
Phoenix or returning to the Denver Nuggets -- the team he played for 
during the 1995-96 and 1996-97 seasons. Considered signing with 
Houston or Chicago, but decided against both choices. Should make 
up his mind Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Gugliotta, Timberwolves: Word last week was that he'd stay  
in Minnesota, but things changed over the weekend with Denver and 
Phoenix re-entering the picture. 
</P>
<P>
	Jayson Williams, Nets: Will stay in New Jersey under a  
seven-year deal that will be worth in excess of $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis Rodman, Bulls: His agent says the Bulls are looking to  
execute a sign-and-trade deal for the seven-time rebounding 
champion, and plenty of teams could use him despite his checkered 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	Derrick Coleman, 76ers: Has reached an agreement to join  
Charlotte, where he is likely to be the starting center because 
Anthony Mason plays power forward. Will get $40 million for five 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Henderson, Hawks: Expected to re-sign with Atlanta.  
</P>
<P>
	Loy Vaught, Clippers: Leaning toward Detroit, which would pay  
him about $23 million for five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Barkley, Rockets: Expected to stay in Houston and sign  
for the $1.75 million salary cap exception as long as the Rockets 
are able to sign Pippen or Gugliotta. 
</P>
<P>
	Clarence Weatherspoon, Warriors: The subject of numerous  
sign-and-trade rumors, the strongest of which has him going to 
Miami in a Latrell Sprewell deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Christian Laettner, Hawks: Rumored to be bringing his busted  
Achilles tendon and questionable attitude to Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
 *SMALL FORWARDS:   	
</P>
<P>
	Scottie Pippen, Bulls: Will either sign in Houston, taking all  
of the Rockets' $9.5 million in cap room, or be involved in a 
sign-and-trade deal sending him elsewhere. As of Monday, the 
Rockets looked to be the likeliest possibility. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Fox, Lakers: Expected to sign with Atlanta, taking over the  
starting job from Tyrone Corbin. 
</P>
<P>
	Corliss Williamson: A wild card, with no one sure if he'll stay  
in an unstable situation in Sacramento or be involved in a 
sign-and-trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Clifford Robinson, Suns: Asked for too much money from Detroit,  
now might end up staying in Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Smith, 76ers: The former overall No. 1 pick, who turned down  
$80 million last season, will be lucky to get one-fourth of that 
now. 
</P>
<P>
	LaPhonso Ellis, Nuggets: For the longest time was rumored to be  
headed to Cleveland, but that talk has died down. 
</P>
<P>
	Dale Ellis, SuperSonics: Will stay in Seattle.  
</P>
<P>
 *POINT GUARDS:   	
</P>
<P>
	Rod Strickland, Wizards: Best offer figures to come from  
Washington, which can exceed the salary cap to re-sign him for an 
annual salary in excess of $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Damon Stoudamire, Trail Blazers: Wants the $9 million maximum  
from Portland, but the Blazers are a few hundred thousand south of 
that mark. Only leverage is to take much less money from Houston, 
but only if Pippen stays away from the Rockets. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Johnson, Suns: Will not stay in Phoenix, and has been  
rumored headed to several teams, most notably the Los Angeles 
Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Charlie Ward, Knicks: Wants to re-sign with New York for an  
average salary of about $5 million, but is wary of Knicks 
immediately trading him. Orlando and Detroit are interested. 
</P>
<P>
	Travis Best, Pacers: Will re-sign in Indiana.  
</P>
<P>
	Sherman Douglas, Nets: A valuable backup in New Jersey, could  
leave to become a starter elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Murdock, Heat: Drawing interest from the Clippers. The Nets  
also interested if Douglas leaves. 
</P>
<P>
	Derek Harper, Magic: Looking to sign with a true contender, be  
it Houston, the Lakers or the Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
 *SHOOTING GUARDS: 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Jordan, Bulls: Says he is 99.9 percent retired. Another  
comeback, if there will be one, would likely come next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Rex Chapman, Suns: Played for $326,700 last season, likely to  
get a lucrative new deal that will keep him in Phoenix for the next 
five or six seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Dumars, Pistons: A lock to re-sign in Detroit.  
</P>
<P>
	Jim Jackson, Warriors: The subject of numerous sign-and-trade  
scenarios, but first Golden State must figure out where to trade 
Sprewell. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell Curry, Hornets: Was expected to stay in Charlotte, but  
Miami might have entered the picture. 
</P>
<P>
	Brent Barry, Heat: Would like to go to Golden State as part of a  
Sprewell deal. If that falls through, he could be Jordan's 
replacement at shooting guard for the Bulls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
