<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 08:16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Jan. 18, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Lawyers Open Defense Tomorrow  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate impeachment trial resumes tomorrow,  
with White House lawyers ready to rebut what Republicans say was 
hard evidence that President Clinton committed perjury and 
obstruction of justice in the Monica Lewinsky affair. Partisan 
differences are hardening over the calling of witnesses, with GOP 
lawmakers saying it's inevitable there will be some testimony and 
Democrats warning that a battle over witnesses could prolong the 
trial for months. Former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo today said the 
Senate should have no qualms about consulting public opinion polls 
when considering Clinton's fate. Most polls show strong support for 
keeping Clinton in office. 

</P>
<P>
	Heavy Fighting Reported in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serb security forces backed by  
artillery today pounded the hills surrounding an ethnic Albanian 
village where dozens were massacred, ignoring NATO demands for an 
end to the onslaught. Serb and ethnic Albanian sources in Kosovo 
today reported heavy mortar and machine gun fire near the village 
of Racak, where the bodies of 45 ethnic Albanians were found 
Saturday. The renewed fighting raises fears that the fragile 
U.S.-brokered cease-fire in Kosovo was near collapse. Meanwhile, 
Yugoslav border guards refused to allow chief U.N. war crimes 
prosecutor Louise Arbour to enter the country to investigate the 
massacre. 

</P>
<P>
	Eight Die in Tennessee Tornadoes  
</P>
<P>
	JACKSON, Tenn. (AP) -- A fierce storm system packing a string of  
tornadoes raced across western Tennessee, ripping apart homes, 
killing at least eight people and critically injuring 11 others. At 
least 60 homes and businesses in the Jackson area were damaged or 
destroyed. Power outages were reported in many areas as high winds 
whipped through the state, snapping tree limbs and power lines. 
Tornadoes were seen or touched down in at least a dozen counties. 

</P>
<P>
	Poll on King Assassination Released  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- A new poll shows that only about one in eight  
Americans believe James Earl Ray was solely responsible for the 
assassination of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. A telephone survey 
by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution found that while 12 percent 
believe Ray alone was to blame for the civil rights leader's death, 
46 percent suspect that Ray was aided by others. Ray pleaded guilty 
in 1969 to killing King, but recanted within days. He maintained 
his innocence until his death last year at age 70 while serving a 
99-year sentence. 

</P>
<P>
	Ulcer Sidelines Russian President  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Doctors today said they will treat President Boris  
Yeltsin's bleeding ulcer with medicine instead of performing 
surgery, a news report said. A spokesman said Yeltsin is in stable 
condition. Yeltsin underwent quintuple heart bypass surgery in 
1996. Since then, he has suffered several serious respiratory 
ailments, including two bouts of pneumonia, the latest in late 
November and early December. Most doctors believe the treatment 
will last two or three weeks, Interfax said. But Yeltsin won't have 
to turn over his presidential powers. 

</P>
<P>
	Brazil Will Allow Currency To Trade  
</P>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil today announced it would continue  
to allow its currency to trade openly on foreign exchange markets 
on a long-term basis, a move seen as a step toward overcoming its 
financial crisis. The country's central bank says it will allow the 
foreign exchange market to define the real's value. However, the 
bank says it may intervene occasionally to prevent what it calls 
disorderly movements in the exchange rate. The Brazilian currency 
fell sharply Friday, on word that Brazil wouldn't use its cash 
reserves to prop up the real. 

</P>
<P>
	Gibson, Sawyer Return to Morning TV  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Charles Gibson and Diane Sawyer returned to  
morning TV today in an attempt to boost the sagging ratings for 
ABC's ``Good Morning, America.'' Gibson left ``GMA'' only last 
year, but was asked to return after replacements Kevin Newman and 
Lisa McRee failed to click with early morning viewers. Sawyer was a 
co-host on CBS' morning show in the early 1980s. ``GMA'' has fallen 
into third place among the top networks' morning shows, behind 
NBC's ``Today'' and CBS' ``This Morning.'' 

</P>
<P>
	More Criticism Over Olympic Scandal  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Community activists are demanding that  
state officials and Olympic organizers take further responsibility 
for the bribery scandal surrounding the 2002 Winter Games. One 
group has called for the resignations of Salt Lake Organizing 
Committee trustees who stand to make money from the games. Two IOC 
members -- South Korea's Kim Un-yong and Russia's Vitaly Smirnov -- 
are under investigation in the Salt Lake scandal but deny any 
wrongdoing. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
</TEXT>
