<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Calls for Euro Cash Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European finance ministers have agreed  
to consider a Belgian proposal to move up the launch date for 
banknotes and coins in Europe's new currency, the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials ordered a study into the feasibly of a proposal  
from Belgium's Jean-Jacques Viseur for introduction of euro-cash 
``a few months earlier'' than the current planned date of Jan. 1, 
2002. 
</P>
<P>
	``An introduction from Oct. 1, 2001 shouldn't pose too many  
problems,'' Viseur told the meeting. Belgium's Deputy Prime 
Minister Elio Di Rupo last week said the launch could be brought 
forward by a whole year. 
</P>
<P>
	Belgium has argued that shortening the transition period will  
take advantage of public enthusiasm generated by the euro's launch 
on New Year's Day as a non-cash currency used for banking, business 
and electronic transactions in 11 of the 15 EU nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have trouble understanding that this new money ... does  
not exist in the most normal form, that is notes and coins,'' 
Viseur said. ``It's like a company launching a new product that's 
only available in three years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal received only lukewarm support from other EU  
nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be good, but there are so many technical reasons for  
not doing it,'' French Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn told 
reporters. ``A big majority feels we can't change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't believe there's much point in re-opening discussion  
on dates,'' added Germany's Oskar Lafontaine. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU set out the three-year introduction period to allow time  
for minting and printing coins and notes, to prepare the public for 
the changeover and to give banks and other businesses -- such as 
vending machine operators -- time to adapt. 
</P>
<P>
	Even after the arrival of euro cash, Europe's old currencies  
won't disappear immediately. During a further transition period, 
euros will exist alongside marks, francs, pesetas and the rest for 
up to six months before the final death knell sounds for the 
national currencies on July 1, 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
