<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll on King Assassination Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Only about one in eight Americans believe James  
Earl Ray was solely responsible for the assassination of the Rev. 
Martin Luther King Jr., according to a poll published today. 
</P>
<P>
	A telephone survey by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution found  
that while 12 percent believe Ray alone was to blame for the civil 
rights leader's death, 46 percent suspect that Ray was aided by 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	Roughly one-quarter of the respondents believe that people other  
than Ray were responsible for the 1968 murder. About one-fifth of 
the respondents said they didn't know who was responsible. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray pleaded guilty in 1969 to killing King, but recanted within  
days. He maintained his innocence until his death last year at age 
70 while serving a 99-year sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll of 818 Southern residents and 394 non-Southerners was  
conducted from Sept. 23 to Nov. 15, and has a margin of error of 
plus or minus 5 percentage points. Generally, there was little 
difference in the responses given by Southerners and 
non-Southerners. 
</P>
<P>
	Family members of the slain civil rights leader believe Ray is  
innocent and supported his efforts in recent years to obtain the 
trial that he circumvented with his plea. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very happy that other people share our conclusions that  
there were others involved,'' said Dexter Scott King, son of the 
slain civil rights leader. ``It's encouraging because... there was 
never a full-blown trial to get to the bottom of everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the Kings' instigation, the Justice Department opened a  
limited probe last year to investigate some aspects of the killing. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll found that a majority of respondents -- 55 percent --  
believe no further investigation is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time to stop dredging all this stuff up,'' said poll  
respondent Amy Cecil, 49, a nursing home employee from Lexington, 
N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, 35 percent of poll respondents and 50 percent of black  
respondents said they would like to see more federal investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are too many questions,'' said Beverly Niemzak, 40, a  
homemaker in Gadsden, Ala. ``I don't know that the investigation 
was ever taken far enough. ...There are too many things that just 
shout that it wasn't done the right way. 
</P>
<P>
	Blacks in particular are likely to believe people other than Ray  
were involved. 
</P>
<P>
	In the South, 42 percent of blacks said they believed Ray was  
not involved in the slaying. Outside the South, 46 percent of 
blacks believed Ray was innocent of the crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 14:16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Family Not Keen on 2000 Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush said Monday his wife and twin  
daughters are not keen on seeing him run for president. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who has said he will announce this spring whether he will  
seek the GOP nomination in 2000, admitted that his wife, Laura, is 
not pushing for the family to be put through ``the meat grinder of 
national politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for his daughters, the governor said: ``I haven't met any  
17-year-old child that's anxious to be drug through the national 
spotlight. I would have been the same way at age 17.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Bush said his family will support him whatever he  
decides. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I choose to seek the presidency, they'll be for me. If I  
choose not to seek the presidency, they'll understand why,'' he 
said. ``I think they're going to love me either way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush commented after speaking at a Martin Luther King Jr. Day  
celebration. He will be inaugurated Tuesday for a second four-year 
term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
