<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Again Delays Windows 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Will Windows 2000 make it out in 1999?  
</P>
<P>
	That's the question at least one analyst is raising after  
Microsoft Corp. said it had again pushed back the release of a new 
test version of its Windows 2000 operating system for business 
computers. 
</P>
<P>
	In a posting Monday on its Web site, Microsoft said the third  
``beta'' or test version of Windows 2000 is now expected out ``in 
the April 1999 timeframe'' with the final version expected to ship 
in late 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, the product's in great shape and we just want to  
take the extra few days to put the last final touches on it,'' said 
Ed Muth, Microsoft's group manager for enterprise marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	Windows 2000 is Microsoft's most important new product. The  
massive and sophisticated network software program, which will be 
marketed in different versions for customers ranging from 
individual users to giant corporations, will be Microsoft's primary 
operating system for business and large-scale computing. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft officials characterized the latest delay as minor,  
since the most recent date for Beta 3's release had been March. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analyst Rob Enderle, vice president of Giga Information  
Group in Santa Clara, Calif., suggested, however, that Windows 2000 
might not be ready for sale until June 2000. If so, he said, that 
could hurt Microsoft's financial performance next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The two big products they have coming out over the next year  
are Windows 2000 and Office 2000'' -- the latter an upgrade to 
Microsoft's business software suite, Enderle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many corporate clients might wait to adopt Windows 2000 until  
after it has a track record and the inevitable fixes are issued for 
problems found in use. And many companies likewise won't make the 
switch to Office 2000, due out later this year, until they are 
running the new operating system, Enderle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Software delays are hardly rare at Microsoft. Its flagship  
product, Windows 95 and its successor, Windows 98, both were 
repeatedly postponed as testers found things needing to be fixed. 
</P>
<P>
	Windows 2000, originally known as Windows NT Version 5.0, once  
was expected in 1998. The first test version of the software was 
released in August 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The second beta was due out last June, but wasn't released until  
September. Microsoft originally had planned only a ``Beta 2 
refresh'' rather than a full-scale third beta, but changed its mind 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Muth said the latest delay ``isn't really a question of  
problems'' in the software. Rather, ``it's a question of fit and 
finish work'' to make sure the beta is ready. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our standards for the beta are very, very high,'' he said.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
