<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Overturns Disney Judgement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- A federal judge has overturned a $20  
million jury award won by Children's Broadcasting Corp. against 
Walt Disney Co., saying there was not sufficient evidence that it 
damaged the smaller broadcaster. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Disney and its ABC Radio Networks division terminated a  
year-old agreement to help CBC find new advertisers and affiliates 
for its Children's AAHS World Radio network, then announced plans 
to launch a rival children's radio service, Radio Disney. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury found last September that Disney and ABC failed to live  
up to the contract and used what they learned from CBC to launch 
the rival network. CBC ceased distributing AAHS World Radio in 
January 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	But U.S. District Judge Donald Alsop ruled that the facts  
presented in the case did not support the verdict, noting that 
Minneapolis-based CBC was in financial trouble before Disney and 
ABC even entered the contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``CBC failed to distinguish between the effects of ABC Radio and  
Disney's wrongdoing and other factors that may have affected CBC's 
business,'' Alsop wrote in Friday's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``CBC presented no testimony as to what revenue CBC lost as a  
result of ABC Radio's failure to use reasonable efforts to sell CBC 
advertising or the misappropriation of (trade secrets),'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Children's AAHS World Radio broadcast music, news, stories and  
games aimed at children and their parents. It was carried on a 
network of 32 stations nationally before CBC ended distribution, 
just two months after Radio Disney went on the air. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
