<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Will Allow Currency To Float </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil announced today that it will  
continue to allow its currency to trade freely on foreign exchange 
markets, an important step toward overcoming its financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's currency, the real, has plunged 21 percent since last  
week, when the government said it would no longer spend foreign 
exchange reserves to prop up the overvalued currency. The real was 
trading lower at 1.55 to the dollar today. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Sao Paulo Stock Exchange, share prices rose steeply this  
morning -- up by 8 percent on top of a stunning 33 percent gain 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials fear that if Brazil succumbs to an Asian-style  
currency crisis, its economy -- Latin America's largest -- could drag 
down other countries in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Plunging currencies and a loss of investor confidence could  
cause a regional economic contraction, which in turn would affect 
U.S. exports and likely hurt the U.S. economy, which has some 2,000 
American multinationals doing business in Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting today, Brazil's central bank will let financial  
institutions determine the currency exchange rate by buying and 
selling the real according to their own needs, bank official 
Demosthenes Madurerira de Pinho said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Central Bank may intervene in the market occasionally and  
in a limited form with the objective of preventing disorderly 
movements in the exchange rate,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement followed the market's positive response to  
action taken by the government on Friday, when Brazil announced it 
would temporarily abandon its effort to defend the real's value by 
not dipping into its hard currency reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the real plunged as low as 1.60 to the dollar before  
strengthening slightly to 1.43 at the close of trading. That was 
down from 1.32 at the close of trading Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The real's decline began when the Central Bank tried a  
devaluation of 8 percent on Wednesday, extending the band in which 
the currency could trade to between 1.20 reals and 1.32 reals to 
the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	President Fernando Henrique Cardoso spoke today on the condition  
of Brazil's economy during the inauguration of a new Audi plant by 
Germany's Volkswagen in the southern state of Parana. 
</P>
<P>
	With the exchange-policy shift, Cardoso said, ``Brazil is paving  
the way to free itself up,'' in a reference to the country's huge 
dependence on foreign capital in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardoso also vowed to control the inflation that many have  
predicted will result from the devaluation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a lot of experience as a finance minister, when  
inflation was 1,000 percent per year,'' Cardoso said, referring to 
his stint as finance minister under former President Itamar Franco. 
Franco is now governor of Minas Gerais state. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven opposition governors, meanwhile, are to meet today in  
Minas Gerais to discuss renegotiating their debts with the federal 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Franco this month declared a moratorium on his state's  
debts of $10.5 billion, triggering the latest round of financial 
turmoil. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Minister Pedro Malan and new Central Bank chief  
Francisco Lopes met in Washington on Sunday with U.S. officials and 
the International Monetary Fund, which in November put together a 
$41.5 billion aid package for Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	The global financial crisis hit Brazil full force in August,  
when investors withdrew their money for fear that the government 
couldn't cover a $65 billion budget deficit and might default on 
its loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
