<DOCNO> APW19990118.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 05:29:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmaker Calls for Big Tax Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The American people should be given tax cuts  
to spend the bulk of a projected federal revenue surplus of up to 
$700 billion over the next decade, says the chairman of the Senate 
Budget Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a surplus over and above what is needed for Social  
Security,'' Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., said Sunday on CBS' ``Face 
the Nation.'' ``We're going to give most of that back to the 
American people, as much as $600 billion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The tax cut will start small and then reach full fruition in a  
few years,'' he said, adding it could start at 4 percent and go up 
to 15 percent, affecting people in all tax brackets. 
</P>
<P>
	Domenici reiterated priorities he favors for Congress to protect  
Social Security, give back the non-Social Security surplus to the 
people with a ``significant tax cut,'' increase military spending 
and direct education aid to local schools. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials said it might be premature to promise how  
the surplus will be used. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president will talk about the budget in detail during the  
State of the Union speech, reiterating our pledge to save Social 
Security first,'' said White House spokesman P.J. Crowley. ``Beyond 
that, we have to start to realize the actual surplus before we 
start spending the money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Domenici said his budget panel would have to recruit help from  
other panels such as the Senate Finance Committee and House budget 
writers. 
</P>
<P>
	Domenici said he believes the plan will have support, adding:  
``We'll have something more precise in a week to 10 days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House and Senate Republicans have been meeting to reach a  
unified front and avoid the standoff that killed their budget plans 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Domenici met this month with Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, chairman  
of the House Budget Committee, to come up with an agreement on 
priorities he mentioned Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The unofficial estimate of a $700 billion surplus came from  
Domenici's committee and is based on expectations of official 
numbers to be released late this month by the Congressional Budget 
Office, The Washington Post reported Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
