<DOCNO> APW19990118.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 06:12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ramadan Ends for Muslims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Muslims in most Middle  
Eastern countries began the feast marking the end of the holy 
fasting month of Ramadan today with morning prayers and visits to 
the graves of relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	The somber start of the Eid al-Fitr, Arabic for ``the feast of  
breaking the fast,'' traditionally is followed by a round of family 
visits, big meals and lots of sweets. 
</P>
<P>
	In Cairo, thousands thronged to the city's mosques as the  
prayers of clerics echoed from loudspeakers across the city. Later, 
families decked out in their new clothes headed to the Nile for 
boat trips and picnics. 
</P>
<P>
	The Eid is a three-day holiday in most countries, although Iran  
feasts for just a single day. 
</P>
<P>
	Muslims in Saudi Arabia and most other Persian Gulf countries  
fasted for a last day from dawn to dusk Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	During Ramadan, Muslims are forbidden to eat, drink, smoke or  
have sexual intercourse between sunrise and sunset. Ramadan marks 
God's revelation of the Koran, Islam's holy book, to the Prophet 
Mohammed. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramadan comes to a close if the crescent moon is seen on the  
29th day of the fasting month. If the moon is not sighted, the 30th 
day is considered the last day of fasting. No crescent moon was 
spotted over Saudi Arabia or the Emirates on Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Iraq's state media announced that Iraq also would begin the Eid  
al-Fitr today, as did clerics in the Palestinian territories, 
Lebanon, Jordan and Egypt. 
</P>
<P>
	Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip went on pre-holiday  
shopping sprees Sunday, visiting sweet shops, gift boutiques and 
grocery stores. 
</P>
<P>
	As a holiday gesture, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat released  
dozens of prisoners who were held without charges in Palestinian 
jails. 
</P>
<P>
	In Egypt, the Arab world's most populous country, the government  
has promised to free 1,600 prisoners to mark the Eid. 
</P>
<P>
	Oman, which began Ramadan a day later than the rest of the Gulf,  
decided the feast would start Tuesday as the crescent moon was not 
spotted Sunday, the official Oman News Agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	In Qatar, a tiny emirate in the southern Gulf, candidates  
running for the country's first municipal elections planned to use 
the Eid celebrations to campaign, setting up tents and hiring 
traditional dancers to attract voters. 
</P>
<P>
	Newspapers in the Emirates announced that hospitals would be  
ready around the clock to receive patients injured in accidents or 
suffering from overeating and indigestion during the feast. 
</P>
<P>
	In Malaysia, meanwhile, police said that 70 were killed on the  
country's roads in the last six days as Muslims raced to their 
hometowns to celebrate the end of Ramadan. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said 19 people were killed in road accidents on Sunday  
alone and that motorcyclists constituted the majority of the dead. 
</P>
<P>
	The end of Ramadan is celebrated in Malaysia as Hari Raya on  
Tuesday and Wednesday. Many stretch the holiday into a long 
weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 06:12:19 </DATE_TIME>
