<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 03:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Prices Climb Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Stock prices in Asia climbed higher today, making  
sharp gains after Wall Street rebounded last week and fears of a 
financial meltdown in Brazil receded. 
</P>
<P>
	Markets in Tokyo, Hong Kong, Seoul, Singapore and Manila surged  
within minutes of opening today, though much of the early gains in 
some markets evaporated as the session continued. 
</P>
<P>
	``As worries over Brazil's financial crisis eased in the  
overseas markets, the Tokyo market continues to rebound,'' said 
Sachio Ishikawa, general manager of the stock division at Chuo 
Securities Co. in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average opened strong  
but lost much of its steam, finishing up just 66.20 points, or 0.48 
percent, at 13,805.06. On Thursday, the average gained 335.26 
points, or 2.50 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index rose sharply, gaining 255.14  
points, or 2.5 percent, to close at 10,402.54. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea Composite Stock Price Index in Seoul also leapt  
higher, closing at 622.52 points, up by 1.27 percent from the 
previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	Markets gained a hefty 4.4 percent in Manila, where the  
30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index ended 89.35 points 
higher at 2130.90 after losing 21.73 points Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore's Straits Times Index rose 47.29 points, or 3.1  
percent, to 1547.10. New Zealand's NZSE-40 capital index finished 
the day up 2.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	One weak spot was China, where the two stock markets opened  
largely unchanged today. Traders said prices could fall because of 
growing numbers of Chinese companies warning of low profits. 
</P>
<P>
	The main Shanghai index, which tracks shares reserved for  
Chinese investors, opened up 0.03 points at 26.77. The Shenzhen 
index of similar stocks was down 0.08 points at 50.22. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in Taiwan ended lower on profit-taking following two  
sessions of government-led stock fund purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	In all the gains in Asia, market watchers credited the recovery  
last week in U.S. and other world stock exchanges following moves 
by the Brazilian government to stabilize its economy, Latin 
America's largest. 
</P>
<P>
	The moves in Brazil not only eased fears about its own economy,  
but also quelled worries that instability in Latin America could 
spread to the United States, which is enjoying its strongest 
economic expansion in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 2.4 percent to  
9,340.55 points when it became apparent Brazil's government 
wouldn't step in to protect its faltering currency, the real. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil caused a panic in world financial markets Wednesday when  
it devalued its currency by 8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But the country's decision not to intervene to support the real  
generated confidence that the government was taking appropriate 
measures to nurse the economy back to health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
