<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- The U.S. military is helping Nicaragua  
locate land mines washed out of the ground by Hurricane Mitch, a 
Nicaraguan military officer said in a report published Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Searchers are trying to determine where overflowing rivers might  
have carried the mines, Sergio Ugarte, chief of Nicaragua's mine 
clearing brigades, told the newsweekly Confidencial. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1980s, Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista administration  
planted land mines to defend itself from attack by the U.S.-backed 
Contra fighters. The Contras, based in neighboring Honduras, also 
planted mines. 
</P>
<P>
	By the end of the war in 1990, it was estimated that 116,000  
mines lay in Nicaragua and the border regions of Honduras and Costa 
Rica. Ugarte said about 74,000 have yet to be destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	In late October, Hurricane Mitch dumped intense rains over  
Central America, causing mudslides that dislodged land mines. Some 
have turned up in farming fields, others are believed buried under 
trash, mud and vegetation. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1993, several nations have been helping Nicaragua locate  
and dismantle the land mines. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- A journalist for a Chilean daily was  
arrested Monday after she refused a judge's orders to disclose her 
sources in a report on a drug trafficking case. 
</P>
<P>
	Police detectives escorted Paula Afani from the downtown offices  
of the paper, La Tercera, amid loud applause and cheer from her 
colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chilean Journalists Association and the newspaper condemned  
the arrest warrant issued by judge Pedro Landeta, who is 
investigating a drug trafficking case. 
</P>
<P>
	Landeta will question the journalist before deciding whether to  
formally charge her with obstruction of justice, a crime that 
carries a maximum sentence of three years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislation granting journalists the right to keep their sources  
secret has been stalled in Chile's congress for more than four 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- About 45,000 public hospital nurses,  
x-ray technicians and cleaners held a one-day strike Monday, 
demanding payment of about $27 million in overdue bonuses and 
insurance policies. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors in the country's 1,500 public hospitals were providing  
treatment only to emergency cases, said union leader Francisco 
Mendoza. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials acknowledge they owe the workers the  
benefits, but say they lack the funds to pay them immediately. 
Prices for Venezuelan oil, the country's main export, have hit a 
12-year low, and the government faces a deficit that could reach $9 
billion this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Venezuela's public hospitals already are badly underfunded, with  
many lacking x-ray machines, medicines and other basic supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- At least 5 million children under age 14 are  
working in Mexico, and about half of those have dropped out of 
school, according to a Mexico City legislative commission study. 
</P>
<P>
	About 70 percent of the child laborers work between five and 14  
hours a day, the daily La Jornada reported Monday citing the study 
by the Legislative Assembly's Employment and Social Welfare 
Protection Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	About 21.5 million of Mexico's 91 million people are between  
ages 5 and 14, according to the government's national statistics 
institute. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
</TEXT>
