<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bid To Take Over Mirror Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Mirror Group PLC confirmed Monday that it had been  
approached by Regional Independent Media Group PLC about a possible 
takeover offer. A merger would create Britain's biggest print media 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirror Group, whose flagship is the tabloid Daily Mirror, said  
the offer would value the company at more than 900 million pounds, 
or $1.49 billion. The group also has regional and Scottish 
newspaper interests. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirror Group's shares rose more than 18 percent after Monday's  
announcement. 
</P>
<P>
	Regional Independent Media, which publishes the Yorkshire Post  
and other newspapers, is owned by the finance group Candover 
Investments PLC. It is chaired by former Conservative Cabinet 
minister Sir Norman Fowler. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirror is advising shareholders to take no action at this stage.  
A formal offer would be subject to recommendation by the Mirror 
Group board and approval by antitrust regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	The move followed the breakdown of talks between Mirror Group  
and Trinity, a regional newspaper group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 19:05:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Again Delays Windows 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft has again pushed back the release of a  
new test version of its Windows 2000 operating system for business 
computers, raising doubts about whether the final version of the 
long-overdue product might ship this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In a posting Monday on its Web site, Microsoft Corp. said the  
third ``beta'' or test version of Windows 2000 is now expected out 
``in the April 1999 timeframe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The low-key announcement came the day before Microsoft was to  
release its second-quarter earnings. Many analysts expect Microsoft 
to do well in the quarter that ended Dec. 31, since computer-chip 
maker Intel Corp. has already reported strong financial results 
from the holiday season. 
</P>
<P>
	Windows 2000 is Microsoft's most important new product. The  
massive and sophisticated network software program, which will be 
marketed in different versions for customers ranging from 
individual users to giant corporations, will be Microsoft's primary 
operating system for business and large-scale computing. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, its technology also will be applied to the Windows  
software that now runs most personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	To eliminate bugs, Microsoft is running an extensive software  
testing program. The testing began 16 months ago and involves about 
250,000 users. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft officials characterized the latest delay as minor,  
since the most recent date for Beta 3's release had been March. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, the product's in great shape and we just want to  
take the extra few days to put the last final touches on it,'' said 
Ed Muth, Microsoft's group manager for enterprise marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	Muth said Microsoft still expects to ship a final version of  
Windows 2000 in late 1999. But others aren't so sure. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analyst Rob Enderle, vice president of Giga Information  
Group in Santa Clara, Calif., suggested Windows 2000 might not be 
ready for sale until June 2000. If so, he said, that could hurt 
Microsoft's financial performance next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The two big products they have coming out over the next year  
are Windows 2000 and Office 2000'' -- the latter an upgrade to 
Microsoft's business software suite, Enderle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many corporate clients might wait to adopt Windows 2000 until  
after it has a track record and the inevitable fixes are issued for 
problems found in use. And many companies likewise won't make the 
switch to Office 2000, due out later this year, until they are 
running the new operating system, Enderle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Software delays are hardly rare at Microsoft. Its flagship  
product, Windows 95 and its successor, Windows 98, both were 
repeatedly postponed as testers found things needing to be fixed. 
</P>
<P>
	Windows 2000, originally known as Windows NT Version 5.0, once  
was expected in 1998. The first test version of the software was 
released in August 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The second beta was due out last June, but wasn't released until  
September. Microsoft originally had planned only a ``Beta 2 
refresh'' rather than a full-scale third beta, but changed its mind 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Muth said the latest delay ``isn't really a question of  
problems'' in the software. Rather, ``it's a question of fit and 
finish work'' to make sure the beta is ready. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our standards for the beta are very, very high,'' he said.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 17:35:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Scottie Pippen To Play for Rockets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Scottie Pippen will be traded from the Chicago  
Bulls to the Houston Rockets as soon as the lockout ends later this 
week, three NBA sources told The Associated Press on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulls will sign Pippen to a deal worth $67.2 million for  
five years before trading him, and get forward Roy Rogers and a 
second-round draft pick in return, said the sources, who spoke on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the salaries for Pippen and Rogers do not match, the  
deal is allowable under NBA rules because Houston will have enough 
salary cap room to fit in Pippen's contract. His salary for this 
season will be $10.6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal will not be finalized until the lockout ends Wednesday  
or Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to confirm anything,'' Rockets spokesman Tim  
Frank said. ``The lockout is technically not over. We're still 
under lockout restrictions. No deal can officially be done until 
that cloak is lifted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen, a six-time champion with the Bulls, talked to the  
Rockets about signing with them as a free agent. It was not 
immediately clear why he agreed to a sign-and-trade deal, but other 
teams were also discussing similar deals involving Pippen with 
Bulls general manager Jerry Krause. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition of Pippen should clear the way for Charles  
Barkley to re-sign with Houston, giving the Rockets a formidable 
front line of Barkley, Pippen and Hakeem Olajuwon. 
</P>
<P>
	The 33-year-old Pippen has been with Chicago since the 1987-88  
season when he was drafted out of Central Arkansas. Last year, he 
averaged 19.1 points and 5.2 rebounds per game. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-time All-star forward is considered one of the top  
three free agents up for grabs as NBA teams prepare to open 
training camps delayed by the 6 1/2-month lockout. 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen should be in uniform for the Rockets when they play an  
exhibition game against San Antonio on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rockets also were interested in the other top two free  
agents, Antonio McDyess and Tom Gugliotta. 
</P>
<P>
	But McDyess has ruled out Houston as a possibility, and  
Gugliotta appears likely to sign with Minnesota or Denver. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 20:16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Found in Plane Wreckage in Ark. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOBIA, Okla. (AP) -- Searchers found the wreckage of a small  
plane Monday with the bodies of a man and his three young sons who 
crashed in an Oklahoma forest while flying home to Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	``The plane disintegrated as it went into the ground,'' said Lt.  
Derral Punneo of the Oklahoma Highway Patrol. ``There's not any 
recognizable pieces.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Airborne state police from Arkansas spotted the plane in the  
Kiamichi Mountains, directing ground searchers to the site of the 
aircraft missing since Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would appear that the wreckage was scattered through a  
heavily wooded area, very rugged terrain,'' said Bill Sadler, a 
state police spokesman in Little Rock, Ark. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims were identified as Dr. Bruce Brown Jr., 36, of  
Springdale, Ark., and sons Hayden, Joshua and Weston, who ranged in 
age from 8 to 3. 
</P>
<P>
	The single-engine Cessna 182 took off Saturday night from  
Dallas' Love Field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0216 </DOCNO>
