<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> KO Punch Turned Around Tyson Bout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Mike Tyson winced in pain as his cut man tried  
to stop the bleeding around his right eye. The look on the face of 
trainer Tommy Brooks was one of growing concern as he implored 
Tyson between rounds to try and get something together. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson's wild punches were hitting nothing but air and Francois  
Botha was making him pay for it with well placed counters. Worse 
yet, Botha was talking trash, taunting the fighter whose mere 
presence in the ring once terrorized his opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	This was no way for the baddest man on the planet to start a  
comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't worry,'' Tyson told Brooks. ``I've got him in my sights.  
Give me time. I'll get him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The time came with 10 seconds left in the fifth round. It came  
in the form of a perfectly thrown right hand that crashed with a 
startling suddenness into Botha's face. 
</P>
<P>
	And it may have come just in time to save a career that seemed  
to be disintegrating once again in the same ring where his biting 
of Evander Holyfield got Tyson banned from boxing 19 months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``You knew it was going to come. You just didn't know when,''  
Tyson said. ``I knew I would knock him out. It was just a matter of 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The right hand that sent Botha sprawling on the canvas Saturday  
night may arguably have been the best single punch ever thrown by a 
man whose entire career is based on throwing big punches. 
</P>
<P>
	It certainly was the most important.  
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't just a million dollar punch. This punch had a career  
riding on it, a career worth tens of millions more. 
</P>
<P>
	Without it, Tyson was heading toward a third straight loss.  
Without it, he was heading away from the multimillion-dollar 
paydays so common for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just feels great to do what I love to do,'' Tyson said.  
``But I've got to improve. I've got a long way to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just how far Tyson has to go in his latest comeback from an  
enforced absence was painfully evident through nearly five full 
rounds against a tough and surprisingly effective Botha. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson missed often with lunging punches that whizzed past  
Botha's head, and it was Botha who was doing most of the damage 
with left-right combinations to Tyson's head. 
</P>
<P>
	Botha had won all four rounds on two of the judge's scorecards  
and three of the four on a third. He was growing increasingly 
confident as the fight neared its scheduled midway point, taunting 
Tyson at times with his gloves dropped to his side and exchanging 
words with him during repeated clinches. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt I was in control of the fight,'' Botha said.  
</P>
<P>
	He was, but not for long.  
</P>
<P>
	As Botha threw a lazy right hand to the body late in the fifth  
round, Tyson threw a counter right hand with such perfect balance 
that when it smashed into Botha's face there was no doubt the fight 
was over. 
</P>
<P>
	Botha tried gamely to get up, but when he finally did at the  
count of seven, he went reeling backwards into the ropes as referee 
Richard Steele waved the fight to a close. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got cocky and I paid for it,'' Botha said. ``It was a punch  
I didn't see. Mike's a great hitter and I just walked into the 
punch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sudden ending of the fight thrilled the crowd of 12,519, who  
for a few brief seconds at the end of the first round may have 
thought they were going to see yet another Tyson fight end in 
bizarre fashion. 
</P>
<P>
	The two fighters were in a clinch as the bell sounded to end the  
round and their arms were linked while they tried to punch with 
their remaining free arm. Steele couldn't separate them, and nearly 
a dozen officials and cornermen rushed into the ring to finally pry 
them apart. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was trying to break my arm,'' Botha said.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's correct,'' Tyson replied.  
</P>
<P>
	The start of the second round was delayed for about 45 seconds  
as Steele conferred in the ring with Nevada Athletic Commission 
executive director Marc Ratner warned both fighters to be on their 
best behavior. A few minutes later, he was penalizing Tyson for 
excessive holding. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told (Steele) to take a deep breath and take command,''  
Ratner said. ``He did a good job under trying circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Tyson, the evening's work was worth at least $10 million and  
it gave him a chance to shake some of the ring rust collected from 
an enforced layoff of 19 months for biting Holyfield's ears. 
</P>
<P>
	It may not have been pretty, but the one right hand salvaged the  
lucrative contracts Tyson has to fight as many as four times this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``In two weeks or so I'll get back into the gym and start  
working to capitalize on everything I screwed up tonight,'' Tyson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Botha, who turned out to be a credible opponent, asked for a  
rematch but Tyson will now go on to other fighters, with the hope 
that he could fight Holyfield for a third time in November. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson's next fight is tentatively set for April 24, possible  
against Germany's Axel Schulz, who was at ringside. Other boxers in 
the mix include Lou Savarese and Shannon Briggs. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson said he really doesn't care who is put in the ring with  
him. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the price is right I'll fight a lion,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
