<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reeves Faces Old Team in Super Bowl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- If he's the vindictive type, Dan Reeves might  
look at this as a chance to get even with John Elway, Mike Shanahan 
and the Denver Broncos. 
</P>
<P>
	Just five weeks removed from heart bypass surgery, Reeves heads  
to the Super Bowl for the fourth time as a head coach, his Atlanta 
Falcons having stunned Minnesota 30-27 in overtime for the NFC 
championship Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, though, Reeves will be on the opposite sideline from  
the team he took to three NFL title games, the team that dominated 
his life for a dozen years, the team that fired him in 1992 after a 
falling-out with Shanahan and Elway. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollywood couldn't have scripted a more dramatic showdown.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to worry about ourselves,'' said Reeves, refusing --  
in the public's eye, at least -- to turn the Jan. 31 game into a 
personal vendetta. ``Whoever we play, we have to go out and play as 
well as we're capable of playing. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got an awful good football team, they're the defending  
world champions and they're going to be defending world champions 
until somebody knocks them off. ... We've got our work cut out for 
us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After his ouster in Denver, Reeves coached the New York Giants  
for four seasons, but he was fired again without ever playing his 
old team. Then it was off to Atlanta, where he finally got a shot 
at the Broncos for the first time since his days in Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves was coaching a winless team at the time, while the  
Broncos were on the way to the Super Bowl championship that eluded 
them during the Reeves' era. Denver won 29-21, and all parties 
insisted that it was time to let bygones be bygones. 
</P>
<P>
	But those stormy moments are sure to be rekindled during the two  
weeks leading up to the Super Bowl in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Everyone will recall how Elway craved to get out from under the  
dictatorial Reeves and his run-oriented offense, a period the 
quarterback later described as ``hell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They'll remember how Shanahan was fired as quarterback coach in  
1991 for insubordination, supposedly for going behind Reeves' back 
to draw up plays with Elway. Reeves lasted only one more season, 
let go in part because of a falling-out with Elway. 
</P>
<P>
	``At times, we were best friends,'' Shanahan said of his  
relationship with Reeves. ``He's done a great job with that 
football team, and we look forward to playing them in Miami. It's 
going to be a great game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, the Falcons were 3-13. Now, they're en route to  
the Super Bowl for the first time in their 33-year history, with 
most of the credit placed squarely on Reeves' shoulders. 
</P>
<P>
	He's brought professionalism to a franchise that was an NFL  
laughingstock. He brought a sense of order to a team that was known 
for its disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got them playing great and Dan is a great football  
coach,'' Elway said after the Broncos defeated the New York Jets 
23-10 in the AFC title game. ``When you look at what he's done in 
the last two years with them, it's just unbelievable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves' current quarterback, Chris Chandler, has no complaints  
about his coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had read a lot about what had happened in Denver with  
John,'' said Chandler, acquired from the Oilers in a trade shortly 
after Reeves was hired by the Falcons. ``I didn't have any 
preconceived thoughts going into it. I know John and I know Dan, 
and they're both great guys. Whatever happened then, happened 
then.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After bouncing from team to team -- five in all -- during the  
first nine years of his career, Chandler will be appearing in the 
Pro Bowl for the second year in a row under Reeves' tutelage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had nothing but fun playing for Dan,'' Chandler said.  
``It's been the best experience of my playing football, by far. 
It's been fun, it's been rewarding, it's been challenging. I'm glad 
I got the chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves was glad to get a second chance at life after feeling a  
burning sensation in his chest and throat during a Dec. 13 game in 
New Orleans. The following day, he underwent four hours of 
quadruple bypass surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	The coach missed the final two games of the regular season but  
returned for the playoffs, insisting his heart was fine. It must 
be. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I can stand today, my heart's got to be in great shape,''  
he said. ``It can't get much tougher than that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Well, maybe it can. Earlier in the season, when the Super Bowl  
still seemed like a faraway, unreachable goal, Reeves vowed to 
perform the Falcons' arm-flapping ``Dirty Bird'' dance in the 
middle of Main Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he has a way out on a technicality -- Atlanta doesn't have  
a Main Street -- he's apparently going to be true to his word. 
</P>
<P>
	``That ain't going to be a pretty sight,'' Reeves said with a  
laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	On a more serious note, he pondered the staggering turnaround  
that has occurred in Atlanta since his arrival. After losing seven 
of their first eight games under Reeves, the Falcons have won 22 of 
26. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's incredible when you think about it,'' he said. ``Coming  
from 1-7 halfway through you first year to be in the Super Bowl in 
the second year. I can't say enough about our players. It's an 
unbelievable group of guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And their coach isn't too bad, either.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
