<DOCNO> APW19990118.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 15:54:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vikes Lose and Billick Eyes Ravens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OWINGS MILLS, Md. (AP) -- The Minnesota Vikings' loss could turn  
out to be the Baltimore Ravens' gain. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings' 30-27 overtime loss to Atlanta in Sunday's NFL  
Championship game cleared the way for Minnesota offensive 
coordinator Brian Billick to interview for the Ravens' head 
coaching vacancy. Billick planned to arrive in Baltimore on Monday 
night and meet with Ravens owner Art Modell on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This thing could happen at any time,'' Billick said before  
leaving Minnesota. ``... I think they have all the information they 
need. I certainly have all the information I need about the 
organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Billick, 44, has been the Vikings' offensive coordinator for the  
past five years. Under his direction, the Vikings scored an 
NFL-record 556 points this regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ravens were not allowed to meet with Billick until the  
Vikings were eliminated from playoff contention. Had Minnesota won 
Sunday, as expected, then Baltimore would have been forced to wait 
until February to speak with Billick. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore received an additional dose of good news Monday when  
the expansion Cleveland Browns dropped Billick from consideration 
as their new head coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Just one day earlier, in the wake of the Vikings' upset loss,  
Billick said he intended to give Baltimore and Cleveland equal 
consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	``The opportunity to be a head coach is something that I've  
worked for my entire life,'' Billick said Sunday. ``If that should 
be presented to me, it will be time to move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings this season established a team-record 6,264 yards on  
offense. Under Billick, Minnesota has recorded the top three 
yardage totals in team history. 
</P>
<P>
	That's attractive to the Ravens, who went 6-10 this season  
despite holding the opposition below 17 points in half their games. 
Minnesota beat Baltimore 38-28 this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Baltimore has some intriguing aspects,'' Billick said. ``I'm  
very impressed with Mr. Modell -- both Modells, Art and David -- in 
terms of their concept of where that organization is going. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Vice president of player personnel) Ozzie Newsome is one of  
the best personal people in the business. They've got talent, and I 
was excited by the city of Baltimore, the energy that was there 
when we (played) there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Billick and Jacksonville Jaguars offensive coordinator Chris  
Palmer are considered favorites to fill the void left by the Dec. 
28 firing of head coach Ted Marchibroda. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer interviewed for the job last week, but the Ravens made it  
clear that they wanted to speak with Billick before making any kind 
of job offer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ravens have also interviewed Pittsburgh Steelers defensive  
coordinator Jim Haslett. Emmitt Thomas, who recently followed Ray 
Rhodes from Philadelphia to Green Bay as the defensive coordinator, 
also had been considered a candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore originally wanted either George Seifert or Mike  
Holmgren, both of whom have already established themselves as 
outstanding NFL head coaches. But Seifert signed with Carolina and 
Holmgren canceled a planned trip to Baltimore after accepting a job 
with the Seattle Seahawks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
