<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Power Outage Stalls Amtrak Trains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- An electrical outage knocked out power  
Monday to Amtrak rail lines between New York and Delaware, putting 
the brakes on 20 rush hour trains. 
</P>
<P>
	The outage happened shortly before 5:30 p.m. as a line of  
thunderstorms made its way through the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Trains for Amtrak, Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation  
Authority and New Jersey Transit were stopped in their tracks as 
far south as Wilmington, Del. Power was restored an hour later 
between Wilmington and Philadelphia, and to the rest of the system 
shortly after 7 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem was traced to an insulator that blew out at a North  
Philadelphia power station that controls the flow of electricity 
used by Amtrak, Amtrak spokesman Rick Remington said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It occurred roughly about the time the storm went through New  
Jersey,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The storms' wind speeds were up to 60 mph in some areas.  
</P>
<P>
	The trains had only emergency lighting when the outage first  
happened, but enough power was restored soon after to provide heat 
and full lighting, Remington said. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no word on how many passengers were affected.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
