<DOCNO> APW19990118.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 14:47:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some See Opportunity in Falcons Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The closer Game Day got, the stronger grew  
Rudolph Terry's belief that the Atlanta Falcons would win the NFC 
title. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why, the night before Sunday's game against the Minnesota  
Vikings, he canceled his flight to Minneapolis and shipped his own 
tickets to an associate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hated to give up my seats, but I said, `We got to go to  
work,''' Terry recounted Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	He cheered the Falcons on his home television, allowed himself a  
few minutes to savor their overtime victory, then headed to his 
Terry Manufacturing apparel business to begin rolling out 
conference championship shirts. 
</P>
<P>
	Eager fans descended on stores Monday in search of such  
paraphernalia, as the sudden rise of the Falcons to their first 
Super Bowl gave some Atlanta-area businesses double reason to 
celebrate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've followed the Falcons for almost 35 years. It just feels  
good,'' said Terry, who with his 70 workers printed up to 20,000 
shirts for shipment to retailers within 12 hours of Morten 
Andersen's game-winning field goal. ``There's a general level of 
both Falcon pride and Atlanta pride, and I'm sure that adrenaline 
allowed people to work 18 or 20 hours without sleep.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They were still cranking out their NFL-licensed shirts Monday to  
meet initial orders. But Terry, like operators of other 
sports-related businesses, was in uncharted territory when trying 
to guess what total demand will be. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are hoping this is going to be a big bonus,'' said Diana  
Harris, president of Glorious Events catering. 
</P>
<P>
	She said her business, which usually caters many  
business-related Super Bowl parties, could jump by a third for this 
year's game, adding another $50,000 in revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's all totally speculative,'' added the 27-year veteran of  
the catering business. ``I'm a native Atlantan and we've never done 
a Falcons Super Bowl before. So it's going to be interesting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Choice, manager at a Buffalo's Cafe suburban Marietta, said  
he was starting work on a game plan for the Jan. 31 Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his restaurant sold $400 worth of takeout chicken wings  
even before it opened its doors Sunday and another seven 40-pound 
cases of wings to customers who dined in and watched the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Ticket brokers and travel agents started getting calls  
immediately after the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Kaplan, owner of Tickets Plus Travel in Atlanta, said Super  
Bowl tickets were starting at $1,650 each, with a variety of hotel 
and transportation packages also available for additional charge. 
Travel agents were offering air charter deals with tickets for up 
to $4,000 per person. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an NFL formula, each participating team will receive about  
11,000 tickets, to be distributed to staff and club associates and 
then split among season-ticket holders via a lottery. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Holman, a season-ticket holder for 20 years, said Monday  
he'd already been notified he could buy two Super Bowl tickets from 
the Falcons at $325 each. The Powder Springs businessman was 
scrambling to make hotel reservations and to decide whether to fly 
or drive to the game-- it's about a 12-hour trip by car. 
</P>
<P>
	Regardless, he wouldn't miss it.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've endured this for so many years. All of them who were  
always saying `you're a fool' for buying those tickets every year 
are the ones who've been calling me now saying, `Hey, you got any 
playoff tickets?''' Holman said. ``It's been a lot of fun. Our day 
has come!'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the Braves Clubhouse store in the CNN Center, manager Don  
Shields said ``tons of people'' had called or come by looking for 
Falcons Super Bowl shirts and caps. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be hot -- probably as big as when the Braves won  
their first championship,'' Shields said. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick Tolbert, 18, of Douglasville, had already been waiting  
more than an hour at the store for the caps, which were due to 
arrive Monday afternoon. But he showed no impatience. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been waiting a long time for this,'' he said. ``I've  
been waiting all my life. Who would think the Falcons are going to 
be in the Super Bowl?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 15:26:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> With Loss, Parcells Talks Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- As much as Bill Parcells talked about  
being physically tired and emotionally drained the day after the 
New York Jets lost the AFC Championship game to Denver, his words 
focused elsewhere -- next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Make no mistake, Parcells and his players on Monday sounded very  
much like a team intent on ending the Jets' Super Bowl drought at 
31 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told the players that I won't rest,'' Parcells told a packed  
news conference less than 24 hours after a 23-10 loss to the 
Broncos on Sunday left them a victory shy of football's biggest 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told them that last year my whole idea is to try to improve  
the team each year. We'll see what we can do to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The immediate agenda was already on the table for Parcells, who  
confirmed Monday that he will return as coach next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The 57-year-old man who is now the only coach to lead three  
teams to conference title games already had a full schedule on 
Tuesday. There was a season-ending meeting planned for his coaching 
staff, administrative conferences to discuss the salary cap and 
free agency and a player-expansion list due. 
</P>
<P>
	Meetings had already been held with some players on Monday, the  
coaching staff had been re-signed and permission had been given to 
Chicago and Kansas City to talk to assistant head coach Bill 
Belichick about head coaching vacancies with the Bears and Chiefs. 
There also were seven free-agent signings, mostly practice squad 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	All this from a guy who claimed he was very tired, and who tried  
to reiterate that during his news conference by discussing his 
thoughts at the 2-minute warning Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always think the same thing,'' Parcells said. ``It's another  
offseason. It's another draft. It's another training camp. It's 
another preseason. It's another regular season and it's another 
semifinal game just to get where you are standing. I can remember 
this feeling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells said he felt the same way in 1985 when the Giants lost  
to NFC semifinal to Chicago 21-0. 
</P>
<P>
	The Giants came back the following year and won the Super Bowl.  
</P>
<P>
	When reminded of that, Parcells said there is no similarity to  
the teams, even though he admitted the Jets, who were met at 
LaGuardia Airport by owner Leon Hess, had a lot more chances to do 
things on Sunday against Denver than the Giants had against the 
Bears. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the Jets led 10-0 and probably were one big play away  
from putting the Broncos away in the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	It never came though, and New York was eventually done in by six  
turnovers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll tell you this, you don't forget,'' said backup  
quarterback and special teams star Ray Lucas. ``I'm not going to 
forget. It's going to be fresh in my mind. It's two years in a row 
we were almost, almost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When asked what Parcells told the team on Monday, Lucas smiled  
confidently. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said: `We'll be back,' so you know it,'' Lucas said.  
``We're all right. We'll be ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was a sentiment echoed by many players after a 12-4 regular  
season and a 1-1 record in the postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want a small victory and say: `Woo, we got to the AFC  
championship,''' receiver Keyshawn Johnson said. ``I don't want to 
smile and be happy about that. That's not the case. Everyone in 
this locker room is not happy about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterback Vinny Testaverde was one of many Jets who had a  
tough night sleeping, knowing the game was there for the taking. 
</P>
<P>
	``To lose it the way we did, it's hard to accept,'' he said.  
``If you get blown out, it's easier to accept. Then they were the 
better team and you lost. The good thing is we know we can play 
with the best of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets did on Sunday, but for only 30-plus minutes.  
</P>
<P>
	``We know that we have accomplished a lot, just thinking about  
it,'' cornerback Ray Mickens said. ``But knowing we could have been 
at the big dance, you really want another shot at that opportunity, 
and we have to wait a whole year for that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That year has already started for Parcells.  
</P>
<P>
	``For us to go through the division next year like we did this  
would be an accomplishment to do that,'' he said. ``But I don't 
think it's impossible.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 04:43:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Denies Part in IOC Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A powerful South Korean member of the  
IOC executive board today denied any wrongdoing in connection with 
the Salt Lake City bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim Un-Yong confirmed he received a letter demanding  
explanations from IOC officials investigating allegations of 
misconduct by IOC members during Salt Lake's bid for the Winter 
Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim, one of 13 International Olympic Committee members linked to  
the scandal, is part of the IOC's powerful inner circle and 
considered a possible candidate to succeed Juan Antonio Samaranch 
as president. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did not do anything that I should be ashamed of,'' he told  
reporters. ``I don't even feel it necessary to comment on it, 
because I have absolutely nothing to do with the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I already clarified my case and this will be cleared up in the  
IOC's executive board meeting on Jan 24.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC is investigating reports of cash payments, extravagant  
gifts and other favors to some of its members in exchange for votes 
leading to the selection of Salt Lake City as the site of the 2002 
Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Sport Intern, a German-based newsletter specializing in Olympic  
news, said Kim was implicated for a ``minor offense'' and is not 
expected to face expulsion or other punishment from the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch told The Associated Press last week that 13 IOC  
members had been implicated in the Salt Lake investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	He said nine had been accused of ``serious'' misconduct which  
could result in expulsions, while four others were cited for minor 
violations. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim said he was asked by the IOC to clarify his 1991 assistance  
in helping a Russian teen-age student enroll in a U.S. school at 
the request of Russian IOC member Vitaly Smirnov. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was simply an effort to help a friend,'' Kim said.  
``Considering a difficult situation in Russia in 1991 after the 
former Soviet Union collapsed, I introduced the student to former 
Salt Lake Olympics chief Tom Welch. I did not receive any money or 
gift in return.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other details of the arrangement were not revealed.  
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Salt Lake was bidding for the 1998 Winter Games,  
which were awarded in 1991 to Nagano, Japan. In 1995, Salt Lake won 
the right to stage the 2002 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Smirnov confirmed today that he also had received notification  
from the IOC that he was under investigation. He said he was asked 
for explanations regarding his request for free medical treatment 
of a Russian hockey player and for receiving a hunting rifle as a 
gift during a trip to Salt Lake. He also denied any wrongdoing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 09:56:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bure Gets Trade Wish, Goes to Fla. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUNRISE, Fla. (AP) -- For all of Pavel Bure's magic on the ice,  
it might be difficult matching the hocus-pocus performed by the 
Florida Panthers in acquiring the high-scoring, high-priced Russian 
holdout. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only did the Panthers obtain one of the most electrifying  
players in hockey, they did so while managing to leave their 
nucleus virtually intact. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're fortunate. Pavel was not going to go to Vancouver,''  
Panthers general manager Bryan Murray said after the deal was 
announced on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	To pry Bure from the Canucks, Florida parted with top defenseman  
Ed Jovanovski, centers Dave Gagner and Mike Brown and holdout 
goaltender Kevin Weekes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Panthers also received defensemen Bret Hedican and Brad  
Ference, and will swap a first-round draft pick in 1999 or 2000 for 
Vancouver's third-rounder. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gives us a shot in the arm,'' Murray said. ``There's not  
one person on our staff that doesn't think (Bure is) a superstar -- 
one of the top five or so players in this league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bure, who has spent the entire season at his home in Moscow  
after telling the Canucks he would never play for them again, is 
expected to join the Panthers in New York for games Wednesday 
against the Islanders and Thursday against the Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was really happy when my agent called me and said I was  
going to the Florida Panthers,'' Bure said Monday during a 
teleconference. ``I know it's a young team. I hope we can do 
something good for the franchise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Canucks president Brian Burke had set a deadline of Monday to  
make a deal or pull the three-time 50-goal scorer off the market 
until the March 23 trade deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, Burke decided Florida's offer met his needs -- a  
tough young defenseman, a No. 2 center and other top young talent 
to help build for the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't have made it if I wasn't comfortable with it,''  
Burke said. ``We're ecstatic. Whether the public sees it that way, 
my guess is probably not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if the wait was worth it, Bure said: ``Oh, yeah. It was an  
important thing in my life. You put a goal in front of yourself and 
you always try to reach that goal. Sometimes you have to make 
sacrifices.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bure, 27, is a four-time all-star who gives Florida its most  
explosive scorer in the franchise's six-year history. No Panther 
has scored more than 32 goals in a season, by Scott Mellanby in 
1995-96 and Ray Whitney last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing like shooting the puck on goal,'' said  
Panthers coach Terry Murray, who plans initially to pair Bure with 
fellow Russian Viktor Kozlov. ``He has the opportunity to be a 
threat every time he's on the ice. I hope he'll also have an effect 
on some of our other players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bure won the 1992 Calder Trophy as the NHL's top rookie, scoring  
34 goals in 60 games. He followed that with consecutive 60-goal 
seasons, leading the Canucks to the 1994 Stanley Cup finals with 16 
postseason goals in 24 games. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian star scored 51 goals last season, one off the league  
lead, but demanded a trade over the summer. Bure would not disclose 
why he had grown disenchanted with the Canucks, but disputed 
Burke's contention that he had wearied of a fish-bowl environment 
in Vancouver. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's so funny. I never said that,'' Bure said. ``People were  
really nice to me there. I have a lot of friends there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bure is in the last season of a five-year deal worth a reported  
$8 million. Talks on an extension have already begun, Murray said, 
and should be completed before the end of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Jovanovski, 22, has been playing some of the best hockey of his  
four-year NHL career. The No. 1 pick of the 1994 draft has three 
goals and 13 assists this season to go with his hard-nosed 
checking. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's punishing and yet he has offensive skill and a hard shot.  
We think he upgrades our defense,'' Burke said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gagner, 34, has four goals and 10 assists this season. Squeezed  
out by the Panthers' young talent, he will move in as Vancouver's 
No. 2 center behind Mark Messier. 
</P>
<P>
	Weekes, once Florida's goalie of the future, fell out of favor  
when he refused a two-way contract that would have paid him a lower 
salary in the minors. He's been playing for Detroit of the IHL, 
compiling a 14-3-6 record with a 2.09 goals-against average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 13:46:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bure Gets Trade Wish, Goes to Fla. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUNRISE, Fla. (AP) -- For all of Pavel Bure's magic on the ice,  
