<P>
	``I wouldn't have made it if I wasn't comfortable with it,''  
Burke said. ``We're ecstatic. Whether the public sees it that way, 
my guess is probably not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if the wait was worth it, Bure said: ``Oh, yeah. It was an  
important thing in my life. You put a goal in front of yourself and 
you always try to reach that goal. Sometimes you have to make 
sacrifices.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bure, 27, is a four-time all-star who gives Florida its most  
explosive scorer in the franchise's six-year history. No Panther 
has scored more than 32 goals in a season, by Scott Mellanby in 
1995-96 and Ray Whitney last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing like shooting the puck on goal,'' said  
Panthers coach Terry Murray, who plans initially to pair Bure with 
fellow Russian Viktor Kozlov. ``He has the opportunity to be a 
threat every time he's on the ice. I hope he'll also have an effect 
on some of our other players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bure won the 1992 Calder Trophy as the NHL's top rookie, scoring  
34 goals in 60 games. He followed that with consecutive 60-goal 
seasons, leading the Canucks to the 1994 Stanley Cup finals with 16 
postseason goals in 24 games. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian star scored 51 goals last season, one off the league  
lead, but demanded a trade over the summer. Bure would not disclose 
why he had grown disenchanted with the Canucks, but disputed 
Burke's contention that he had wearied of a fish-bowl environment 
in Vancouver. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's so funny. I never said that,'' Bure said. ``People were  
really nice to me there. I have a lot of friends there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bure is in the last season of a five-year deal worth a reported  
$8 million. Talks on an extension have already begun, Murray said, 
and should be completed before the end of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Jovanovski, 22, has been playing some of the best hockey of his  
four-year NHL career. The No. 1 pick of the 1994 draft has three 
goals and 13 assists this season to go with his hard-nosed 
checking. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's punishing and yet he has offensive skill and a hard shot.  
We think he upgrades our defense,'' Burke said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gagner, 34, has four goals and 10 assists this season. Squeezed  
out by the Panthers' young talent, he will move in as Vancouver's 
No. 2 center behind Mark Messier. 
</P>
<P>
	Weekes, once Florida's goalie of the future, fell out of favor  
when he refused a two-way contract that would have paid him a lower 
salary in the minors. He's been playing for Detroit of the IHL, 
compiling a 14-3-6 record with a 2.09 goals-against average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 13:46:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bure Gets Trade Wish, Goes to Fla. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUNRISE, Fla. (AP) -- For all of Pavel Bure's magic on the ice,  
it might be difficult matching the hocus-pocus performed by the 
Florida Panthers in acquiring the high-scoring, high-priced Russian 
holdout. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only did the Panthers obtain one of the most electrifying  
players in hockey, they did so while managing to leave their 
nucleus virtually intact. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're fortunate. Pavel was not going to go to Vancouver,''  
Panthers general manager Bryan Murray said after the deal was 
announced on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	To pry Bure from the Canucks, Florida parted with top defenseman  
Ed Jovanovski, centers Dave Gagner and Mike Brown and holdout 
goaltender Kevin Weekes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Panthers also received defensemen Bret Hedican and Brad  
Ference, and will swap a first-round draft pick in 1999 or 2000 for 
Vancouver's third-rounder. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gives us a shot in the arm,'' Murray said. ``There's not  
one person on our staff that doesn't think (Bure is) a superstar -- 
one of the top five or so players in this league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bure, who has spent the entire season at his home in Moscow  
after telling the Canucks he would never play for them again, is 
expected to join the Panthers in New York for games Wednesday 
against the Islanders and Thursday against the Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was really happy when my agent called me and said I was  
going to the Florida Panthers,'' Bure said Monday during a 
teleconference. ``I know it's a young team. I hope we can do 
something good for the franchise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Canucks president Brian Burke had set a deadline of Monday to  
make a deal or pull the three-time 50-goal scorer off the market 
until the March 23 trade deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, Burke decided Florida's offer met his needs -- a  
tough young defenseman, a No. 2 center and other top young talent 
to help build for the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't have made it if I wasn't comfortable with it,''  
Burke said. ``We're ecstatic. Whether the public sees it that way, 
my guess is probably not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if the wait was worth it, Bure said: ``Oh, yeah. It was an  
important thing in my life. You put a goal in front of yourself and 
you always try to reach that goal. Sometimes you have to make 
sacrifices.'' 
</P>
