<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Chief Wants Labor Market Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Europe must reform rigid labor  
policies and avoid budget deficits if it wants to boost growth and 
cut chronically high unemployment, European Central Bank President 
Wim Duisenberg said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jan. 1 launch of the euro, Europe's single currency, has  
helped create the conditions needed to foster flagging growth, 
Duisenberg said in a speech delivered to the European Parliament's 
monetary affairs committee. 
</P>
<P>
	But to really dent Europe's high unemployment, currently at 10.8  
percent for the 11 euro participating countries, structural reform 
of labor and product markets is needed, Duisenberg said in a copy 
of the speech released early. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro is expected to cut the cost of doing business in Europe  
and will create a more unified, transparent market. 
</P>
<P>
	Duisenberg's call for governments to reform labor markets was  
more strongly expressed than usual, in an apparent attempt counter 
pressure from some center-left European finance ministers for lower 
interest rates as a way to boost the economy and cut unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	Duisenberg opposes that, and has said the bank's key rate of 3  
percent will stay for now. 
</P>
<P>
	Growth in Europe is expected to flag to 2.4 percent in the third  
quarter of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
