<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boy Suggests Punishment for Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- William Preston Summers is getting a lot of  
attention for lying, but the 8-year-old wants another William -- 
President Clinton -- to know that telling lies is wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	During an appearance today on ABC's ``Good Morning America,''  
William said he doesn't think Clinton should be removed from 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still like him because of all his education -- the schools  
and stuff,'' he said. ``I don't think he should be impeached. Just 
have to write, like, an essay. Like I did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago boy wrote a letter to Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., as  
punishment for a fib to his parents. Hyde, who chairs the House 
Judiciary Committee, read it on the Senate floor Saturday to sum up 
the case for removing the president from office. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is bad to lie because it just gets you in more trouble. I  
hate getting in trouble,'' William wrote in the letter. He later 
added: ``If you cannot believe the president, who can you believe? 
If you have no one to believe in, then how do you run your life?'' 
</P>
<P>
	William today cautioned the president: ``If he lied ever again,  
he should be impeached.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So what was the lie that prompted the boy's letter to Hyde?  
</P>
<P>
	William had twisted the arm of another boy after swim practice  
but later told his mother two boys had been ganging up on him. The 
lie was revealed when William's brother, Christopher, leaked the 
true story. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the tattletale of the family,'' William said.  
</P>
<P>
	William's father Bobby Summers, 31, a graduate student in  
political science, suggested the letter when father and son were 
watching news of the impeachment proceedings in December. 
</P>
<P>
	It seems to have worked.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's the cure,'' William said. ``I haven't lied since.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
