<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Jan. 18, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	NATO Generals To Warn Milosevic  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two top NATO officials plan to warn Yugoslav  
President Slobodan Milosevic that NATO is prepared to act 
militarily unless he abides by commitments to Kosovo Albanians that 
he agreed to three months ago, a senior official said today. 
Meanwhile, Serb forces pounded villages in Kosovo with artillery. 
The government also barred the U.N. war crimes prosecutor from 
entering the province and ordered the chief U.S. peace verifier to 
leave. The defiant moves came after last week's massacre of 45 
ethnic Albanian civilians 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Defense Hones Strategy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- White House lawyers today honed the defense  
presentation for President Clinton's impeachment trial that they 
will begin tomorrow. It will focus on conflicts in testimony, a 
strategy that aims at undercutting House charges of perjury and 
obstruction of justice but that also could open the way to 
Republican demands for witnesses to help resolve the disputes. The 
White House has been fighting that demand, but now expects 
witnesses, officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Honors King, Volunteers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After knocking down a wall with AmeriCorps  
volunteers, President Clinton used today's holiday honoring Martin 
Luther King Jr. to announce a $6.5 billion fair housing settlement 
reached by enforcing a law passed days after King's death. The 
president cited King's philosophy as he joined Vice President Al 
Gore and the team volunteers in tearing down a wall to make way for 
a health clinic at a retirement home. Clinton announced that the 
Department of Housing and Urban Development and Columbia National 
Mortgage Co. had settled a housing discrimination case worth $6.5 
billion in loans and homeownership programs. 

</P>
<P>
	King Remembered at Church Services  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- From the pulpit where Martin Luther King Jr. once  
preached, South African Archbishop Desmond Tutu today gave thanks 
to King and all American civil rights leaders he credited with 
paving the way for the end of apartheid in his country. People 
across the country celebrated Martin Luther King Day with speeches, 
sermons and volunteerism. Last Friday would have been King's 70th 
birthday. He died April 4, 1968, from an assassin's bullet. 

</P>
<P>
	N.Ireland Government Blueprint OK'd  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- A strong majority of Protestant  
and Catholic politicians in Northern Ireland's new legislature 
voted tonight to support a blueprint for a compromise government. 
The decision endorsed the document by Protestant politician David 
Trimble and Catholic politician Seamus Mallon, would-be leaders of 
the unformed government. It details 10 new government departments 
for Northern Ireland -- with majority Protestants and minority 
Catholics equally sharing top posts. 

</P>
<P>
	Tenn. Residents View Tornado Damage  
</P>
<P>
	JACKSON, Tenn. (AP) -- Residents of a housing subdivision  
hard-hit by a deadly tornado got their first daylight look today at 
the damage. Eight people were killed statewide by twisters and at 
least 100 were hurt. The fast-moving storm system that swept across 
western and central Tennessee packed high winds, hail and heavy 
rain. Tornadoes were seen or touched down in 12 counties and damage 
was reported in 28 counties. 

</P>
<P>
	Europe, Asia Markets Gain  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Receding worries about Brazil's economic problems  
touched off a global rally in stock markets today as the country's 
central bank announced it would continue to float Brazil's 
currency. However, other world markets were still volatile. Brazil 
had caused a panic in world financial markets Wednesday when it 
devalued its currency by 8 percent, sparking fears that the country 
could succumb to an Asian-style currency crisis. U.S. financial 
markets were closed Monday for the Martin Luther King Jr. Day 
holiday. 

</P>
<P>
	Super Bowl May Be Bust for Miami  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The Super Bowl may prove to be a super bust for  
South Florida, a new study suggests, contradicting the notion that 
the NFL's premier event generates hundreds of millions of dollars 
for the host city. A look at six Super Bowls dating to 1979 found 
no increase in sales revenue over previous years without the big 
game, said Philip Porter, author of the study. The NFL contends the 
economic benefits will be huge -- as much as $365 million -- when the 
Super Bowl makes its eighth trip to South Florida next week. 

</P>
<P>
	Yankee Clipper Out of Hospital  
</P>
<P>
	HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) -- Baseball great Joe DiMaggio was released  
from the hospital today. He spent 99 days in the intensive care 
unit for treatment of lung cancer and pneumonia. His release marked 
an incredible recovery for the Yankee Clipper, who was near death 
several times and even was administered last rites. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
</P>
