<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schools To Get Civil Rights Lesson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A handbook that seeks to educate students and  
teachers on civil rights and how they can be protected by school 
policies will be distributed this month to schools across the 
country, officials announced Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In honor of Martin Luther King Day, the U.S. Department of  
Education announced the creation of the new 60-plus page book 
called ``Protecting Students from Harassment and Hate Crimes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The book was the brainchild of the Massachusetts Attorney  
General's Office of Civil Rights, which came up with the idea after 
visiting dozens of schools across the state. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some schools only had policies because there had already been  
a lawsuit or a crisis,'' said Richard Cole, chief of civil rights 
office for the Massachusetts Attorney General. ``We want schools to 
look at this handbook, look at the examples and set up policies 
before problems arise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The book defines potential violations such as name-calling,  
graffiti, harassment, unwanted touching and physical threats, and 
offers ways to address the problems. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, if two students get into a racially motivated  
brawl, the first thing that should be done is report the incident 
to school administrators, the handbook suggests. From there, the 
book suggests sitting students down with a team of mediators to get 
to the root of the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most students have never been taught it's possible for things  
to be talked out first without fighting,'' Cole said. 
</P>
<P>
	And many also know little about the civil rights movement, which  
the book also discusses. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomasina Disola, 17, said she hoped her school would pass out  
the guidebook so students can learn about their rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``We basically know about all the racial stuff but a lot of kids  
at school don't know what harassment is or what types of touching 
is cool, or when enough is enough,'' said Disola, a senior at John 
D. O'Bryant High School in Boston. ``I think this guidebook will 
help a lot.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
