<DOCNO> APW19990118.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 17:36:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Part of Expos Stadium Collapses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- A part of the Olympic Stadium's problem-plagued  
roof caved in Monday as some 200 workers were setting up for an 
auto show. 
</P>
<P>
	An avalanche of snow tumbled down and five people were injured.  
</P>
<P>
	``If I had been at my booth, I would be dead.'' said 28-year-old  
Todd Joel, who was working inside at the stadium at the time. ``It 
was bloody scary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joel, who is from Toronto and works for a company that sets up  
display booths for Subaru, said the ``the roof has been raining on 
us'' for days. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the latest chapter in the difficult history of the  
stadium, built for the 1976 Summer Olympics and home to the 
Montreal Expos baseball team. The Expos insist they must have a new 
baseball-only stadium to survive. 
</P>
<P>
	About 200 people were inside the stadium when one of the 63  
panels on the latest edition of the roof -- made of fiberglass with 
Teflon coating -- gave way. 
</P>
<P>
	The workers were preparing the stadium for an auto show when the  
mid-afternoon collapse occurred, sparked apparently by recent heavy 
snowfall. 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Gilbert, a spokesman for the Montreal fire department,  
said two people were taken to a hospital and three others were 
treated on the scene for slight injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	In previous incidents, chunks of outer wall of the stadium  
crashed to the ground but no one was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	The original roof was built to be retractable but didn't work.  
It had to replaced by synthetic material at a cost of about $37 
million Canadian ($24 million U.S. at current rates). 
</P>
<P>
	An American firm, Birdair, has been installing the new roof,  
which is largely complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers setting up for the auto show said they had been told  
repeatedly by the agency that runs the Olympic Stadium not to 
worry. 
</P>
<P>
	They said the Regie des Installations Olympiques (RIO) told them  
there was a bit of a problem with leaks but everything was fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, water was falling on the Subaru booth. Other booths,  
including the Jaguar and Land Rover displays, also were affected. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we can say we are embarrassed by this,'' said Andre  
Huberdeau, vice president of marketing for the RIO. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be easy to condemn them (Birdair) but we have to wait  
to have their explanation,'' RIO president Andre Tetrault. 
</P>
<P>
	The RIO recently asked Birdair whether it needed to clear the  
roof because of all the heavy snow and rain. Tetrault said the 
company answered no. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 15:34:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Floats Anti-Tobaaco Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OTTAWA (AP) -- The government Monday proposed new regulations  
that would more than double the size of health warnings on 
cigarette packs and require the inclusion of additional 
anti-smoking information. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new rules, expected to take effect later this year, 60  
percent of the front and back of a cigarette pack would be devoted 
to warnings, compared to the current requirement of 25 percent on 
the front panel. 
</P>
<P>
	A list of the toxic ingredients in cigarette smoke would be  
printed on each pack, as would a toll-free number for advice on 
quitting smoking. 
</P>
<P>
	Health Minister Allan Rock said several new warnings would be  
among those used on the package, possibly including ``Smoking can 
cause a slow and painful death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His department also is considering a warning that smoking could  
impair male sexual performance. 
</P>
<P>
	Rob Parker, president of the Canadian Tobacco Manufacturers'  
Council, said the industry could do little to influence the content 
of health warnings but might object if the size of the warnings 
limited their ability to portray their trademark on cigarette 
packs. 
</P>
<P>
	Parker also said the new regulations were inspired more by  
politics than practicality. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe there's one chance in 1,000 they will change  
the smoking rate in Canada,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to changing warning-label rules, Rock said the  
government plans to tighten restrictions on cigarette displays in 
stores and to conduct more frequent studies into tobacco use and 
the chemical composition of tobacco products. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada already has a comprehensive ban on cigarette advertising.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990118.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 22:13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PBS Kids Channel To Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- PBS plans to boost spending on  
children's television, with some money devoted to a 24-hour PBS 
Kids Channel. 
</P>
<P>
	The channel scheduled to begin broadcasting in September will  
include such shows as ``Barney &AMP; Friends'' and ``Teletubbies,'' PBS 
President Ervin Duggan told the Television Critics Association on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	By the end of 1999, about a third of the country will be able to  
receive the channel through PBS stations with digital capability, 
Duggan said. 
</P>
<P>
	How many viewers see it will depend on how many invest in costly  
digital TV sets. Duggan acknowledged that the initial audience will 
be small. 
</P>
<P>
	The channel is part of a children's initiative that will include  
new preschool programs, an expansion of the PBS Kids Web site and 
an increase in PBS's free book distribution program, Duggan said. 
</P>
<P>
	PBS expects to spend substantially more on children's  
programming and services next year. The budget for 1999 is $27 
million; the proposed budget for 2000 is $40 million, PBS spokesman 
Tom Epstein said. 
</P>
<P>
	Over three years, the planned investment is about $125 million,  
said Kathy Quattrone, executive vice president of PBS Programming 
Services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
